{"title_page": "Constitution of the Kingdom of Denmark", "text_new": "{{Infobox constitution\n| document_name        = Constitutional Act of the Kingdom of Denmark\n| image                = Grundloven-1849-forside.jpg\n| image_alt            =\n| caption              = Front page of the first constitution from 1849\n| orig_lang_code       = da\n| title_orig           = Danmarks Riges Grundlov\n| jurisdiction         = [[Denmark]], [[Greenland]] and the [[Faroe Islands]]\n| date_ratified        = 25 May 1849 (first)<br />[[1953 Danish constitutional and electoral age referendum|28 May 1953]] (current)\n| date_effective       = [[Constitution Day (Denmark)|5 June]] 1849 (first)<br /> 5 June 1953 (current)\n| system               = [[Constitutional monarchy]]\n| branches             = Three (executive, legislature and judiciary)\n| chambers             = Unicameral ([[Folketing]])\n| executive            = [[Cabinet of Denmark|Cabinet]] responsible to parliament\n| courts               = [[Supreme Court (Denmark)|Supreme Court]] and others\n| location_of_document =\n| writer               = Constitutional Assembly of the Realm\n| signers              = [[Frederick VII of Denmark|Frederick VII]] (first)<br />[[Frederick IX of Denmark|Frederick IX]] (current)\n| media_type           =\n}}\n{{Politics of Denmark}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n\nThe '''Constitutional Act of the Kingdom of Denmark''' ({{lang-da|Danmarks Riges Grundlov}}), or simply '''the Constitution''' ({{lang-da|Grundloven}}), is the [[constitution]] of the [[Denmark|Kingdom of Denmark]], applying equally in Denmark proper, [[Greenland]] and the [[Faroe Islands]]. The first constitution was adopted in 1849, and the current constitution is from 1953. It is one of the oldest constitutions in the world.<ref name=\"danishparliament\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedanishparliament.dk/Democracy/The_Constitutional_Act_of_Denmark.aspx|title=The Constitutional Act of Denmark|website=thedanishparliament.dk|publisher=The Danish Parliament (Folketinget)|accessdate=14 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120170200/http://www.thedanishparliament.dk/Democracy/The_Constitutional_Act_of_Denmark.aspx|archive-date=20 November 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Constitutional Act has been changed a few times. The wording is general enough to still apply today.<ref name=\"danishparliament\" />\n\nThe constitution defines the Kingdom as a [[constitutional monarchy]], governed thought a [[parliamentary system]]. It creates [[Separation of powers|separations of power]] between the [[Folketing]], which enact laws, [[Government of Denmark|the government]], which implements them, and [[Courts of Denmark|the courts]], which makes judgment about them. In addition it gives a number of [[fundamental rights]] to people in the Kingdom, including [[freedom of speech]], [[freedom of religion]], [[freedom of association]], and [[freedom of assembly]]. The constitution applies to all persons in the Kingdom, not only [[Danish nationality law|Danish citizens]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.berlingske.dk/politik/df-mener-at-grundloven-kun-er-til-for-danske-statsborgere-men-en-afdoed|title=DF mener, at Grundloven kun er til for danske statsborgere \u2013 men en afd\u00f8d professor og tre nulevende eksperter er dybt uenige|last=Holm|first=Thue Ahrenkilde|date=21 November 2019|work=Berlingske|access-date=29 October 2019|last2=Rohde|first2=Thomas S\u00f8gaard|language=Danish|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIts adoption in 1849 ended an [[absolute monarchy]] and introduced [[democracy]]. The Kingdom of Denmark celebrates the adoption of the Constitution on 5 June\u2014the date in which the first Constitution was ratified\u2014every year as [[Constitution Day (Denmark)|Constitution Day]].\n\nThe main principle of the Constitutional Act was to limit the King's power (section 2).<ref name=\"Act\">[http://www.servat.unibe.ch/icl/da00000_.html The Constitution of Denmark] Accessed on 14 April 2016.</ref> It creates a comparatively weak constitutional monarch who is dependent on Ministers for advice and Parliament to draft and pass [[legislation]]. The Constitution of 1849 established a [[bicameralism|bicameral]] parliament, the {{lang|da|[[Rigsdag]]}}, consisting of the [[Landsting (Denmark)|Landsting]] and the [[Folketing]]. The most significant change in the Constitution of 1953 was the abolishment of the Landsting, leaving the [[unicameral]] Folketing. It also enshrined fundamental [[civil rights]], which remain in the current constitution: such as ''[[habeas corpus]]'' (section 71), [[private property rights]] (section 72) and [[freedom of speech]] (section 77).<ref name=\"Act\" />\n\nThe [[Folketing|Danish Parliament]] ({{lang|da|Folketinget}}) cannot make any laws which may be repugnant or contrary to the Constitutional Act. While the Kingdom has no [[constitutional court]], laws can be declared unconstitutional and rendered void by the [[Supreme Court (Denmark)|Supreme Court of Denmark]].\n\nChanges to the Act must be confirmed by a majority in two consecutive parliamentary terms and then approval of the electorate through a national [[referendum]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Tschentscher, Axel  |url=http://www.servat.unibe.ch/icl/da00000_.html |title=The Constitution of Denmark \u2013 Section 88 |publisher=Servat.unibe.ch |accessdate=2016-02-12}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|History of Denmark}}\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2016}}\n\n=== Background ===\n[[File:Frederik VII af August Schi\u00f8tt.jpg|upright|thumb|left|Frederick VII, the last king of Denmark to rule as an absolute monarch.]]\nDuring the [[Late Middle Ages|late middle ages]] and the [[renaissance]], the power of the king was tempered by a [[h\u00e5ndf\u00e6stning]], a coronation charter each king had to sign before being accepted as king by the [[nobility]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/haandfaestning/|title=Vis|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-04-13|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref> This tradition was abandoned in 1665 when King [[Frederick III of Denmark]] managed to establish a [[Hereditary monarchy|hereditary]] [[absolute monarchy]] by '''Lex Regia''' (''The Law of The King'', {{lang-da|Kongeloven}}). This was Europe's only formal absolutist constitution.<ref>[http://www.folketinget.dk/BAGGRUND/00000033/00972093.htm Folketinget] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507190923/http://www.folketinget.dk/BAGGRUND/00000033/00972093.htm |date=7 May 2009 }}</ref> Under Lex Regia, absolute power was inherited for almost 200 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/kongeloven-1665/#indhold5|title=Vis|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-04-13|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the beginning of the 19th century, there were a growing democratic movement in Denmark and [[Frederick VI of Denmark|King Frederick VI]] only made some small concessions, such as creation of ''Consultative Estate Assemblies'' ({{Lang-da|R\u00e5dgivende St\u00e6nderforsamlinger}}) in 1834. But these only served to help the political movements, of which the [[National Liberal Party (Denmark)|National Liberals]] and the [[Society of the Friends of Peasants|Friends of Peasants]] were the forerunners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/inddragelse-af-befolkningen-i-den-enevaeldige-administration/|title=Vis|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-04-13|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref> When [[Christian VIII of Denmark|Christian VIII]] became king in 1839, he continued the political line of only making small democratic concessions, while upholding the absolute monarchy.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAt this time Denmark was in a [[personal union]] between kingdom of Denmark and the duchies of [[Duchy of Schleswig|Schleswig]], [[Duchy of Holstein|Holstein]], and [[Saxe-Lauenburg|Lauenburg]] called ''The Unitary State'' (Danish: ''Helstaten''), but the [[Schleswig-Holstein Question|Schleswig-Holstein question]] was causing tension. Under the slogan ''Denmark to the [[Eider (river)|Eider]]'', the National Liberals campaigned for Schleswig to become an integral part of Denmark, while separating Holstein and Lauenburg from Denmark.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/perioder/det-unge-demokrati-1848-1901/kritik-af-enevaelden-og-debat-om-slesvig/|title=Kritik af enev\u00e6lden og debat om Slesvig|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-05-18|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref> Holstein and Lauenburg were then part of the [[German Confederation]], while Schleswig was not. On the other side, German nationalists in Schleswig were keen to keep Schleswig and Holstein together, and wanted Schleswig to join the German Confederation.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/perioder/det-unge-demokrati-1848-1901/marts-1848/|title=Marts 1848|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-05-18|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref> Christian VIII had reached the conclusion that, should the Unitary State survive, a constitution covering both Denmark, Schleswig and Holstein was necessary. Before his death in January 1848, he advised his [[Heir apparent|heir]] [[Frederick VII of Denmark|Frederick VII]] to create such a constitution.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/christian-8-1786-1848/|title=Vis|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-04-13|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1848 following a [[Revolutions of 1848|series of European revolutions]], the Schleswig-Holstein question became increasingly tense. Following an ultimatum from Schleswig and Holstein, political pressure from the National Liberals intensified, and Frederick VII replaced the sitting government with the [[Moltke I Cabinet|March Cabinet]], where four leaders of the Friends of Peasants and the National Liberals served, among those [[Ditlev Gothard Monrad|D.G. Monrad]] and [[Orla Lehmann]], both National Liberals. The ultimatum from Schleswig and Holstein was rejected, and the [[First Schleswig War]] started.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Drafting and signing of the first constitution (1849) ===\n[[File:Grundlovgivende rigsforsamling - Constantin Hansen.jpg|thumb|The National Constitutional Assembly (painting by [[Constantin Hansen]] 1860\u201364) ([[Frederiksborg Castle]], Hiller\u00f8d)]]\n[[File:Grundloven 1849 i 2018.jpg|thumb|The Constitutional Act of 1849 on display in 2018]]\n\nMonrad drafted the first draft of the Constitution, which was then edited by Lehmann. Sources of inspiration included the [[Constitution of Norway]] of 1814 and the [[Constitution of Belgium]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Danmarks_geografi_og_historie/Danmarks_historie/Danmark_1536-1849/Den_Grundlovgivende_Rigsforsamling|title=Den Grundlovgivende Rigsforsamling {{!}} Gyldendal - Den Store Danske|website=denstoredanske.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> The draft was laid before the ''Constitutional Assembly of the Realm'' ({{lang|da|Den Grundlovgivende Rigsforsamling}}). This assembly, which consisted of 114 members directly elected in October 1848, and 38 members appointed by Frederick VII, was overall split in three different groupings: the National Liberals, the Friends of Peasants, and the Conservatives. A key topic for discussion was the political system, and the rules governing elections.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/perioder/det-unge-demokrati-1848-1901/demokratiets-etablering-den-grundlovgivende-forsamling/|title=Demokratiets etablering: Den Grundlovgivende Forsamling|last=103982@au.dk|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 May 1849, the Constitutional Assembly approved the new constitution, and on 5 June 1849 it was signed by Frederick VII. For this reason, it is also known as the ''June constitution''.<ref name=\":4\" /> Today, 5 June is known as [[Constitution Day (Denmark)|Constitution Day]] and is a national holiday in Denmark.\n\nThe new constitution establish the [[Rigsdagen|Rigsdag]], a [[Bicameralism|bicameral]] parliament, with an upper house called the [[Landsting (Denmark)|Landsting]], and a lower house called the [[Folketing]]. While the voting rights for both chambers were the same, the elections to the Landsting was indirect, and the eligibility requirements harder. The constitution gave voting rights to 15% of the Danish population. Due to the First Schleswig war, the constitution was not put into force for Schleswig; instead this question was postponed to after the war.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/danmarks-riges-grundlov-af-5-juni-1849-junigrundloven/|title=Danmarks Riges Grundlov, 5. juni 1849 (Junigrundloven)|last=103982@au.dk|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Parallel constitution for the Unitary State (1855-1866) ===\nFollowing the First Schleswig war, which ended in Danish victory in 1852, the [[London Protocol (1852)|London Protocol]] reaffirmed the territorial integrity of the Unitary State, and solved an impending succession issue, since Frederick VII was childless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/londontraktaten-8-maj-1852/|title=Londontraktaten, 8. maj 1852|last=103982@au.dk|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> Since the June constitution was not put into force in Schleswig, the Schleswig-Holstein question remained unsolved. Work for creating a common constitution for the Unitary State started, and in 1855 the rigsdag accepted ''Helstatsforfatning (Constitution for The Unitary State),'' which covered affairs common to Denmark, Schleswig and Holstein. At the same time, the June constitution was limited to only be applicable in Denmark.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/helstatsforfatningen-1855-faellesforfatningen/|title=Helstatsforfatningen (F\u00e6llesforfatningen), 2. oktober 1855|last=103982@au.dk|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 1863 this constitution was changed, the new one was called ''Novemberforfatningen''. This was shortly before [[Second Schleswig War|Second Schleswig war]], where Denmark lost control of Schleswig and Holstein, rendering the parallel constitution void.\n\n===The Revised Constitution (1866)===\n\n[[File:Danish Constitions in Folketinget 20090520.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The Constitutions of Denmark located inside [[Folketinget]].]]In 1866, the defeat in the [[Second Schleswig War]], and the loss of [[Schleswig-Holstein]] led to tightened election rules for the Upper Chamber, which paralyzed legislative work, leading to provisional laws.\n\nThe conservative [[Conservative People's Party (Denmark)|H\u00f8jre]] had pressed for a new constitution, giving the upper chamber of parliament more power, making it more exclusive and switching power to the conservatives from the original long standing dominance of the [[National Liberal Party (Denmark)|National Liberals]], who lost influence and was later disbanded. This long period of dominance of the H\u00f8jre party under the leadership of [[Jacob Br\u00f8nnum Scavenius Estrup]] with the backing of the king [[Christian IX of Denmark]] was named the ''provisorietid'' (provisional period) because the government was based on provisional laws instead of parliamentary decisions. This also gave rise to a conflict with the Liberals (farm owners) at that time and now known as [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]] (Left). This constitutional battle concluded in 1901 with the so-called systemskifte (change of system) with the liberals as victors. At this point the king and H\u00f8jre finally accepted [[parliamentarism]] as the ruling principle of Danish political life. This principle was not [[Codification (law)|codified]] until the 1953 constitution.\n\n=== Universal suffrage (1915) ===\nIn 1915, the tightening from 1866 was reversed, and women were given the right to vote. Also, a new requirement for changing the constitution was introduced. Not only must the new constitution be passed by two consecutive parliaments, it must also pass a referendum, where 45% of the electorate must vote yes. This meant that Prime Minister [[Thorvald Stauning]]'s attempt to change the Constitution in 1939 failed.<ref>S\u00f8ren M\u00f8rch: ''24 statsministre''. {{ISBN|87-02-00361-9}}.</ref>\n\n=== Reunion with Schleswig (1920) ===\n{{See also|1920 Schleswig plebiscites}}\nIn 1920, a [[1920 Danish constitutional referendum|new referendum]] was held to change the Constitution again, allowing for the reunification of Denmark following the defeat of Germany in [[World War I]]. This followed a [[referendum]] held in the former Danish territories of Schleswig-Holstein regarding how the new border should be placed. This resulted in upper Schleswig becoming Danish, today known as [[Southern Jutland]], and the rest remained German.\n\n=== Current Constitution (1953) ===\nIn 1953, the [[1953 Danish constitutional and electoral age referendum|fourth constitution]] abolished the Upper Chamber (the [[Landsting (Denmark)|Landsting]]), giving Denmark a [[Unicameralism|unicameral]] parliament. It also enabled females to inherit the throne (see ''[[Danish monarchy#Succession|Succession]]''), but the change still favored boys over girls (this was changed by a [[2009 Danish Act of Succession referendum|referendum in 2009]] so the first-born inherits the throne regardless of sex). Finally, the required number of votes in favor of a change of the Constitution was decreased to the current value of 40% of the electorate.\n\nIn 2009, the [[Danish Act of Succession|Act of Succession]], which is referenced in the constitution and considered an integral part of it, was changed to  eliminate [[male-preference primogeniture]] in favour of [[absolute primogeniture]]. The changes was approved in a [[2009 Danish Act of Succession referendum|referendum]].\n\n== Summary of the constitution ==\nThe Danish constitution consists of 89 sections, structured into 11 chapters. The Folketing have published the constitution with explanatory annotations; it is available in both Danish and English through their website.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.ft.dk/~/media/sites/ft/pdf/publikationer/grundloven/min-grundlov_web.ashx|title=Min grundlov \u2013 Grundloven med forklaringer.|last=|first=|publisher=Folketinget|year=2017|isbn=87-7982-172-3|edition=14.|location=|pages=|language=Danish}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.thedanishparliament.dk/~/media/pdf/publikationer/english/my_constitutional_act_with_explanations.ashx|title=My Constitutional Act \u2013 My Constitutional Act with explanations|last=|first=|publisher=Folketinget|year=2014|isbn=978-87-7982-168-2|edition=12.|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" |Chapter\n!Sections\n!Content\n|-\n|1\n|Form of government\n|\u00a7\u00a7 1\u20134\n|Denmark is a [[constitutional monarchy]], with [[separation of powers]] into the three classic branches: the legislative, held by the [[Folketing]]; the executive held by the [[Cabinet of Denmark|government]]; and the judiciary, held by the [[Courts of Denmark|courts]]. The throne is inherited according to the [[Danish Act of Succession|Act of Succession]], which itself has the same status as the constitution. The [[Church of Denmark]] is the state church. The constitution holds for the entire [[The unity of the Realm|Danish realm]].\n|-\n|2\n|The royal family\n|\u00a7\u00a7 5\u201311\n|There are a number of requirements that the [[Monarchy of Denmark|sovereign]] must live up to, most importantly they must belong to the [[evangelical Lutheran]] faith; in practice they have always have been members of the Church of Denmark. The [[age of majority]] for the sovereign is at 18 years, and the Folketing can make provisions if the sovereign in incapable, minor or abroad, and choose a new sovereign if there are no heirs to the throne. Royal expenses are financed through [[Annuity|annuities]] granted by the Folketing.\n|-\n|3\n|The government\n|\u00a7\u00a7 12\u201327\n|The sovereign,{{Efn|The constitution refers to the sovereign as the \"King\", even though it is currently [[Margrethe II of Denmark|a queen]]. As the queen executes her powers through the government, the use of \"King\" nearly always means the government.|name=|group=lower-alpha}} who formally holds executive power, always exercises this power through the ministers in the government, making the role of sovereign fully ceremonial. The Kingdom employs the principle of negative [[Parliamentary system|parliamentarianism]], namely that no minister can remain in their post, if a majority of the Folketing opposes them. In addition ministers can be trialed at the Court of [[Impeachment]] (\u00a7\u00a7 59-60) for their actions while in government. Government business are discussed in the Council of State or the Council of Ministers, who today have little importance. New laws must receive [[royal assent]] and be proclaimed; this happens in ''[[Lovtidende]]''. Pre-constitutional laws remain in effect.\n\nMinisters have the right to propose laws and decision (in case they are not members of the Folketing), and the government is allowed to pardon criminals and mint coins. Under exceptional circumstances, the government can enact temporary laws, which must be reaffirmed by the Folketing as quickly as possible. In foreign policy, important decisions are taken by the Foreign Policy Committee in the Folketing, including the ratification of treaties, and the initiation of offensive military operations. A certain type of civil servants, known in Danish as ''tjenestem\u00e6nd'' (lit. servicemen), have special privileges to prevent corruption.\n\n\u00a7 20 allows the State of Denmark to hand over [[sovereignty]] to [[intergovernmental organization]]s, which is often a requirement for joining them. This needs a [[supermajority]] of 5/6 in the Folketing, or that it is approved in a referendum.\n|-\n|4\n|Elections to the Folketing\n|\u00a7\u00a7 28\u201334\n|The Folketing consists of up to 179 members,{{Efn|The constitution says \"not more than\" 179, but the Danish election law says that exactly 179 members are elected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.retsinformation.dk/Forms/R0710.aspx?id=206576|title=LBK nr 137 af 07/02/2019|last=|first=|date=21 February 2019|website=Retsinformation|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref>|name=|group=}} of which two are elected from [[Greenland]], and two from the [[Faroe Islands]]. Elections are held at least every 4 years, with the [[Prime Minister of Denmark|Prime Minister]] able to call a [[snap election]]. Elections are direct and secret, and the voting system shall ensure [[proportional representation]]. To vote you need to be a Danish citizen not under [[legal guardian]]ship, live in Denmark, and be above the voting age. The voting age was set to 23 years in a [[1953 Danish constitutional and electoral age referendum|1953 referendum]], but has since been lowered three times, and has been 18 years since 1978. Changes to the voting age require a referendum. All eligible to vote are eligible to run for a seat in the Folketing; however the Folketing can expel members who have been convicted of a crime, if they deem that they are \"unworthy\" of their seat. Acts against the security or freedom of the Folketing is high treason.\n|-\n|5\n|The Folketing\n|\u00a7\u00a7 35\u201358\n|The business year runs from the first Tuesday in October to the first Tuesday in October the next year. After a general election and at the beginning of a new business year, all unfinished business is dropped, and the Folketing starts anew. The Folketing elects a [[Speaker of the Folketing|speaker]] and vice chairmen, both after an election and at the beginning of each business year. A business year starts with an opening speech from the prime minister.\nThe Folketing meets where the government resides, which is in [[Christiansborg Palace]]. The speaker calls the meetings, and are obliged to do so on request from the prime minister or two-fifths of the Folketing. Meetings are public accessible; closed meetings can be held, but the last time this happened was in 1924, during a [[Erik the Red's Land|conflict with Norway over Greenland]]. A [[quorum]] consists of half of the members. Every member of the Folketing can propose laws and decisions, and only they (and ministers per \u00a7 21) can do that. All bills require three [[Reading (legislature)|readings]] before being passed into law. One-third of the Folketing can demand that an otherwise passed bill should be confirmed in a referendum, though some bills, among those fiscal bills, cannot be subject of a referendum.\n\nEach year, a finance bill, which defines the state budget, needs to be passed into law for the following fiscal year (which since 1979 has followed the calendar year). A provisional appropriations bill can be passed if the finance bill is not passed in time. A budget or a supplementary appropriation act is necessary to charge taxes and spend money, though in practice the Finance Committee have been allowed to approve extra expenditures, which are then spent before being passed into law. The public accounts shall be ready six months after the fiscal year, and are audited by the State Auditors, who are appointed by the Folketing.\n\nMembers of the Folketing receive a salary, and have absolute [[freedom of speech]] within the Folketing. In addition, they have [[parliamentary immunity]], except if caught in the act, though this immunity can be lifted by the Folketing. Members are not in any way bound by pledges or what [[Party discipline|their party says]], but free to vote in any way they wish. They can ask ministers questions, who are then obliged to answer.\n\nAppointments to parliamentary committees are done through proportional representation. The Folketing appoint one or two [[ombudsman|ombudsmen]]; the Folketing have decided to only appoint one. The Folketing can establish parliamentary commissions for investigations, though this have only happened five times; usually commissions led by a judge is used instead. All taxes, state loans, and military inscriptions must be set in laws. Foreigners can only be [[Danish nationality law|naturalized by law]], and only buy real-estate as permitted by law.\n|-\n|6\n|The courts\n|\u00a7\u00a7 59\u201365\n|The courts are independent of the government, though they are regulated by law. Establishing a new court to handle a specific case is not allowed. Judges answers to no-one, and in general cannot be fired or forcefully moved to a new position, unless due to a restructuring, or by verdict from other judges. Judges above 65 years can be fired, but will receive full pay until the mandatory retirement age, which is currently 70 years. It is possible to sue public agencies. The Folketing can establish special courts to handle such cases, and their verdicts can be appealed to the [[Supreme Court (Denmark)|Supreme Court]], though none have been established. Court proceedings must be as transparent as possible, and [[lay judge]]s must be used in criminal cases.\nThe special Court of Impeachment, which decides cases against ministers, consists of the 15 most senior Supreme Court judges and an equal amount appointed by the Folketing. The appointed judges cannot be members of the Folketing themselves, and sits for 6 years but remain on cases started before the end of their term. Cases are brought before the impeachment court by the government or the Folketing. Only five impeachment cases have been held; the latest was the 1993\u20131995 case against former [[Justice Minister (Denmark)|Minister of Justice]], [[Erik Ninn-Hansen]] regarding the [[Tamil Case (Denmark)|Tamil Case]].\n|-\n|7\n|Religion\n|\u00a7\u00a7 66\u201370\n|The Church of Denmark is the state church by \u00a7 4, and the Folketing can by statue decide its constitution, but has not done so. Denmark has [[freedom of religion]], and allows all to form and join religious communities, as long as they do not impinge on \"good morals or public order\". No-one is forced to pay to religions that are not their own, so the church tax is only paid by members of the Church of Denmark. Religious observance or race does not affect people's civic and political rights and duties.\n|-\n|8\n|Citizens' rights\n|\u00a7\u00a7 71\u201385\n|No citizen can be held in detention based on their race, religion or political views, and detention can only be used if prescribed by law. People arrested need to be put before a judge within 24 hours, known in Danish as a ''grundlovsforh\u00f8r'' (lit. constitutional interrogation), which decides if the [[Remand (detention)|provisional detention]] should be continued, and this decision can always be appealed. Special rules can apply in Greenland. Detention outside the criminal system or the immigration system, say due to [[Psychiatry|mental illness]], can be brought before the courts.\nA [[search warrant]] is needed to enter private property, confiscate things, or break the [[secrecy of correspondence]], though general exemptions can be made by law. [[Eminent domain|Expropriations]] must be for the public good, with full compensation, and as allowed by law. Bills regarding expropriations can by 1/3 of the Folketing be delayed until passed again after a general election. All expropriations can be brought before the courts.\n\nThe Kingdom of Denmark have [[freedom of speech]] and [[Freedom of the press|freedom of press]], but some things, say [[Defamation|libel]] or breaking [[confidentiality]], can still be brought before a judge. [[Censorship]] is forbidden. All citizens have [[freedom of association]], but associations who use violence or other illegal means can be temporary banned by the government, while dissolution is tested in court. Dissolution of political association can always be appealed to the Supreme Court. Citizens have [[freedom of assembly]] when unarmed, though danger to public order can lead to outdoor assemblies being banned. In case of riots, the police can dissolve assemblies when it \"in the name of the King and the law\" have requested it three times. Freedom from detention, freedom of association and freedom of assembly can be restricted for military personnel.\n\nAll children have the right to free [[State school|public education]], though no duty to use it; [[Homeschooling|home schooling]] and [[private school]]s are allowed. The political system shall seek to make sure that all able to work can find a job. Those unable to support themselves have the right to public support, if they submit to the related requirements. Access to professions shall only be regulated for the public good, so [[Guild|trade guilds]] cannot regulate this themselves. Every healthy man have a duty to take part in the [[Conscription|military draft]]. There are no privileges attached to [[nobility]], and in the future, no [[fief]]s or [[fee tail]]s can be created. [[Municipality|Municipalities]] have the right to govern themselves.\n|-\n|9\n|The Faroe Islands, Greenland and Iceland\n|\u00a7\u00a7 66\u201367\n|In Denmark, the voting age for municipally elections and elections to [[Church (congregation)|congregation]] boards are the same as for general elections. In Greenland and the Faroe Island, it is decided by law.\n[[Iceland]]ic citizens, who already have rights as if they were Danish citizens, retains these rights. The background for this transitional provision is that Iceland became independent from Denmark in 1918, but, as [[Kingdom of Iceland]], remained in a [[personal union]] until 1944, when it [[1944 Icelandic constitutional referendum|became a republic]]. The 1918 [[Danish\u2013Icelandic Act of Union]] granted Icelandic citizens the same rights in Denmark as Danish citizens, and after the union was dissolved in 1944, these rights were limited to Icelandic citizens then living in Denmark.\n|-\n|10\n|Changes to the constitution\n|\u00a7 88\n|All changes to the constitution requires a majority in the Folketing twice; both before and after a general election. In addition, changes must pass a referendum, where at least 40% of all eligible voters must support the change.\n|-\n|11\n|Entry into force\n|\u00a7 89\n|The current constitution entered into force on 5 June 1953, when published in ''Lovtidende''. The [[Rigsdagen|Rigsdag]], the sitting bicameral legislative under the old constitution, remained in place until the [[1953 Danish general election|September 1953 general election]], where the [[Landstinget|Landsting]], the chamber in addition to the Folketing, was abolished.\n|}\n\n== Constitutional institutions ==\n[[File:Christiansborg Slot Copenhagen 2014 01.jpg|thumb|320x320px|[[Christiansborg Palace]], where both the government, the [[Folketing]] and the [[Supreme Court (Denmark)|Supreme Court]] resides.]]\nThe Constitution establishes Denmark as a [[Constitutional monarchy|constitutional monarcy]], where the [[Monarchy of Denmark|monarch]] serves as a [[ceremonial Head of state]]. The title of monarch is [[Hereditary monarchy|hereditary]] and passed on to the firstborn child, with [[Absolute primogeniture|equal rights for sons and daughters]].\n\nThe political system of Denmark can be described as a [[democracy]] with a [[parliamentary system]] of governance. The powers of the state is [[Separation of powers|separated]] into 3 different branches. The [[legislative branch]] held by the [[Folketing]], the [[executive branch]] held by the [[Danish Government|Danish government]], and the [[judicial branch]] held by the [[Courts of Denmark]].\n\n=== The monarchy ===\n{{Main|Monarchy of Denmark}}\nThe Danish monarch,{{efn|While the Constitution consistently refer to the monarch as the \"king\", this can also be a queen regnant. In fact, the current monarch of the Kingdom of Denmark is [[Queen Margrethe II]].}} as the [[head of state]], holds great ''[[de jure]]'' power, but ''[[de facto]]'' only serves as a figurehead who is not interfering in politics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kongehuset.dk/en/the-royal-house/regentparret/hm-the-queen|title=HM The Queen|last=|first=|date=2016-04-07|work=The Danish Monarchy - Front Page|access-date=2018-06-20|language=en|quote=\"HM The Queen takes no part in politics and does not express any political opinions.\"}}</ref> The monarch formally holds [[executive power]] and, co-jointly with the [[Folketing]], [[legislative power]], since each new law requires [[royal assent]]. By article 12, 13 and 14, the powers vested in the monarch can only be exercised through the ministers, who are responsible for all acts, thus removing any political or legal liability from the monarch.<ref name=\":1\">Grundloven, Mikael Witte 1997 {{ISBN|87-7724-672-1}}</ref>{{efn|For this reason, when reading the Constitution, the word ''king'', in the context of exercising acts of state, is to be read as the ''Government'' (consisting of the Prime Minister and other ministers)}} The monarch appoints the ministers after advice from the [[Prime Minister of Denmark|Prime Minister]]. The Prime Minister is itself appointed after advice from the leaders of the political parties of the Folketing, a process known as a ''Queen's meeting'' ({{Lang-da|dronningerunde}}).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedanishparliament.dk/democracy/the-division-of-powers|title=The Division of Powers|last=|first=|date=|work=The Danish Parliament|access-date=2018-06-20|language=en|quote=\"The political party leaders will then advise the Queen on whom to invite to lead the negotiations to form a new Government. The person who has the support of a majority of party leaders is chosen as the chief negotiator and usually also becomes Prime Minister. In principle, the Constitutional Act gives the Queen the authority to appoint and dismiss Ministers, but she has no real political influence. In practice, it is the Prime Minister who selects Ministers, and subsequently the Queen formally appoints the Ministers recommended by the Prime Minister.\"}}</ref> The monarch and the Cabinet attend regular meetings in the [[Council of State (Denmark)|Council of State]], where royal assent is given, and the monarch is regularly briefed on the political situation by the Prime Minister and Foreign minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kongehuset.dk/en/the-royal-house/regentparret/hm-the-queen|title=HM The Queen|last=|first=|date=2016-04-07|work=The Danish Monarchy - Front Page|access-date=2018-06-20|language=en|quote=\"Additionally, The Queen is the formal Head of the Government and therefore presides over the State Council, where the Acts that have been passed by the Folketing are signed into law. The Prime Minister and the Minister of Foreign Affairs report regularly to The Queen to inform her of the latest political developments.\"}}</ref>\n\nThe Constitution requires the monarch to be a member of the [[Lutheranism|evangelical lutheran church]], though not necessary the [[Church of Denmark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thedanishparliament.dk/~/media/pdf/publikationer/english/my_constitutional_act_with_explanations.ashx|title=My Constitutional Act with explanations|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|quote=\"[the Queen] must belong to the Evangelical-Lutheran Church. However, she need  not necessarily be a member of the Evangelical- Lutheran Church of Denmark (Folkekirken).\"}}</ref>\n\n=== The government ===\n{{Main|Government of Denmark}}\nThe Government holds executive power, and is responsible for carrying out the acts of the Folketing. The Government does not have to pass a [[Vote of Confidence|vote of confidence]] before taking the seat, but any minister can be subject to a motion of no confidence. If a vote of no confidence is successfully passed against the Prime Minister, the government must resign or call a [[snap election]].\n\n=== The Folketing ===\n{{Main|Folketing}}\n[[File:Det danske parlament.jpg|thumb|240x240px|The Folketing chamber, inside Christiansborg Palace]]\nThe Folketing is the legislative branch of Denmark, and is located at [[Christiansborg Palace|Christiansborg]]. It consists of 179 members,{{efn|While the Constitution says that \"not more than\" 179 members are elected, the law concerning general elections states that exactly 179 members are elected.<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Bekendtg\u00f8relse af lov om valg til Folketinget|date=2017-12-08|url=https://www.retsinformation.dk/Forms/R0710.aspx?id=194769|volume=|issue=LBK nr 1426|pages=|quote=\"\u00a7 7. To the Folketing, a total of 179 people are chosen.\"|access-date=2018-06-20}}</ref>}} of which 2 members are elected in [[Greenland]], and 2 in the [[Faroe Islands]]. [[General election]]s is nominally held every 4 years, but the Prime Minister can at any point call a snap election. All Danish citizens over the age of 18 years who are living permanently within Denmark is eligible to vote, except those placed under [[legal guardianship]]. The same group of people is able to run for office. The electoral system is characterized as a [[party-list proportional representation]] system, with an [[election threshold]] on 2%. As a result, Denmark has a [[Multi-party system|multi-party parliamentary system]], where no single party has an absolute majority.\n\nThe session starts anew each year on the first Tuesday in October, and when interrupted by a general election; all previously unfinished business is cancelled. The Folketing then elects a [[Speaker of the Folketing|speaker]], who is responsible for convening meetings. The Folketing lay down their own [[Parliamentary procedure|rules of procedure]], subject to the requirements in the Constitution. Among those, the required [[quorum]] of 90 members of the Folketing, and the rule that every [[Bill (law)|proposed law]] requires three [[Reading (legislature)|readings]] in the Folketing, before it can be passed into law.\n\nThe Folketing also have the responsibility of holding the government accountable for the governance. The members of the Folketing does this by submitting questing to the ministers and convene them to explanatory hearings. In addition, the Folketing elect a number of ''State Auditors'' ({{Lang-da|Statsrevisorer}}), who has the responsibility to look through the public accounts, and check that everything is okay, and that the government only spend money approved by the Folketing. Furthermore, the Folketing also appoints an [[ombudsman]], who investigates wrongdoings by the public administrative authorities on behalf of the public.\n\n=== The courts ===\n{{Main|Courts of Denmark}}\nThe [[Courts of Denmark]] are independent of the other two branches. The Constitution does not stipulate how the courts are to be organized. Instead, this is regulated by statute. In the normal court system, there are 24 District Courts, High Courts and the [[Supreme Court (Denmark)|Supreme Court]]. In addition to these, there is some special courts. There are certain rights in the Constitution with respect to the judiciary system.\n\nThere is a special Court of Impeachment, which can prosecute ministers for their official acts.\n\nThe court system is [[Judicial review in Denmark|able to perform judicial review]] of laws, i.e. check [[Judicial review|if they are constitutional]]. This right is not included in the constitution, but was established by the Supreme Court in the beginning of the 20'th century, when it decided to hear cases about the constitutionally of land laws. While this right was contested in the beginning, the political system eventually accepted it. The Supreme Court have been reluctant to rules laws unconstitutional; the only time it have done so was in 1999, when it found that the [[Tvind]] law breached the principle of separations of power. Cases about the constitutionality of laws can only be initiated by people directly affected by the laws. All can do this with respect to the Danish relation to EU, because of its wide effects on society.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jyllands-posten.dk/debat/kronik/article5217123.ece/|title=Domstolene som grundlovens vogter|last=Christensen|first=Jens Peter|date=23 February 2013|work=Jyllands-Posten|access-date=26 November 2019|language=da|author-link=Jens Peter Christensen}}</ref>\n\n=== The Church of Denmark ===\n{{Main|Church of Denmark}}\nThe Evangelical-Lutheran Church of Denmark is the [[State religion|state church]] established by the Constitution. The queen have a number of duties in the Church of Denmark, and is often considered its head, but this is not a formal role in any way.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kristeligt-dagblad.dk/kirke-tro/er-dronningen-folkekirkens-overhoved|title=Er Dronningen folkekirkens overhoved?|last=Fjelstervang|first=Josefine|date=8 January 2019|work=Kristeligt Dagblad|access-date=7 December 2019|language=da}}</ref>\n\n=== The State Auditors ===\nThe state auditors are responsible for checking the public accounts. They are supported by [[Rigsrevisionen]].\n\n=== The Parliamentary Ombudsman ===\nThe Parliamentary [[Ombudsman]] is an independent institution under the Folketing, in charge of investigating and inspecting public authorities.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.dk/da/organisation/folketingets-institutioner/folketingets-ombudsmand|title=Folketingets Ombudsmand|last=|first=|date=|website=Folketinget|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> It is inspired by [[Parliamentary Ombudsman#Sweden|Swedish example]], and was established in 1955, following its inclusion in the 1953 constitution. The ombudsman is both appointed by and can be dismissed by the Folketing. The ombudsman cannot be a member of the Folketing themselves. While the constitution allows the Folketing to appoint two ombudsmen, by law it only appoints one.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Samfund,_jura_og_politik/Jura/Danmarks_statsforfatning/Folketingets_Ombudsmand|title=Folketingets Ombudsmand|last=Jensen|first=Claus Haagen|date=3 January 2015|website=Den Store Danske|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> The current ombudsman, {{As of|2019|December|df=|lc=y}}, is [[Niels Fenger]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ombudsmanden.dk/find/nyheder/alle/niels_fenger_valgt_som_ny_ombudsmand/|title=Niels Fenger valgt som ny ombudsmand|last=|first=|date=26 November 2019|work=Folketingets Ombudsmand|access-date=6 December 2019|language=da}}</ref>\n\nThe ombudsman handles 4,000-5,000 complains annually from the general public, and can also open cases on its own accord. In addition to that, the ombudsman have a monitoring division that inspects prisons, psychiatric institutions and social care homes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.ombudsmanden.dk/introduktion/|title=About the Ombudsman|last=|first=|date=|website=Folketingets Ombudsmand|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> Since 2012 it has also had a children's division.<ref name=\":8\" /> The ombudsman cannot demand any action from the administration. It can only voice criticism and make recommendations, but these carry a lot of weight, and its recommendations are usually followed by the administration.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\" />\n\n== Civil rights ==\nThe Constitution of Denmark outlines fundamental rights in sections 71\u201380. Several of these are of only limited scope and thus serve as a sort of lower bar. The [[European Convention on Human Rights]] was introduced in Denmark by law on 29 April 1992 and supplements the mentioned paragraphs.\n\n=== Personal liberty ===\n{{quote box\n| width = 20em\n| align = right\n| quote = Personal liberty shall be inviolable. No Danish subject shall in any manner whatever be deprived of his liberty because of his political or religious convictions or because of his descent.\n| source = Section 71\n}}The constitution guarantees the personal liberty. No citizen can be held in detention based on their race, religion or political views, and detention can only be used if prescribed by law. People arrested need to be put before a judge within 24 hours, known in Danish as a ''grundlovsforh\u00f8r'' (lit. constitutional interrogation), who decides if the [[Remand (detention)|provisional detention]] should be continued, and this decision can always be appealed. Special rules can apply in Greenland. Detention outside the criminal system or the immigration system, say due to [[Psychiatry|mental illness]], can be brought before the courts.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Right to property ===\nThe constitution guarantees the [[right to property]]. A [[search warrant]] is needed to enter private property, confiscate things, or break the [[secrecy of correspondence]], though general exemptions can be made by law. [[Eminent domain|Expropriations]] must be for the public good, with full compensation, and as allowed by law. Bills regarding expropriations can by 1/3 of the Folketing be delayed until passed again after a general election. All expropriations can be brought before the courts.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Freedom of speech and freedom of the press ===\n{{Further|Freedom of speech and freedom of the press in Denmark}}Denmark have [[freedom of speech]] and [[Freedom of the press|freedom of press]], but some things, say [[Defamation|libel]] or breaking [[confidentiality]], can still be brought before a judge. [[Censorship]] is forbidden. \u00a777: \"Anyone is entitled to in print, writing and speech to publish his or hers thoughts, yet under responsibility to the courts. Censorship and other preventive measures can never again be introduced.\"<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThere's widespread agreement in Danish legal theory that \u00a7 77 protects what is called \"formal freedom of speech\" (formel ytringsfrihed), meaning that one cannot be required to submit one's speech for review by authorities before publishing or otherwise disseminating it.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Danmarks Riges Grundlov med kommentarer|date=2006|publisher=Jurist- og \u00d8konomforbundets Forlag|isbn=8757411565|editor-last=Zahle|editor-first=Henrik|edition=2nd|location=[[Copenhagen]]|p=536|trans-title=Constitution of the Kingdom of Denmark with comments|oclc=466582184|ref=harv}}</ref> However, there is disagreement about whether or not \u00a7 77 covers \"material freedom of speech\" (materiel ytringsfrihed), the right to not be punished for ones speech. There is agreement that the phrasing \"under responsibility to the courts\" gives legislators some right to restrict speech, but conversely there have been several court decisions implying that some material freedom of speech does exist.{{Sfn|Zahle|2006|p=539}} The discussion is about whether the material speech has limits or not, and if so, what those limits are.{{Sfn|Zahle|2006|p=539}}<ref>See {{Harvnb|Zahle|2006|pp=539-552}} for differing perspectives on the issue.</ref>\n\n=== Freedom of association ===\nAll citizens have [[freedom of association]], but associations who use violence or other illegal means can be temporary banned by the government, while dissolution is tested in court. Dissolution of political association can always be appealed to the Supreme Court.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn 1941, during the [[Denmark in World War II|occupation by Nazi Germany]], the Rigsdag banned the [[Communist Party of Denmark|Communist Party]] through the [[Communist Law|communist law]]. The law also legalized existing interments of Danish communists, including members of the Folketing. Both the internments and the law broke rights in the constitution, but was justified by the [[Doctrine of necessity|necessity of the situation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Danmarks_geografi_og_historie/Danmarks_historie/Danmark_1849-1945/Kommunistloven_af_1941|title=Kommunistloven af 1941|last=Kjeldb\u00e6k|first=Esben|date=17 February 2015|website=Den Store Danske|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/kommunistinterneringerne-under-besaettelsen-1941-1945/|title=Kommunistinterneringerne under bes\u00e6ttelsen, 1941-1945|last=B\u00f8gh|first=Louise Skovholm|date=3 February 2017|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|publisher=Aarhus Universitet|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref> The Supreme Court found the law constitutional; a decision that was criticized as the Supreme Court President had been involved in its creation. The case illustrated how long Danish politicians was willing to go to ensure Danish control of law enforcement, and that democracy can be stretched to ensure its continued existence.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn addition to the communist law, on only two occasions have an association been forcefully dissolved. In 1874, the International Workers Organization, a precursor to the [[Social Democrats (Denmark)|Social Democrats]], was dissolved for being revolutionary, and in 1924, the organization Nekkab was dissolved for being a meeting place for [[Homosexuality|homosexuals]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kristeligt-dagblad.dk/historie/det-har-aldrig-vaeret-let-lukke-foreninger|title=Det har aldrig v\u00e6ret let at lukke foreninger|last=Mikkelsen|first=Morten|date=2 May 2016|work=Kristeligt Dagblad|access-date=26 November 2019|language=da}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.berlingske.dk/samfund/er-loyal-to-familia-en-voldelig-forening-forstaa-forbudssagen-mod-ltf|title=Er Loyal to Familia en voldelig forening? Forst\u00e5 forbudssagen mod LTF|last=Lingren|first=Daniel|date=10 May 2019|work=Berlingske|access-date=26 November 2019|language=da}}</ref> In 2020, the gang [[Loyal to Familia]] was dissolved by the Copenhagen City Court; a judgment that has been appealed. The gang was temporarily banned in 2018, and the court case \u2013 the first dissolution case against a criminal gang \u2013 was initiated.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nyheder.tv2.dk/krimi/2020-01-24-banden-loyal-to-familia-oploeses|title=Banden Loyal to Familia opl\u00f8ses|last=S\u00f8ndberg|first=Astrid|date=24 January 2020|work=TV 2|access-date=24 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Jensen|first2=Marie}}</ref> Prior to this, it has been investigated if [[Hells Angels]], [[Bandidos Motorcycle Club|Bandidos]] and [[Hizb ut-Tahrir]] could be banned, but the conclusions was that it would be difficult to win the cases.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/indland/rigsadvokaten-siger-ok-et-forbud-mod-loyal-familia-er-paa-vej|title=Rigsadvokaten siger ok: Et forbud mod Loyal to Familia er p\u00e5 vej|last=Toft|first=Emma|date=2 November 2017|work=DR|access-date=26 November 2019|language=da}}</ref>\n\n=== Freedom of assembly ===\nCitizens have [[freedom of assembly]] when unarmed, though danger to public order can lead to outdoor assemblies being banned. In case of riots, the police can dissolve assemblies when it \"in the name of the King and the law\" have requested it three times.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Freedom of religion ===\n\nSection 4 establishes that the [[Church of Denmark|Evangelical Lutheran Church]] is \"the people's church\" ({{lang|da|folkekirken}}), and as such is [[state religion|supported by the state]]. Freedom of religion is granted in section 67, and official discrimination based on faith is forbidden in section 70.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Other rights ===\nAll children have the right to free [[State school|public education]], though no duty to use it; [[Homeschooling|home schooling]] and [[private school]]s are allowed. The political system shall seek to make sure that all able to work can find a job. Those unable to support themselves have the right to public support, if they submit to the related requirements. Access to professions shall only be regulated for the public good, so [[Guild|trade guilds]] cannot regulate this themselves.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== Other themes ==\n\n=== National sovereignty ===\nSection 20 of the current constitution establishes that the delegation of specified parts of national sovereignty to international authorities requires either a 5/6 majority in Parliament or an ordinary majority in both Parliament and the electorate. This section has been debated heavily in connection with Denmark's membership of the [[European Union]] (EU), as critics hold that changing governments have violated the Constitution by surrendering too much power.\n\nIn 1996, Prime Minister [[Poul Nyrup Rasmussen]] was sued by twelve [[Eurosceptics]] for violating this section. The [[Supreme Court of Denmark|Supreme Court]] acquitted Rasmussen (and thereby earlier governments dating back to 1972) but reaffirmed that there are limits to how much sovereignty can be surrendered. In 2011, Prime Ministers [[Lars L\u00f8kke Rasmussen]] faced a similar challenge when he was sued by twenty-eight citizens for having adopted the European [[Lisbon Treaty]] without a referendum. The group of professors, actors, writers and Eurosceptic politicians argued that the Lisbon Treaty hands over parts of national sovereignty to the EU and therefore a referendum should have taken place.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pop|first1=Valentina|title=Danish PM sued over Lisbon Treaty|url=https://euobserver.com/political/31622|accessdate=14 April 2016|publisher=[[EUobserver]]|date=11 January 2011|location=Brussels}}</ref> The case was later dismissed.\n\nSection 20 was used in 1972 when Denmark, after a [[1972 Danish European Communities membership referendum|referendum]], joined the [[European Economic Community|EEC]] (now [[European Union|EU]]). More recently, in 2015 an (unsuccessful) [[2015 Danish European Union opt-out referendum|referendum]] was held on one of its EU-opt-outs.\n\n===Greenland and the Faroe Islands===\n{{See also|The unity of the Realm}}\nSection 32 states \"special rules may be provided by Statute for the commencement and determination of Faroe Islands and Greenland representation in the Parliament.\"<ref name=\"Act\" /> This section refers to [[home rule]] in both territories. The specific arrangements for the transfer of powers and monetary competency to Greenland and the Faroe Islands are contained in separate statues, with equal constitutional status (see below).\n\n===Separation of powers===\n{{See also|Separation of powers}}\n\nDenmark have [[separation of powers]] into the three classic branches: the legislative, held by the [[Folketing]]; the executive held by the [[Cabinet of Denmark|government]]; and the judiciary, held by the [[Courts of Denmark|courts]]. The separation of powers is described in the constitution, and is there, as in many democracies, to prevent abuse of power. The Folketing enact laws, and the government implements them. The courts make judgments in disputes, either between citizens, or between authorities and citizens.<ref name=\"danishparliament\" />\n\nThe Constitution is heavily influenced by the French philosopher [[Montesquieu]],{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} whose separation of powers was aimed at achieving mutual monitoring of each of the branches of government. However, the division between legislative and executive power in Denmark is not as sharp as in the [[United States]].\n\nIn 1999, the Supreme Court found that the [[Tvind]] law, a law that barred specific schools from receiving public funding, was unconstitutional, because it breached the concept of separation of powers by settling a concrete dispute between the Tvind schools and the government. The judgment is the only time the courts have found a law to be unconstitutional.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/indland/historisk-tvind-dom|title=Historisk Tvind-dom|last=|first=|date=19 February 1999|work=DR|access-date=26 November 2019|language=da}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Samfund,_jura_og_politik/Jura/Enkelte_navngivne_retssager/Tvind-dommen|title=Tvind-dommen|last=L.|first=Mads|date=|website=Den Store Danske|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary power===\nIn several sections the Constitutional Act sets out the powers and duties of the Danish Parliament. Section 15 in the Act, which deals with\nthe parliamentary principle, lays down that \"a Minister shall not remain in office after the Parliament has passed a vote of no confidence in him\".<ref name=\"Act\" /> This suggests that Ministers are accountable to Parliament and even subservient to it. The Cabinet exerts executive power through its Ministers, but cannot remain in office if the majority of the Folketing goes against it. Another important feature of the Danish parliamentary system is that the Constitutional Act lays down that \"the Members of the Folketing shall be elected for a period of four years\", but still, \"the King may at any time issue writs for a new election\".<ref name=\"danishparliament\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Politics|Denmark|Faroe Islands}}\n*[[Codified constitution]]\n*[[Constitutional economics]]\n*[[Constitutionalism]]\n*[[Constitutional law]]\n*[[Index of Denmark-related articles]]\n*[[Politics of Denmark]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisourcepar|Constitutional Act of Denmark, 5 June 1953}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121120170200/http://www.thedanishparliament.dk/Democracy/The_Constitutional_Act_of_Denmark.aspx The Constitutional Act of Denmark] - The Danish Parliament\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140714134738/http://pub.uvm.dk/2008/democracycanon/kap20.html The Constitutional Act of the Kingdom of Denmark] - Ministry of Education of Denmark\n\n{{Constitution of Europe}}\n{{Denmark topics}}\n{{Faroe Islands topics}}\n{{Greenland topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Constitution Of Denmark}}\n[[Category:1849 in law]]\n[[Category:Government of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Legal history of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Politics of Denmark]]\n[[Category:History of the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:History of Greenland]]\n[[Category:Politics of Greenland]]\n[[Category:Danish law| ]]\n[[Category:1849 in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Constitution of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Kingdom of Denmark]]\n[[Category:June 1849 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox constitution\n| document_name        = Constitutional Act of the Kingdom of Denmark\n| image                = Grundloven-1849-forside.jpg\n| image_alt            =\n| caption              = Front page of the first constitution from 1849\n| orig_lang_code       = da\n| title_orig           = Danmarks Riges Grundlov\n| jurisdiction         = [[Denmark]], [[Greenland]] and the [[Faroe Islands]]\n| date_ratified        = 25 May 1849 (first)<br />[[1953 Danish constitutional and electoral age referendum|28 May 1953]] (current)\n| date_effective       = [[Constitution Day (Denmark)|5 June]] 1849 (first)<br /> 5 June 1953 (current)\n| system               = [[Constitutional monarchy]]\n| branches             = Three (executive, legislature and judiciary)\n| chambers             = Unicameral ([[Folketing]])\n| executive            = [[Cabinet of Denmark|Cabinet]] responsible to parliament\n| courts               = [[Supreme Court (Denmark)|Supreme Court]] and others\n| location_of_document =\n| writer               = Constitutional Assembly of the Realm\n| signers              = [[Frederick VII of Denmark|Frederick VII]] (first)<br />[[Frederick IX of Denmark|Frederick IX]] (current)\n| media_type           =\n}}\n{{Politics of Denmark}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n\nThe '''Constitutional Act of the Kingdom of Denmark''' ({{lang-da|Danmarks Riges Grundlov}}), or simply '''the Constitution''' ({{lang-da|Grundloven}}), is the [[constitution]] of the [[Denmark|Kingdom of Denmark]], applying equally in Denmark proper, [[Greenland]] and the [[Faroe Islands]]. The first constitution was adopted in 1849, and the current constitution is from 1953. It is one of the oldest constitutions in the world.<ref name=\"danishparliament\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedanishparliament.dk/Democracy/The_Constitutional_Act_of_Denmark.aspx|title=The Constitutional Act of Denmark|website=thedanishparliament.dk|publisher=The Danish Parliament (Folketinget)|accessdate=14 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120170200/http://www.thedanishparliament.dk/Democracy/The_Constitutional_Act_of_Denmark.aspx|archive-date=20 November 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Constitutional Act has been changed a few times. The wording is general enough to still apply today.<ref name=\"danishparliament\" />\n\nThe constitution defines Denmark as a [[constitutional monarchy]], governed thought a [[parliamentary system]]. It creates [[Separation of powers|separations of power]] between the [[Folketing]], which enact laws, [[Government of Denmark|the government]], which implements them, and [[Courts of Denmark|the courts]], which makes judgment about them. In addition it gives a number of [[fundamental rights]] to people in Denmark, including [[freedom of speech]], [[freedom of religion]], [[freedom of association]], and [[freedom of assembly]]. The constitution applies to all persons in Denmark, not just [[Danish nationality law|Danish citizens]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.berlingske.dk/politik/df-mener-at-grundloven-kun-er-til-for-danske-statsborgere-men-en-afdoed|title=DF mener, at Grundloven kun er til for danske statsborgere \u2013 men en afd\u00f8d professor og tre nulevende eksperter er dybt uenige|last=Holm|first=Thue Ahrenkilde|date=21 November 2019|work=Berlingske|access-date=29 October 2019|last2=Rohde|first2=Thomas S\u00f8gaard|language=Danish|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIts adoption in 1849 ended an [[absolute monarchy]] and introduced [[democracy]]. Denmark celebrates the adoption of the Constitution on 5 June\u2014the date in which the first Constitution was ratified\u2014every year as [[Constitution Day (Denmark)|Constitution Day]].\n\nThe main principle of the Constitutional Act was to limit the King's power (section 2).<ref name=\"Act\">[http://www.servat.unibe.ch/icl/da00000_.html The Constitution of Denmark] Accessed on 14 April 2016.</ref> It creates a comparatively weak constitutional monarch who is dependent on Ministers for advice and Parliament to draft and pass [[legislation]]. The Constitution of 1849 established a [[bicameralism|bicameral]] parliament, the {{lang|da|[[Rigsdag]]}}, consisting of the [[Landsting (Denmark)|Landsting]] and the [[Folketing]]. The most significant change in the Constitution of 1953 was the abolishment of the Landsting, leaving the [[unicameral]] Folketing. It also enshrined fundamental [[civil rights]], which remain in the current constitution: such as ''[[habeas corpus]]'' (section 71), [[private property rights]] (section 72) and [[freedom of speech]] (section 77).<ref name=\"Act\" />\n\nThe [[Folketing|Danish Parliament]] ({{lang|da|Folketinget}}) cannot make any laws which may be repugnant or contrary to the Constitutional Act. While Denmark has no [[constitutional court]], laws can be declared unconstitutional and rendered void by the [[Supreme Court (Denmark)|Supreme Court of Denmark]].\n\nChanges to the Act must be confirmed by a majority in two consecutive parliamentary terms and then approval of the electorate through a national [[referendum]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Tschentscher, Axel  |url=http://www.servat.unibe.ch/icl/da00000_.html |title=The Constitution of Denmark \u2013 Section 88 |publisher=Servat.unibe.ch |accessdate=2016-02-12}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|History of Denmark}}\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2016}}\n\n=== Background ===\n[[File:Frederik VII af August Schi\u00f8tt.jpg|upright|thumb|left|Frederick VII, the last king of Denmark to rule as an absolute monarch.]]\nDuring the [[Late Middle Ages|late middle ages]] and the [[renaissance]], the power of the king was tempered by a [[h\u00e5ndf\u00e6stning]], a coronation charter each king had to sign before being accepted as king by the [[nobility]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/haandfaestning/|title=Vis|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-04-13|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref> This tradition was abandoned in 1665 when King [[Frederick III of Denmark]] managed to establish a [[Hereditary monarchy|hereditary]] [[absolute monarchy]] by '''Lex Regia''' (''The Law of The King'', {{lang-da|Kongeloven}}). This was Europe's only formal absolutist constitution.<ref>[http://www.folketinget.dk/BAGGRUND/00000033/00972093.htm Folketinget] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507190923/http://www.folketinget.dk/BAGGRUND/00000033/00972093.htm |date=7 May 2009 }}</ref> Under Lex Regia, absolute power was inherited for almost 200 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/kongeloven-1665/#indhold5|title=Vis|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-04-13|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the beginning of the 19th century, there were a growing democratic movement in Denmark and [[Frederick VI of Denmark|King Frederick VI]] only made some small concessions, such as creation of ''Consultative Estate Assemblies'' ({{Lang-da|R\u00e5dgivende St\u00e6nderforsamlinger}}) in 1834. But these only served to help the political movements, of which the [[National Liberal Party (Denmark)|National Liberals]] and the [[Society of the Friends of Peasants|Friends of Peasants]] were the forerunners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/inddragelse-af-befolkningen-i-den-enevaeldige-administration/|title=Vis|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-04-13|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref> When [[Christian VIII of Denmark|Christian VIII]] became king in 1839, he continued the political line of only making small democratic concessions, while upholding the absolute monarchy.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAt this time Denmark was in a [[personal union]] between kingdom of Denmark and the duchies of [[Duchy of Schleswig|Schleswig]], [[Duchy of Holstein|Holstein]], and [[Saxe-Lauenburg|Lauenburg]] called ''The Unitary State'' (Danish: ''Helstaten''), but the [[Schleswig-Holstein Question|Schleswig-Holstein question]] was causing tension. Under the slogan ''Denmark to the [[Eider (river)|Eider]]'', the National Liberals campaigned for Schleswig to become an integral part of Denmark, while separating Holstein and Lauenburg from Denmark.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/perioder/det-unge-demokrati-1848-1901/kritik-af-enevaelden-og-debat-om-slesvig/|title=Kritik af enev\u00e6lden og debat om Slesvig|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-05-18|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref> Holstein and Lauenburg were then part of the [[German Confederation]], while Schleswig was not. On the other side, German nationalists in Schleswig were keen to keep Schleswig and Holstein together, and wanted Schleswig to join the German Confederation.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/perioder/det-unge-demokrati-1848-1901/marts-1848/|title=Marts 1848|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-05-18|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref> Christian VIII had reached the conclusion that, should the Unitary State survive, a constitution covering both Denmark, Schleswig and Holstein was necessary. Before his death in January 1848, he advised his [[Heir apparent|heir]] [[Frederick VII of Denmark|Frederick VII]] to create such a constitution.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/christian-8-1786-1848/|title=Vis|last=103982@au.dk|date=2018-04-13|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1848 following a [[Revolutions of 1848|series of European revolutions]], the Schleswig-Holstein question became increasingly tense. Following an ultimatum from Schleswig and Holstein, political pressure from the National Liberals intensified, and Frederick VII replaced the sitting government with the [[Moltke I Cabinet|March Cabinet]], where four leaders of the Friends of Peasants and the National Liberals served, among those [[Ditlev Gothard Monrad|D.G. Monrad]] and [[Orla Lehmann]], both National Liberals. The ultimatum from Schleswig and Holstein was rejected, and the [[First Schleswig War]] started.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Drafting and signing of the first constitution (1849) ===\n[[File:Grundlovgivende rigsforsamling - Constantin Hansen.jpg|thumb|The National Constitutional Assembly (painting by [[Constantin Hansen]] 1860\u201364) ([[Frederiksborg Castle]], Hiller\u00f8d)]]\n[[File:Grundloven 1849 i 2018.jpg|thumb|The Constitutional Act of 1849 on display in 2018]]\n\nMonrad drafted the first draft of the Constitution, which was then edited by Lehmann. Sources of inspiration included the [[Constitution of Norway]] of 1814 and the [[Constitution of Belgium]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Danmarks_geografi_og_historie/Danmarks_historie/Danmark_1536-1849/Den_Grundlovgivende_Rigsforsamling|title=Den Grundlovgivende Rigsforsamling {{!}} Gyldendal - Den Store Danske|website=denstoredanske.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> The draft was laid before the ''Constitutional Assembly of the Realm'' ({{lang|da|Den Grundlovgivende Rigsforsamling}}). This assembly, which consisted of 114 members directly elected in October 1848, and 38 members appointed by Frederick VII, was overall split in three different groupings: the National Liberals, the Friends of Peasants, and the Conservatives. A key topic for discussion was the political system, and the rules governing elections.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/perioder/det-unge-demokrati-1848-1901/demokratiets-etablering-den-grundlovgivende-forsamling/|title=Demokratiets etablering: Den Grundlovgivende Forsamling|last=103982@au.dk|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 May 1849, the Constitutional Assembly approved the new constitution, and on 5 June 1849 it was signed by Frederick VII. For this reason, it is also known as the ''June constitution''.<ref name=\":4\" /> Today, 5 June is known as [[Constitution Day (Denmark)|Constitution Day]] and is a national holiday in Denmark.\n\nThe new constitution establish the [[Rigsdagen|Rigsdag]], a [[Bicameralism|bicameral]] parliament, with an upper house called the [[Landsting (Denmark)|Landsting]], and a lower house called the [[Folketing]]. While the voting rights for both chambers were the same, the elections to the Landsting was indirect, and the eligibility requirements harder. The constitution gave voting rights to 15% of the Danish population. Due to the First Schleswig war, the constitution was not put into force for Schleswig; instead this question was postponed to after the war.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/danmarks-riges-grundlov-af-5-juni-1849-junigrundloven/|title=Danmarks Riges Grundlov, 5. juni 1849 (Junigrundloven)|last=103982@au.dk|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Parallel constitution for the Unitary State (1855-1866) ===\nFollowing the First Schleswig war, which ended in Danish victory in 1852, the [[London Protocol (1852)|London Protocol]] reaffirmed the territorial integrity of the Unitary State, and solved an impending succession issue, since Frederick VII was childless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/londontraktaten-8-maj-1852/|title=Londontraktaten, 8. maj 1852|last=103982@au.dk|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref> Since the June constitution was not put into force in Schleswig, the Schleswig-Holstein question remained unsolved. Work for creating a common constitution for the Unitary State started, and in 1855 the rigsdag accepted ''Helstatsforfatning (Constitution for The Unitary State),'' which covered affairs common to Denmark, Schleswig and Holstein. At the same time, the June constitution was limited to only be applicable in Denmark.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/helstatsforfatningen-1855-faellesforfatningen/|title=Helstatsforfatningen (F\u00e6llesforfatningen), 2. oktober 1855|last=103982@au.dk|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|language=da|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 1863 this constitution was changed, the new one was called ''Novemberforfatningen''. This was shortly before [[Second Schleswig War|Second Schleswig war]], where Denmark lost control of Schleswig and Holstein, rendering the parallel constitution void.\n\n===The Revised Constitution (1866)===\n\n[[File:Danish Constitions in Folketinget 20090520.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The Constitutions of Denmark located inside [[Folketinget]].]]In 1866, the defeat in the [[Second Schleswig War]], and the loss of [[Schleswig-Holstein]] led to tightened election rules for the Upper Chamber, which paralyzed legislative work, leading to provisional laws.\n\nThe conservative [[Conservative People's Party (Denmark)|H\u00f8jre]] had pressed for a new constitution, giving the upper chamber of parliament more power, making it more exclusive and switching power to the conservatives from the original long standing dominance of the [[National Liberal Party (Denmark)|National Liberals]], who lost influence and was later disbanded. This long period of dominance of the H\u00f8jre party under the leadership of [[Jacob Br\u00f8nnum Scavenius Estrup]] with the backing of the king [[Christian IX of Denmark]] was named the ''provisorietid'' (provisional period) because the government was based on provisional laws instead of parliamentary decisions. This also gave rise to a conflict with the Liberals (farm owners) at that time and now known as [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]] (Left). This constitutional battle concluded in 1901 with the so-called systemskifte (change of system) with the liberals as victors. At this point the king and H\u00f8jre finally accepted [[parliamentarism]] as the ruling principle of Danish political life. This principle was not [[Codification (law)|codified]] until the 1953 constitution.\n\n=== Universal suffrage (1915) ===\nIn 1915, the tightening from 1866 was reversed, and women were given the right to vote. Also, a new requirement for changing the constitution was introduced. Not only must the new constitution be passed by two consecutive parliaments, it must also pass a referendum, where 45% of the electorate must vote yes. This meant that Prime Minister [[Thorvald Stauning]]'s attempt to change the Constitution in 1939 failed.<ref>S\u00f8ren M\u00f8rch: ''24 statsministre''. {{ISBN|87-02-00361-9}}.</ref>\n\n=== Reunion with Schleswig (1920) ===\n{{See also|1920 Schleswig plebiscites}}\nIn 1920, a [[1920 Danish constitutional referendum|new referendum]] was held to change the Constitution again, allowing for the reunification of Denmark following the defeat of Germany in [[World War I]]. This followed a [[referendum]] held in the former Danish territories of Schleswig-Holstein regarding how the new border should be placed. This resulted in upper Schleswig becoming Danish, today known as [[Southern Jutland]], and the rest remained German.\n\n=== Current Constitution (1953) ===\nIn 1953, the [[1953 Danish constitutional and electoral age referendum|fourth constitution]] abolished the Upper Chamber (the [[Landsting (Denmark)|Landsting]]), giving Denmark a [[Unicameralism|unicameral]] parliament. It also enabled females to inherit the throne (see ''[[Danish monarchy#Succession|Succession]]''), but the change still favored boys over girls (this was changed by a [[2009 Danish Act of Succession referendum|referendum in 2009]] so the first-born inherits the throne regardless of sex). Finally, the required number of votes in favor of a change of the Constitution was decreased to the current value of 40% of the electorate.\n\nIn 2009, the [[Danish Act of Succession|Act of Succession]], which is referenced in the constitution and considered an integral part of it, was changed to  eliminate [[male-preference primogeniture]] in favour of [[absolute primogeniture]]. The changes was approved in a [[2009 Danish Act of Succession referendum|referendum]].\n\n== Summary of the constitution ==\nThe Danish constitution consists of 89 sections, structured into 11 chapters. The Folketing have published the constitution with explanatory annotations; it is available in both Danish and English through their website.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.ft.dk/~/media/sites/ft/pdf/publikationer/grundloven/min-grundlov_web.ashx|title=Min grundlov \u2013 Grundloven med forklaringer.|last=|first=|publisher=Folketinget|year=2017|isbn=87-7982-172-3|edition=14.|location=|pages=|language=Danish}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.thedanishparliament.dk/~/media/pdf/publikationer/english/my_constitutional_act_with_explanations.ashx|title=My Constitutional Act \u2013 My Constitutional Act with explanations|last=|first=|publisher=Folketinget|year=2014|isbn=978-87-7982-168-2|edition=12.|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" |Chapter\n!Sections\n!Content\n|-\n|1\n|Form of government\n|\u00a7\u00a7 1\u20134\n|Denmark is a [[constitutional monarchy]], with [[separation of powers]] into the three classic branches: the legislative, held by the [[Folketing]]; the executive held by the [[Cabinet of Denmark|government]]; and the judiciary, held by the [[Courts of Denmark|courts]]. The throne is inherited according to the [[Danish Act of Succession|Act of Succession]], which itself has the same status as the constitution. The [[Church of Denmark]] is the state church. The constitution holds for the entire [[The unity of the Realm|Danish realm]].\n|-\n|2\n|The royal family\n|\u00a7\u00a7 5\u201311\n|There are a number of requirements that the [[Monarchy of Denmark|sovereign]] must live up to, most importantly they must belong to the [[evangelical Lutheran]] faith; in practice they have always have been members of the Church of Denmark. The [[age of majority]] for the sovereign is at 18 years, and the Folketing can make provisions if the sovereign in incapable, minor or abroad, and choose a new sovereign if there are no heirs to the throne. Royal expenses are financed through [[Annuity|annuities]] granted by the Folketing.\n|-\n|3\n|The government\n|\u00a7\u00a7 12\u201327\n|The sovereign,{{Efn|The constitution refers to the sovereign as the \"King\", even though it is currently [[Margrethe II of Denmark|a queen]]. As the queen executes her powers through the government, the use of \"King\" nearly always means the government.|name=|group=lower-alpha}} who formally holds executive power, always exercises this power through the ministers in the government, making the role of sovereign fully ceremonial. Denmark employs the principle of negative [[Parliamentary system|parliamentarianism]], namely that no minister can remain in their post, if a majority of the Folketing opposes them. In addition ministers can be trialed at the Court of [[Impeachment]] (\u00a7\u00a7 59-60) for their actions while in government. Government business are discussed in the Council of State or the Council of Ministers, who today have little importance. New laws must receive [[royal assent]] and be proclaimed; this happens in ''[[Lovtidende]]''. Pre-constitutional laws remain in effect.\n\nMinisters have the right to propose laws and decision (in case they are not members of the Folketing), and the government is allowed to pardon criminals and mint coins. Under exceptional circumstances, the government can enact temporary laws, which must be reaffirmed by the Folketing as quickly as possible. In foreign policy, important decisions are taken by the Foreign Policy Committee in the Folketing, including the ratification of treaties, and the initiation of offensive military operations. A certain type of civil servants, known in Danish as ''tjenestem\u00e6nd'' (lit. servicemen), have special privileges to prevent corruption.\n\n\u00a7 20 allows Denmark to hand over [[sovereignty]] to [[intergovernmental organization]]s, which is often a requirement for joining them. This needs a [[supermajority]] of 5/6 in the Folketing, or that it is approved in a referendum.\n|-\n|4\n|Elections to the Folketing\n|\u00a7\u00a7 28\u201334\n|The Folketing consists of up to 179 members,{{Efn|The constitution says \"not more than\" 179, but the Danish election law says that exactly 179 members are elected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.retsinformation.dk/Forms/R0710.aspx?id=206576|title=LBK nr 137 af 07/02/2019|last=|first=|date=21 February 2019|website=Retsinformation|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref>|name=|group=}} of which two are elected from [[Greenland]], and two from the [[Faroe Islands]]. Elections are held at least every 4 years, with the [[Prime Minister of Denmark|Prime Minister]] able to call a [[snap election]]. Elections are direct and secret, and the voting system shall ensure [[proportional representation]]. To vote you need to be a Danish citizen not under [[legal guardian]]ship, live in Denmark, and be above the voting age. The voting age was set to 23 years in a [[1953 Danish constitutional and electoral age referendum|1953 referendum]], but has since been lowered three times, and has been 18 years since 1978. Changes to the voting age require a referendum. All eligible to vote are eligible to run for a seat in the Folketing; however the Folketing can expel members who have been convicted of a crime, if they deem that they are \"unworthy\" of their seat. Acts against the security or freedom of the Folketing is high treason.\n|-\n|5\n|The Folketing\n|\u00a7\u00a7 35\u201358\n|The business year runs from the first Tuesday in October to the first Tuesday in October the next year. After a general election and at the beginning of a new business year, all unfinished business is dropped, and the Folketing starts anew. The Folketing elects a [[Speaker of the Folketing|speaker]] and vice chairmen, both after an election and at the beginning of each business year. A business year starts with an opening speech from the prime minister.\nThe Folketing meets where the government resides, which is in [[Christiansborg Palace]]. The speaker calls the meetings, and are obliged to do so on request from the prime minister or two-fifths of the Folketing. Meetings are public accessible; closed meetings can be held, but the last time this happened was in 1924, during a [[Erik the Red's Land|conflict with Norway over Greenland]]. A [[quorum]] consists of half of the members. Every member of the Folketing can propose laws and decisions, and only they (and ministers per \u00a7 21) can do that. All bills require three [[Reading (legislature)|readings]] before being passed into law. One-third of the Folketing can demand that an otherwise passed bill should be confirmed in a referendum, though some bills, among those fiscal bills, cannot be subject of a referendum.\n\nEach year, a finance bill, which defines the state budget, needs to be passed into law for the following fiscal year (which since 1979 has followed the calendar year). A provisional appropriations bill can be passed if the finance bill is not passed in time. A budget or a supplementary appropriation act is necessary to charge taxes and spend money, though in practice the Finance Committee have been allowed to approve extra expenditures, which are then spent before being passed into law. The public accounts shall be ready six months after the fiscal year, and are audited by the State Auditors, who are appointed by the Folketing.\n\nMembers of the Folketing receive a salary, and have absolute [[freedom of speech]] within the Folketing. In addition, they have [[parliamentary immunity]], except if caught in the act, though this immunity can be lifted by the Folketing. Members are not in any way bound by pledges or what [[Party discipline|their party says]], but free to vote in any way they wish. They can ask ministers questions, who are then obliged to answer.\n\nAppointments to parliamentary committees are done through proportional representation. The Folketing appoint one or two [[ombudsman|ombudsmen]]; the Folketing have decided to only appoint one. The Folketing can establish parliamentary commissions for investigations, though this have only happened five times; usually commissions led by a judge is used instead. All taxes, state loans, and military inscriptions must be set in laws. Foreigners can only be [[Danish nationality law|naturalized by law]], and only buy real-estate as permitted by law.\n|-\n|6\n|The courts\n|\u00a7\u00a7 59\u201365\n|The courts are independent of the government, though they are regulated by law. Establishing a new court to handle a specific case is not allowed. Judges answers to no-one, and in general cannot be fired or forcefully moved to a new position, unless due to a restructuring, or by verdict from other judges. Judges above 65 years can be fired, but will receive full pay until the mandatory retirement age, which is currently 70 years. It is possible to sue public agencies. The Folketing can establish special courts to handle such cases, and their verdicts can be appealed to the [[Supreme Court (Denmark)|Supreme Court]], though none have been established. Court proceedings must be as transparent as possible, and [[lay judge]]s must be used in criminal cases.\nThe special Court of Impeachment, which decides cases against ministers, consists of the 15 most senior Supreme Court judges and an equal amount appointed by the Folketing. The appointed judges cannot be members of the Folketing themselves, and sits for 6 years but remain on cases started before the end of their term. Cases are brought before the impeachment court by the government or the Folketing. Only five impeachment cases have been held; the latest was the 1993\u20131995 case against former [[Justice Minister (Denmark)|Minister of Justice]], [[Erik Ninn-Hansen]] regarding the [[Tamil Case (Denmark)|Tamil Case]].\n|-\n|7\n|Religion\n|\u00a7\u00a7 66\u201370\n|The Church of Denmark is the state church by \u00a7 4, and the Folketing can by statue decide its constitution, but has not done so. Denmark has [[freedom of religion]], and allows all to form and join religious communities, as long as they do not impinge on \"good morals or public order\". No-one is forced to pay to religions that are not their own, so the church tax is only paid by members of the Church of Denmark. Religious observance or race does not affect people's civic and political rights and duties.\n|-\n|8\n|Citizens' rights\n|\u00a7\u00a7 71\u201385\n|No citizen can be held in detention based on their race, religion or political views, and detention can only be used if prescribed by law. People arrested need to be put before a judge within 24 hours, known in Danish as a ''grundlovsforh\u00f8r'' (lit. constitutional interrogation), which decides if the [[Remand (detention)|provisional detention]] should be continued, and this decision can always be appealed. Special rules can apply in Greenland. Detention outside the criminal system or the immigration system, say due to [[Psychiatry|mental illness]], can be brought before the courts.\nA [[search warrant]] is needed to enter private property, confiscate things, or break the [[secrecy of correspondence]], though general exemptions can be made by law. [[Eminent domain|Expropriations]] must be for the public good, with full compensation, and as allowed by law. Bills regarding expropriations can by 1/3 of the Folketing be delayed until passed again after a general election. All expropriations can be brought before the courts.\n\nDenmark have [[freedom of speech]] and [[Freedom of the press|freedom of press]], but some things, say [[Defamation|libel]] or breaking [[confidentiality]], can still be brought before a judge. [[Censorship]] is forbidden. All citizens have [[freedom of association]], but associations who use violence or other illegal means can be temporary banned by the government, while dissolution is tested in court. Dissolution of political association can always be appealed to the Supreme Court. Citizens have [[freedom of assembly]] when unarmed, though danger to public order can lead to outdoor assemblies being banned. In case of riots, the police can dissolve assemblies when it \"in the name of the King and the law\" have requested it three times. Freedom from detention, freedom of association and freedom of assembly can be restricted for military personnel.\n\nAll children have the right to free [[State school|public education]], though no duty to use it; [[Homeschooling|home schooling]] and [[private school]]s are allowed. The political system shall seek to make sure that all able to work can find a job. Those unable to support themselves have the right to public support, if they submit to the related requirements. Access to professions shall only be regulated for the public good, so [[Guild|trade guilds]] cannot regulate this themselves. Every healthy man have a duty to take part in the [[Conscription|military draft]]. There are no privileges attached to [[nobility]], and in the future, no [[fief]]s or [[fee tail]]s can be created. [[Municipality|Municipalities]] have the right to govern themselves.\n|-\n|9\n|The Faroe Islands, Greenland and Iceland\n|\u00a7\u00a7 66\u201367\n|In Denmark, the voting age for municipally elections and elections to [[Church (congregation)|congregation]] boards are the same as for general elections. In Greenland and the Faroe Island, it is decided by law.\n[[Iceland]]ic citizens, who already have rights as if they were Danish citizens, retains these rights. The background for this transitional provision is that Iceland became independent from Denmark in 1918, but, as [[Kingdom of Iceland]], remained in a [[personal union]] until 1944, when it [[1944 Icelandic constitutional referendum|became a republic]]. The 1918 [[Danish\u2013Icelandic Act of Union]] granted Icelandic citizens the same rights in Denmark as Danish citizens, and after the union was dissolved in 1944, these rights were limited to Icelandic citizens then living in Denmark.\n|-\n|10\n|Changes to the constitution\n|\u00a7 88\n|All changes to the constitution requires a majority in the Folketing twice; both before and after a general election. In addition, changes must pass a referendum, where at least 40% of all eligible voters must support the change.\n|-\n|11\n|Entry into force\n|\u00a7 89\n|The current constitution entered into force on 5 June 1953, when published in ''Lovtidende''. The [[Rigsdagen|Rigsdag]], the sitting bicameral legislative under the old constitution, remained in place until the [[1953 Danish general election|September 1953 general election]], where the [[Landstinget|Landsting]], the chamber in addition to the Folketing, was abolished.\n|}\n\n== Constitutional institutions ==\n[[File:Christiansborg Slot Copenhagen 2014 01.jpg|thumb|320x320px|[[Christiansborg Palace]], where both the government, the [[Folketing]] and the [[Supreme Court (Denmark)|Supreme Court]] resides.]]\nThe Constitution establishes Denmark as a [[Constitutional monarchy|constitutional monarcy]], where the [[Monarchy of Denmark|monarch]] serves as a [[ceremonial Head of state]]. The title of monarch is [[Hereditary monarchy|hereditary]] and passed on to the firstborn child, with [[Absolute primogeniture|equal rights for sons and daughters]].\n\nThe political system of Denmark can be described as a [[democracy]] with a [[parliamentary system]] of governance. The powers of the state is [[Separation of powers|separated]] into 3 different branches. The [[legislative branch]] held by the [[Folketing]], the [[executive branch]] held by the [[Danish Government|Danish government]], and the [[judicial branch]] held by the [[Courts of Denmark]].\n\n=== The monarchy ===\n{{Main|Monarchy of Denmark}}\nThe Danish monarch,{{efn|While the Constitution consistently refer to the monarch as the \"king\", this can also be a queen regnant. In fact, the current monarch of Denmark is [[Queen Margrethe II]].}} as the [[head of state]], holds great ''[[de jure]]'' power, but ''[[de facto]]'' only serves as a figurehead who is not interfering in politics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kongehuset.dk/en/the-royal-house/regentparret/hm-the-queen|title=HM The Queen|last=|first=|date=2016-04-07|work=The Danish Monarchy - Front Page|access-date=2018-06-20|language=en|quote=\"HM The Queen takes no part in politics and does not express any political opinions.\"}}</ref> The monarch formally holds [[executive power]] and, co-jointly with the [[Folketing]], [[legislative power]], since each new law requires [[royal assent]]. By article 12, 13 and 14, the powers vested in the monarch can only be exercised through the ministers, who are responsible for all acts, thus removing any political or legal liability from the monarch.<ref name=\":1\">Grundloven, Mikael Witte 1997 {{ISBN|87-7724-672-1}}</ref>{{efn|For this reason, when reading the Constitution, the word ''king'', in the context of exercising acts of state, is to be read as the ''Government'' (consisting of the Prime Minister and other ministers)}} The monarch appoints the ministers after advice from the [[Prime Minister of Denmark|Prime Minister]]. The Prime Minister is itself appointed after advice from the leaders of the political parties of the Folketing, a process known as a ''Queen's meeting'' ({{Lang-da|dronningerunde}}).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedanishparliament.dk/democracy/the-division-of-powers|title=The Division of Powers|last=|first=|date=|work=The Danish Parliament|access-date=2018-06-20|language=en|quote=\"The political party leaders will then advise the Queen on whom to invite to lead the negotiations to form a new Government. The person who has the support of a majority of party leaders is chosen as the chief negotiator and usually also becomes Prime Minister. In principle, the Constitutional Act gives the Queen the authority to appoint and dismiss Ministers, but she has no real political influence. In practice, it is the Prime Minister who selects Ministers, and subsequently the Queen formally appoints the Ministers recommended by the Prime Minister.\"}}</ref> The monarch and the Cabinet attend regular meetings in the [[Council of State (Denmark)|Council of State]], where royal assent is given, and the monarch is regularly briefed on the political situation by the Prime Minister and Foreign minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kongehuset.dk/en/the-royal-house/regentparret/hm-the-queen|title=HM The Queen|last=|first=|date=2016-04-07|work=The Danish Monarchy - Front Page|access-date=2018-06-20|language=en|quote=\"Additionally, The Queen is the formal Head of the Government and therefore presides over the State Council, where the Acts that have been passed by the Folketing are signed into law. The Prime Minister and the Minister of Foreign Affairs report regularly to The Queen to inform her of the latest political developments.\"}}</ref>\n\nThe Constitution requires the monarch to be a member of the [[Lutheranism|evangelical lutheran church]], though not necessary the [[Church of Denmark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thedanishparliament.dk/~/media/pdf/publikationer/english/my_constitutional_act_with_explanations.ashx|title=My Constitutional Act with explanations|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|quote=\"[the Queen] must belong to the Evangelical-Lutheran Church. However, she need  not necessarily be a member of the Evangelical- Lutheran Church of Denmark (Folkekirken).\"}}</ref>\n\n=== The government ===\n{{Main|Government of Denmark}}\nThe Government holds executive power, and is responsible for carrying out the acts of the Folketing. The Government does not have to pass a [[Vote of Confidence|vote of confidence]] before taking the seat, but any minister can be subject to a motion of no confidence. If a vote of no confidence is successfully passed against the Prime Minister, the government must resign or call a [[snap election]].\n\n=== The Folketing ===\n{{Main|Folketing}}\n[[File:Det danske parlament.jpg|thumb|240x240px|The Folketing chamber, inside Christiansborg Palace]]\nThe Folketing is the legislative branch of Denmark, and is located at [[Christiansborg Palace|Christiansborg]]. It consists of 179 members,{{efn|While the Constitution says that \"not more than\" 179 members are elected, the law concerning general elections states that exactly 179 members are elected.<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Bekendtg\u00f8relse af lov om valg til Folketinget|date=2017-12-08|url=https://www.retsinformation.dk/Forms/R0710.aspx?id=194769|volume=|issue=LBK nr 1426|pages=|quote=\"\u00a7 7. To the Folketing, a total of 179 people are chosen.\"|access-date=2018-06-20}}</ref>}} of which 2 members are elected in [[Greenland]], and 2 in the [[Faroe Islands]]. [[General election]]s is nominally held every 4 years, but the Prime Minister can at any point call a snap election. All Danish citizens over the age of 18 years who are living permanently within Denmark is eligible to vote, except those placed under [[legal guardianship]]. The same group of people is able to run for office. The electoral system is characterized as a [[party-list proportional representation]] system, with an [[election threshold]] on 2%. As a result, Denmark has a [[Multi-party system|multi-party parliamentary system]], where no single party has an absolute majority.\n\nThe session starts anew each year on the first Tuesday in October, and when interrupted by a general election; all previously unfinished business is cancelled. The Folketing then elects a [[Speaker of the Folketing|speaker]], who is responsible for convening meetings. The Folketing lay down their own [[Parliamentary procedure|rules of procedure]], subject to the requirements in the Constitution. Among those, the required [[quorum]] of 90 members of the Folketing, and the rule that every [[Bill (law)|proposed law]] requires three [[Reading (legislature)|readings]] in the Folketing, before it can be passed into law.\n\nThe Folketing also have the responsibility of holding the government accountable for the governance. The members of the Folketing does this by submitting questing to the ministers and convene them to explanatory hearings. In addition, the Folketing elect a number of ''State Auditors'' ({{Lang-da|Statsrevisorer}}), who has the responsibility to look through the public accounts, and check that everything is okay, and that the government only spend money approved by the Folketing. Furthermore, the Folketing also appoints an [[ombudsman]], who investigates wrongdoings by the public administrative authorities on behalf of the public.\n\n=== The courts ===\n{{Main|Courts of Denmark}}\nThe [[Courts of Denmark]] are independent of the other two branches. The Constitution does not stipulate how the courts are to be organized. Instead, this is regulated by statute. In the normal court system, there are 24 District Courts, High Courts and the [[Supreme Court (Denmark)|Supreme Court]]. In addition to these, there is some special courts. There are certain rights in the Constitution with respect to the judiciary system.\n\nThere is a special Court of Impeachment, which can prosecute ministers for their official acts.\n\nThe court system is [[Judicial review in Denmark|able to perform judicial review]] of laws, i.e. check [[Judicial review|if they are constitutional]]. This right is not included in the constitution, but was established by the Supreme Court in the beginning of the 20'th century, when it decided to hear cases about the constitutionally of land laws. While this right was contested in the beginning, the political system eventually accepted it. The Supreme Court have been reluctant to rules laws unconstitutional; the only time it have done so was in 1999, when it found that the [[Tvind]] law breached the principle of separations of power. Cases about the constitutionality of laws can only be initiated by people directly affected by the laws. All can do this with respect to the Danish relation to EU, because of its wide effects on society.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jyllands-posten.dk/debat/kronik/article5217123.ece/|title=Domstolene som grundlovens vogter|last=Christensen|first=Jens Peter|date=23 February 2013|work=Jyllands-Posten|access-date=26 November 2019|language=da|author-link=Jens Peter Christensen}}</ref>\n\n=== The Church of Denmark ===\n{{Main|Church of Denmark}}\nThe Evangelical-Lutheran Church of Denmark is the [[State religion|state church]] established by the Constitution. The queen have a number of duties in the Church of Denmark, and is often considered its head, but this is not a formal role in any way.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kristeligt-dagblad.dk/kirke-tro/er-dronningen-folkekirkens-overhoved|title=Er Dronningen folkekirkens overhoved?|last=Fjelstervang|first=Josefine|date=8 January 2019|work=Kristeligt Dagblad|access-date=7 December 2019|language=da}}</ref>\n\n=== The State Auditors ===\nThe state auditors are responsible for checking the public accounts. They are supported by [[Rigsrevisionen]].\n\n=== The Parliamentary Ombudsman ===\nThe Parliamentary [[Ombudsman]] is an independent institution under the Folketing, in charge of investigating and inspecting public authorities.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.dk/da/organisation/folketingets-institutioner/folketingets-ombudsmand|title=Folketingets Ombudsmand|last=|first=|date=|website=Folketinget|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> It is inspired by [[Parliamentary Ombudsman#Sweden|Swedish example]], and was established in 1955, following its inclusion in the 1953 constitution. The ombudsman is both appointed by and can be dismissed by the Folketing. The ombudsman cannot be a member of the Folketing themselves. While the constitution allows the Folketing to appoint two ombudsmen, by law it only appoints one.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Samfund,_jura_og_politik/Jura/Danmarks_statsforfatning/Folketingets_Ombudsmand|title=Folketingets Ombudsmand|last=Jensen|first=Claus Haagen|date=3 January 2015|website=Den Store Danske|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> The current ombudsman, {{As of|2019|December|df=|lc=y}}, is [[Niels Fenger]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ombudsmanden.dk/find/nyheder/alle/niels_fenger_valgt_som_ny_ombudsmand/|title=Niels Fenger valgt som ny ombudsmand|last=|first=|date=26 November 2019|work=Folketingets Ombudsmand|access-date=6 December 2019|language=da}}</ref>\n\nThe ombudsman handles 4,000-5,000 complains annually from the general public, and can also open cases on its own accord. In addition to that, the ombudsman have a monitoring division that inspects prisons, psychiatric institutions and social care homes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.ombudsmanden.dk/introduktion/|title=About the Ombudsman|last=|first=|date=|website=Folketingets Ombudsmand|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> Since 2012 it has also had a children's division.<ref name=\":8\" /> The ombudsman cannot demand any action from the administration. It can only voice criticism and make recommendations, but these carry a lot of weight, and its recommendations are usually followed by the administration.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\" />\n\n== Civil rights ==\nThe Constitution of Denmark outlines fundamental rights in sections 71\u201380. Several of these are of only limited scope and thus serve as a sort of lower bar. The [[European Convention on Human Rights]] was introduced in Denmark by law on 29 April 1992 and supplements the mentioned paragraphs.\n\n=== Personal liberty ===\n{{quote box\n| width = 20em\n| align = right\n| quote = Personal liberty shall be inviolable. No Danish subject shall in any manner whatever be deprived of his liberty because of his political or religious convictions or because of his descent.\n| source = Section 71\n}}The constitution guarantees the personal liberty. No citizen can be held in detention based on their race, religion or political views, and detention can only be used if prescribed by law. People arrested need to be put before a judge within 24 hours, known in Danish as a ''grundlovsforh\u00f8r'' (lit. constitutional interrogation), who decides if the [[Remand (detention)|provisional detention]] should be continued, and this decision can always be appealed. Special rules can apply in Greenland. Detention outside the criminal system or the immigration system, say due to [[Psychiatry|mental illness]], can be brought before the courts.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Right to property ===\nThe constitution guarantees the [[right to property]]. A [[search warrant]] is needed to enter private property, confiscate things, or break the [[secrecy of correspondence]], though general exemptions can be made by law. [[Eminent domain|Expropriations]] must be for the public good, with full compensation, and as allowed by law. Bills regarding expropriations can by 1/3 of the Folketing be delayed until passed again after a general election. All expropriations can be brought before the courts.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Freedom of speech and freedom of the press ===\n{{Further|Freedom of speech and freedom of the press in Denmark}}Denmark have [[freedom of speech]] and [[Freedom of the press|freedom of press]], but some things, say [[Defamation|libel]] or breaking [[confidentiality]], can still be brought before a judge. [[Censorship]] is forbidden. \u00a777: \"Anyone is entitled to in print, writing and speech to publish his or hers thoughts, yet under responsibility to the courts. Censorship and other preventive measures can never again be introduced.\"<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThere's widespread agreement in Danish legal theory that \u00a7 77 protects what is called \"formal freedom of speech\" (formel ytringsfrihed), meaning that one cannot be required to submit one's speech for review by authorities before publishing or otherwise disseminating it.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Danmarks Riges Grundlov med kommentarer|date=2006|publisher=Jurist- og \u00d8konomforbundets Forlag|isbn=8757411565|editor-last=Zahle|editor-first=Henrik|edition=2nd|location=[[Copenhagen]]|p=536|trans-title=Constitution of the Kingdom of Denmark with comments|oclc=466582184|ref=harv}}</ref> However, there is disagreement about whether or not \u00a7 77 covers \"material freedom of speech\" (materiel ytringsfrihed), the right to not be punished for ones speech. There is agreement that the phrasing \"under responsibility to the courts\" gives legislators some right to restrict speech, but conversely there have been several court decisions implying that some material freedom of speech does exist.{{Sfn|Zahle|2006|p=539}} The discussion is about whether the material speech has limits or not, and if so, what those limits are.{{Sfn|Zahle|2006|p=539}}<ref>See {{Harvnb|Zahle|2006|pp=539-552}} for differing perspectives on the issue.</ref>\n\n=== Freedom of association ===\nAll citizens have [[freedom of association]], but associations who use violence or other illegal means can be temporary banned by the government, while dissolution is tested in court. Dissolution of political association can always be appealed to the Supreme Court.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn 1941, during the [[Denmark in World War II|occupation by Nazi Germany]], the Rigsdag banned the [[Communist Party of Denmark|Communist Party]] through the [[Communist Law|communist law]]. The law also legalized existing interments of Danish communists, including members of the Folketing. Both the internments and the law broke rights in the constitution, but was justified by the [[Doctrine of necessity|necessity of the situation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Danmarks_geografi_og_historie/Danmarks_historie/Danmark_1849-1945/Kommunistloven_af_1941|title=Kommunistloven af 1941|last=Kjeldb\u00e6k|first=Esben|date=17 February 2015|website=Den Store Danske|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://danmarkshistorien.dk/leksikon-og-kilder/vis/materiale/kommunistinterneringerne-under-besaettelsen-1941-1945/|title=Kommunistinterneringerne under bes\u00e6ttelsen, 1941-1945|last=B\u00f8gh|first=Louise Skovholm|date=3 February 2017|website=danmarkshistorien.dk|publisher=Aarhus Universitet|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref> The Supreme Court found the law constitutional; a decision that was criticized as the Supreme Court President had been involved in its creation. The case illustrated how long Danish politicians was willing to go to ensure Danish control of law enforcement, and that democracy can be stretched to ensure its continued existence.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn addition to the communist law, on only two occasions have an association been forcefully dissolved. In 1874, the International Workers Organization, a precursor to the [[Social Democrats (Denmark)|Social Democrats]], was dissolved for being revolutionary, and in 1924, the organization Nekkab was dissolved for being a meeting place for [[Homosexuality|homosexuals]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kristeligt-dagblad.dk/historie/det-har-aldrig-vaeret-let-lukke-foreninger|title=Det har aldrig v\u00e6ret let at lukke foreninger|last=Mikkelsen|first=Morten|date=2 May 2016|work=Kristeligt Dagblad|access-date=26 November 2019|language=da}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.berlingske.dk/samfund/er-loyal-to-familia-en-voldelig-forening-forstaa-forbudssagen-mod-ltf|title=Er Loyal to Familia en voldelig forening? Forst\u00e5 forbudssagen mod LTF|last=Lingren|first=Daniel|date=10 May 2019|work=Berlingske|access-date=26 November 2019|language=da}}</ref> In 2020, the gang [[Loyal to Familia]] was dissolved by the Copenhagen City Court; a judgment that has been appealed. The gang was temporarily banned in 2018, and the court case \u2013 the first dissolution case against a criminal gang \u2013 was initiated.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nyheder.tv2.dk/krimi/2020-01-24-banden-loyal-to-familia-oploeses|title=Banden Loyal to Familia opl\u00f8ses|last=S\u00f8ndberg|first=Astrid|date=24 January 2020|work=TV 2|access-date=24 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Jensen|first2=Marie}}</ref> Prior to this, it has been investigated if [[Hells Angels]], [[Bandidos Motorcycle Club|Bandidos]] and [[Hizb ut-Tahrir]] could be banned, but the conclusions was that it would be difficult to win the cases.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/indland/rigsadvokaten-siger-ok-et-forbud-mod-loyal-familia-er-paa-vej|title=Rigsadvokaten siger ok: Et forbud mod Loyal to Familia er p\u00e5 vej|last=Toft|first=Emma|date=2 November 2017|work=DR|access-date=26 November 2019|language=da}}</ref>\n\n=== Freedom of assembly ===\nCitizens have [[freedom of assembly]] when unarmed, though danger to public order can lead to outdoor assemblies being banned. In case of riots, the police can dissolve assemblies when it \"in the name of the King and the law\" have requested it three times.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Freedom of religion ===\n\nSection 4 establishes that the [[Church of Denmark|Evangelical Lutheran Church]] is \"the people's church\" ({{lang|da|folkekirken}}), and as such is [[state religion|supported by the state]]. Freedom of religion is granted in section 67, and official discrimination based on faith is forbidden in section 70.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Other rights ===\nAll children have the right to free [[State school|public education]], though no duty to use it; [[Homeschooling|home schooling]] and [[private school]]s are allowed. The political system shall seek to make sure that all able to work can find a job. Those unable to support themselves have the right to public support, if they submit to the related requirements. Access to professions shall only be regulated for the public good, so [[Guild|trade guilds]] cannot regulate this themselves.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== Other themes ==\n\n=== National sovereignty ===\nSection 20 of the current constitution establishes that the delegation of specified parts of national sovereignty to international authorities requires either a 5/6 majority in Parliament or an ordinary majority in both Parliament and the electorate. This section has been debated heavily in connection with Denmark's membership of the [[European Union]] (EU), as critics hold that changing governments have violated the Constitution by surrendering too much power.\n\nIn 1996, Prime Minister [[Poul Nyrup Rasmussen]] was sued by twelve [[Eurosceptics]] for violating this section. The [[Supreme Court of Denmark|Supreme Court]] acquitted Rasmussen (and thereby earlier governments dating back to 1972) but reaffirmed that there are limits to how much sovereignty can be surrendered. In 2011, Prime Ministers [[Lars L\u00f8kke Rasmussen]] faced a similar challenge when he was sued by twenty-eight citizens for having adopted the European [[Lisbon Treaty]] without a referendum. The group of professors, actors, writers and Eurosceptic politicians argued that the Lisbon Treaty hands over parts of national sovereignty to the EU and therefore a referendum should have taken place.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pop|first1=Valentina|title=Danish PM sued over Lisbon Treaty|url=https://euobserver.com/political/31622|accessdate=14 April 2016|publisher=[[EUobserver]]|date=11 January 2011|location=Brussels}}</ref> The case was later dismissed.\n\nSection 20 was used in 1972 when Denmark, after a [[1972 Danish European Communities membership referendum|referendum]], joined the [[European Economic Community|EEC]] (now [[European Union|EU]]). More recently, in 2015 an (unsuccessful) [[2015 Danish European Union opt-out referendum|referendum]] was held on one of its EU-opt-outs.\n\n===Greenland and the Faroe Islands===\n{{See also|The unity of the Realm}}\nSection 32 states \"special rules may be provided by Statute for the commencement and determination of Faroe Islands and Greenland representation in the Parliament.\"<ref name=\"Act\" /> This section refers to [[home rule]] in both territories. The specific arrangements for the transfer of powers and monetary competency to Greenland and the Faroe Islands are contained in separate statues, with equal constitutional status (see below).\n\n===Separation of powers===\n{{See also|Separation of powers}}\n\nDenmark have [[separation of powers]] into the three classic branches: the legislative, held by the [[Folketing]]; the executive held by the [[Cabinet of Denmark|government]]; and the judiciary, held by the [[Courts of Denmark|courts]]. The separation of powers is described in the constitution, and is there, as in many democracies, to prevent abuse of power. The Folketing enact laws, and the government implements them. The courts make judgments in disputes, either between citizens, or between authorities and citizens.<ref name=\"danishparliament\" />\n\nThe Constitution is heavily influenced by the French philosopher [[Montesquieu]],{{citation needed|date=April 2016}} whose separation of powers was aimed at achieving mutual monitoring of each of the branches of government. However, the division between legislative and executive power in Denmark is not as sharp as in the [[United States]].\n\nIn 1999, the Supreme Court found that the [[Tvind]] law, a law that barred specific schools from receiving public funding, was unconstitutional, because it breached the concept of separation of powers by settling a concrete dispute between the Tvind schools and the government. The judgment is the only time the courts have found a law to be unconstitutional.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/indland/historisk-tvind-dom|title=Historisk Tvind-dom|last=|first=|date=19 February 1999|work=DR|access-date=26 November 2019|language=da}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Samfund,_jura_og_politik/Jura/Enkelte_navngivne_retssager/Tvind-dommen|title=Tvind-dommen|last=L.|first=Mads|date=|website=Den Store Danske|language=da|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary power===\nIn several sections the Constitutional Act sets out the powers and duties of the Danish Parliament. Section 15 in the Act, which deals with\nthe parliamentary principle, lays down that \"a Minister shall not remain in office after the Parliament has passed a vote of no confidence in him\".<ref name=\"Act\" /> This suggests that Ministers are accountable to Parliament and even subservient to it. The Cabinet exerts executive power through its Ministers, but cannot remain in office if the majority of the Folketing goes against it. Another important feature of the Danish parliamentary system is that the Constitutional Act lays down that \"the Members of the Folketing shall be elected for a period of four years\", but still, \"the King may at any time issue writs for a new election\".<ref name=\"danishparliament\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Politics|Denmark|Faroe Islands}}\n*[[Codified constitution]]\n*[[Constitutional economics]]\n*[[Constitutionalism]]\n*[[Constitutional law]]\n*[[Index of Denmark-related articles]]\n*[[Politics of Denmark]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisourcepar|Constitutional Act of Denmark, 5 June 1953}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121120170200/http://www.thedanishparliament.dk/Democracy/The_Constitutional_Act_of_Denmark.aspx The Constitutional Act of Denmark] - The Danish Parliament\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140714134738/http://pub.uvm.dk/2008/democracycanon/kap20.html The Constitutional Act of the Kingdom of Denmark] - Ministry of Education of Denmark\n\n{{Constitution of Europe}}\n{{Denmark topics}}\n{{Faroe Islands topics}}\n{{Greenland topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Constitution Of Denmark}}\n[[Category:1849 in law]]\n[[Category:Government of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Legal history of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Politics of Denmark]]\n[[Category:History of the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:History of Greenland]]\n[[Category:Politics of Greenland]]\n[[Category:Danish law| ]]\n[[Category:1849 in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Constitution of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Kingdom of Denmark]]\n[[Category:June 1849 events]]\n", "name_user": "BALMAINM", "label": "safe", "comment": "dK kingdom", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constitution_of_the_Kingdom_of_Denmark"}
{"title_page": "Rory Barrett", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand weightlifter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Rory Barrett\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = New Zealand\n| sport          = [[Olympic weightlifting|Weightlifting]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1945|12|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Mumbai]], India\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''John Rory Barrett''' (born 31 December 1945) is a New Zealand [[Olympic weightlifting|weightlifter]]. He competed in the [[Weightlifting at the 1976 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 110 kg|men's heavyweight event]] at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ba/rory-barrett-1.html |title=Rory Barrett Olympic Results |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1974 New Zealand British Commonwealth Games team}}\n{{1976 New Zealand Olympic team |state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrett, Rory}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male weightlifters]]\n[[Category:Olympic weightlifters of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Weightlifters at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Mumbai]]\n{{NewZealand-weightlifting-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|New Zealand weightlifter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Rory Barrett\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = New Zealand\n| sport          = [[Olympic weightlifting|Weightlifting]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1945|12|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Mumbai]], India\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''John Rory Barrett''' (born 31 December 1945) is a New Zealand [[Olympic weightlifting|weightlifter]]. He competed in the [[Weightlifting at the 1976 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 110 kg|men's heavyweight event]] at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ba/rory-barrett-1.html |title=Rory Barrett Olympic Results |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1974 New Zealand British Commonwealth Games team}}\n{{1976 New Zealand Olympic team |state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrett, Rory}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male weightlifters]]\n[[Category:Olympic weightlifters of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Weightlifters at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Mumbai]]\n{{NewZealand-weightlifting-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rory_Barrett"}
{"title_page": "Jussi Huttunen", "text_new": "Professor '''Jussi Kalervo Huttunen''' (born 1941 in Helsinki) is a physician (1966 University of Helsinki), scientist, and former director general of the [[National Public Health Institute of Finland]] (1978-2003).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ktl.fi/attachments/english/english-vk.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929011544/http://www.ktl.fi/attachments/english/english-vk.pdf |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ktl.fi/portal/english/ktl/organization/annual_reviews/annual_review_2003/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929011600/http://www.ktl.fi/portal/english/ktl/organization/annual_reviews/annual_review_2003/ |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is an internist by training, and served as associate professor of internal medicine at the [[University of Kuopio]] 1975\u20131978. As the first director general of the reformed (1982) National Public Health Institute he guided the institute from previously routine microbiological and clinical chemistry laboratory to an internationally recognized research institute in public health.<ref>[http://terho.thl.fi/wiki01/pages/viewpageattachments.action?pageId=49513&highlight=ktl-evaluaatio-95.pdf#Julkaistuja+arviointeja+Kansanterveyslaitoksesta-attachment-ktl-evaluaatio-95.pdf International Evaluations]</ref>\n\nThroughout his career Huttunen has been involved in many different organisations, and he has been a well-known health care expert often consulted by the government as well as by international and local authorities. He served as an acting director general and department chief at the Ministry of Social Welfare and Health (2000-2001).<ref name=SITRA>{{cite web |url=http://www.sitra.fi/en/Media/articles/release_2006-03-17.htm |title=Jussi Huttunen: Money and health |author=Jussi Huttunen |publisher=[[SITRA]] |accessdate=August 12, 2011 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20071228115619/http://www.sitra.fi/en/Media/articles/release_2006-03-17.htm |archive-date=December 28, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> One of the longest activities is in the Finnish Medical Association Duodecim: he acted several years as editor of its journal Duodecim, and in several positions in the activities including presidency of the Association (1996-1999). He has also been president of the Finnish Diabetes Research Foundation (1985-1991), Finnish Cancer Research Foundation (1989-1990), Finnish Cancer Association (1992-1995), and Finnish Heart Association (1998-2003), among others. International assignments include presidency of the Governing Council of the [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]] (IARC, 1990-1992), Nordic Cancer Union (1991), and vice presidency of a committee evaluating the Framework Programs of the European Union (2008).<ref>[http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/jrc/downloads/jrc_eval_report_2008_09_expost_fp6.pdf Framework Programmes]</ref> He has belonged to editorial boards of several international scientific journals and was editor of Annals of Clinical Research (1984-1989).\n\nHuttunen started his research career as medical biochemist, and presented his dissertation for doctor of medical sciences degree on sugar metabolism (1966). Subsequently, his interests have been in important national diseases such as cardiovascular diseases and diabetes, as well as nutrition. Even as director general he was actively involved in epidemiological studies on cardiovascular and metabolic diseases. He has also been concerned on great health differences between social groups.<ref>[http://www.suomi-yhtio.fi/_InEnglish/Releases/Medical+Award+Granted+to+Jussi+Huttunen.htm Challenges in healthcare]</ref> He holds honorary doctorate in medicine from the University of Kuopio (2000)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uef.fi/promootio/kunniatohtorit-1978-2005 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002034915/http://www.uef.fi/promootio/kunniatohtorit-1978-2005 |archive-date=2011-10-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and many other honours.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thl.fi/en_US/web/en National Institute for Health and Welfare]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huttunen, Jussi}}\n[[Category:Finnish public health doctors]]\n[[Category:People from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n", "text_old": "Professor '''Jussi Kalervo Huttunen''' (born 1941 in Helsinki) is a physician (1966 University of Helsinki), scientist, and former director general of the [[National Public Health Institute of Finland]] (1978-2003).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ktl.fi/attachments/english/english-vk.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929011544/http://www.ktl.fi/attachments/english/english-vk.pdf |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ktl.fi/portal/english/ktl/organization/annual_reviews/annual_review_2003/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929011600/http://www.ktl.fi/portal/english/ktl/organization/annual_reviews/annual_review_2003/ |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is an internist by training, and served as associate professor of internal medicine at the [[University of Kuopio]] 1975-1978. As the first director general of the reformed (1982) National Public Health Institute he guided the institute from previously routine microbiological and clinical chemistry laboratory to an internationally recognized research institute in public health.<ref>[http://terho.thl.fi/wiki01/pages/viewpageattachments.action?pageId=49513&highlight=ktl-evaluaatio-95.pdf#Julkaistuja+arviointeja+Kansanterveyslaitoksesta-attachment-ktl-evaluaatio-95.pdf International Evaluations]</ref>\n\nThroughout his career Huttunen has been involved in many different organisations, and he has been a well-known health care expert often consulted by the government as well as by international and local authorities. He served as an acting director general and department chief at the Ministry of Social Welfare and Health (2000-2001).<ref name=SITRA>{{cite web |url=http://www.sitra.fi/en/Media/articles/release_2006-03-17.htm |title=Jussi Huttunen: Money and health |author=Jussi Huttunen |publisher=[[SITRA]] |accessdate=August 12, 2011 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20071228115619/http://www.sitra.fi/en/Media/articles/release_2006-03-17.htm |archive-date=December 28, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> One of the longest activities is in the Finnish Medical Association Duodecim: he acted several years as editor of its journal Duodecim, and in several positions in the activities including presidency of the Association (1996-1999). He has also been president of the Finnish Diabetes Research Foundation (1985-1991), Finnish Cancer Research Foundation (1989-1990), Finnish Cancer Association (1992-1995), and Finnish Heart Association (1998-2003), among others. International assignments include presidency of the Governing Council of the [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]] (IARC, 1990-1992), Nordic Cancer Union (1991), and vice presidency of a committee evaluating the Framework Programs of the European Union (2008).<ref>[http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/jrc/downloads/jrc_eval_report_2008_09_expost_fp6.pdf Framework Programmes]</ref> He has belonged to editorial boards of several international scientific journals and was editor of Annals of Clinical Research (1984-1989).\n\nHuttunen started his research career as medical biochemist, and presented his dissertation for doctor of medical sciences degree on sugar metabolism (1966). Subsequently, his interests have been in important national diseases such as cardiovascular diseases and diabetes, as well as nutrition. Even as director general he was actively involved in epidemiological studies on cardiovascular and metabolic diseases. He has also been concerned on great health differences between social groups.<ref>[http://www.suomi-yhtio.fi/_InEnglish/Releases/Medical+Award+Granted+to+Jussi+Huttunen.htm Challenges in healthcare]</ref> He holds honorary doctorate in medicine from the University of Kuopio (2000)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uef.fi/promootio/kunniatohtorit-1978-2005 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002034915/http://www.uef.fi/promootio/kunniatohtorit-1978-2005 |archive-date=2011-10-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and many other honours.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thl.fi/en_US/web/en National Institute for Health and Welfare]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huttunen, Jussi}}\n[[Category:Finnish public health doctors]]\n[[Category:People from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1975-1978 \u2192 1975\u20131978", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jussi_Huttunen"}
{"title_page": "Stephen Duneier", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               =  Stephen Duneier\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              =  Stephen_Duneier,_CEO_Bija_Advisors.png\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         =  <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         =  {{Birth-date and age|July 1967}}\n| birth_place        = [[Brooklyn]], New York<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cooper|first1=Arnie|title=HEDGE FUNDER-TURNED-CROCHETER 'YARNBOMBS' THE COUNTRY'S WILDERNESS|url=http://www.artnews.com/2014/11/18/steve-duneier-yarnbombs/|accessdate=December 9, 2015|issue=November 2014|publisher=ArtNews Magazine|date=November 2014}}</ref>\n| baptised           =  <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| disappeared_date   =  <!-- {{disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place  = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_date         =  <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| burial_place       =  <!-- may be used instead of resting_place and resting_place_coordinates - displays \"Burial place\" as label -->\n| burial_coordinates =  <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments          = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| citizenship        = \n| education          = [[MBA]] in finance and economics\n| alma_mater         = [[New York University]], [[Stern School of Business]]\n| occupation         = Founder and CEO of Bija Advisors LLC, Lecturer at [[University of California]], Artist, Author\n| years_active       = \n| era                = \n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| agent              =  <!-- Discouraged in most cases, specifically when promotional, and requiring a reliable source -->\n| known_for          = Incorporating [[Cognitive Science]] with [[Investment Management]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Greenberg|first1=Greg|title=Powerless Fed Can't Stop Stocks From Heading Higher, Says Bija CIO|url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/13188471/1/what-does-cognitive-science-have-to-do-with-investing-lots-says-stephen-duneier.html|accessdate=December 9, 2015|publisher=The Street|date=June 16, 2015}}</ref> [[Yarnbombing]] in the Wilderness,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dinaberg|first1=Leslie|title=The Art of Getting People Back to Nature|url=http://sbseasons.com/2015/06/yarnbomber-stephen-duneier/|accessdate=December 9, 2015|publisher=SB Seasons|date=June 16, 2015}}</ref> Extreme Goal Achievement\n| notable_works      =  <!-- produces label \"Notable work\"; may be overridden by |credits=, which produces label \"Notable credit(s)\"; or by |works=, which produces label \"Works\" -->\n| style              = \n| home_town          = \n| salary             = \n| net_worth          =  <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height             =  <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| weight             =  <!-- \"X kg\", \"X lb\" or \"X st Y lb\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| television         = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| movement           = \n| opponents          = \n| boards             = \n| religion           =  <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| denomination       =  <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| criminal_charge    =  <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    = \n| spouse             =  Barbara\n| partner            =  <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| callsign           = \n| awards             = \n| website            =  {{URL|BijaAdvisorsLLC.com}}, {{URL|Yarnbomber.com}}, {{URL|TheLPE.com}}\n| module             = \n| module2            = \n| module3            = \n| module4            = \n| module5            = \n| module6            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_size     = \n| signature_alt      = \n| footnotes          = \n| ethnicity          =  <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n}}\n'''Stephen Duneier''' is an American professional investment manager, strategy consultant, speaker, lecturer, author, artist and Guinness World Record holder.\n\n==Education==\nDuneier attended the [[University of Florida]] from 1985 to 1987 before leaving to pursue a career in financial management with [[Drexel Burnham Lambert]] and then [[Prudential-Bache]]. He finished his undergraduate education at [[Florida Atlantic University]] with a BBA in finance and economics and received an [[MBA]] in finance and economics from [[New York University]]'s [[Stern School of Business]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CEO, Stephen Duneier|url=http://www.bijaadvisorsllc.com/ceo-stephen-duneier.html|website=Bija Advisors LLC|publisher=Bija Advisors LLC|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career in Finance==\nWhile still attending graduate school at [[NYU]], Duneier worked as a foreign exchange option trader specializing in exotic derivatives at [[Credit Suisse]] in New York City. He was later hired by [[Bank of America]] to expand their foreign exchange business into European crosses and [[Emerging Markets]] and eventually promoted to Global Head of Currency Option Trading. Soon after Bank of America merged with Nations Bank, Duneier moved to AIG International where he was eventually named managing director in charge of Emerging Markets trading and based out of London, England. In 2002, Duneier launched a proprietary trading portfolio known as \"TIP\" for AIG International.<ref>{{cite web|title=Creation of Additional Incubator Fund|url=http://www.investegate.co.uk/sgam-a-i--starway-fd/rns/creation-of-additional-incuba/200809021630065818C/|website=FE Investegate|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> Shortly after the firm merged with Banque AIG, Duneier became a global macro portfolio manager at London Diversified Fund Management in London and later at Peloton Partners in [[Santa Barbara, California]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Drobny|first1=Andres|title=Drobny Global Monitor|url=http://www.drobny.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Conference-Review-Santa-Monica-2009-19.pdf|website=Drobny|publisher=Drobny Global|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> In 2008, he was one of the founding partners at Grant Capital Partners<ref>{{cite web|title=Alternative Investment News|url=http://www.strandfund.com/images/Alternative_Investment_News_October_2008.pdf|website=Strand Fund|publisher=Total Alternatives|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> which grew to $1.25&nbsp;billion in assets under management.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Friedman|first1=Steven|title=Stephen Duneier; Bija Advisors|url=https://www.santangelsreview.com/stephen-duneier-bija-advisors/|website=Santangels Review|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> He left in 2012 to launch Bija Capital Management and eventually Bija Advisors LLC, a consulting firm which advises experienced hedge fund managers, CIO's and asset allocators. Through Bija Advisors, he speaks on and publishes a subscription based newsletter covering topics on economics,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Xie|first1=Ye|title=Dollar Turning Point Aided by U.S. Investor Reversal: Currencies|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-10-20/dollar-turning-point-aided-by-u-s-investor-reversal-currencies|accessdate=December 9, 2015|publisher=Bloomberg|date=October 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lloyd|first1=Colin|title=Will Europe Benefit Economically from the Migrant Crisis|url=http://www.nasdaq.com/article/will-europe-benefit-economically-from-the-migrant-crisis-cm524368|accessdate=December 9, 2015|agency=Seeking Alpha|publisher=Nasdaq|date=September 25, 2015}}</ref> cognitive science,<ref>{{cite web|title=Cognitive science exposes a serious mistake made by most asset allocators|url=http://2n20.com/opinion-cognitive-science-exposes-a-serious-mistake-made-by-most-asset-allocators/|website=2n20.com|publisher=2n20 AG|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> and investment management.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chen|first1=Vivian|title=AUM's Impact on Performance|url=http://www.pmjar.com/?p=1589|website=PM Jar|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Duneier|first1=Stephen|title=Declawing the Federal Reserve|url=http://advisorhubinc.com/declawing-of-the-federal-reserve-2/|accessdate=December 9, 2015|publisher=Advisor Hub|date=July 9, 2015}}</ref> Duneier's book, ''AlphaBrain'' is due for release in early 2019 (Wiley & Sons).\n\n==Career as a cognitive science practitioner==\nIn 2001, Duneier began to apply his approach to decision making, which he calls \"Bija\", to his personal life, leading to a long string of eccentric goals and resolutions being set and achieved.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Secret to Successful New Year's Resolutions|url=http://www.bijaadvisorsllc.com/the-secret-to-successful-new-years-resolutions.html|website=Bija Advisors LLC|publisher=Bija Advisors LLC|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> In 2012, it reached fever pitch when he embarked upon 12 for 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=12 for 2012|url=http://12for2012.com/|website=12for2012|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> a New Year's resolution which included 12 Learning Resolutions and 12 Giving Resolutions.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burgess|first1=Phil|title=Bonus Years: New year is good time to commit to new learning and giving|url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/lifestyle/health/ph-ac-cl-bonus-1227-20151227-story.html|accessdate=December 28, 2015|publisher=Capital Gazette|date=December 27, 2015}}</ref> As part of his resolutions, he has performed at [[comedy clubs]]; learned to fly a [[helicopter]]; climbed iced waterfalls; raced cars; had [[root canal]] without anesthetic; learned to speak German; read 50 books in 52 weeks;<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mills|first1=Ted|title=Episode 24: The Yarnbomber|url=http://www.funkzonepodcast.com/?p=251|website=Funkzone Podcast|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> participated in the Pier to Peak [[half marathon]]; learned to [[unicycle]]; used [[jumping stilts]] to hike; fostered a [[pit bull]]; built homes for families in [[Arizona]]; learned [[ballroom dancing]], how to drum, [[slackline]], [[parkour]], [[skydive]]; and flown planes acrobatically.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nHe set the Guinness World Record for the largest crocheted [[granny square]]. It is 1,311 square feet, incorporates more than 30 miles of yarn and weighs over 60 pounds. It took  2 years, 7 months and 17 days to create, and required more than 500,000 double crochet stitches.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yarnbomber Achieves World Record for Largest Granny Square|url=http://blog.redheart.com/world-record-granny-square-achieved/|website=Heart Strings by Red Heart Yarns|publisher=Red Heart|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Vercillo|first1=Kathryn|title=5 Shockingly Humongous Crochet Blankets|url=http://crochet.about.com/od/crochetcommunity/tp/5-Shockingly-Humongous-Crochet-Blankets.htm|website=About.com|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=World Record Attempt|url=http://www.yarnbomber.com/world-record-attempt.html|website=Yarnbomber.com|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/Account/Login?ReturnUrl=%2fsearch%2fapplicationrecordsearch%3fterm%3d%2522largest%2bcrochet%2bsquare%2522%26contentType%3drecord&term=%22largest+crochet+square%22&contentType=record|title=Sign in|website=Guinness World Records|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\nDuneier now speaks<ref>{{cite web|title=Speaker Inspires Monroe Students|url=https://www.sbunified.org/2015/03/13/speaker-inspires-monroe-students/|website=Santa Barbara Unified|publisher=Santa Barbara Unified School District|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> and writes about his experience and how others can take what we have learned from research conducted in the field of [[cognitive science]] in order to make better decisions and achieve bigger goals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Volunteer Spotlight: Stephen Duneier|url=http://youthinteractive.tumblr.com/post/113980039096/volunteer-spotlight-stephen-duneier|website=Youth Interactive|publisher=Youth Interactive|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career as a Lecturer==\nDuneier teaches undergraduate and graduate level courses on [[Decision Analysis]] in the College of Engineering at the [[University of California in Santa Barbara]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lecturers|url=http://www.tmp.ucsb.edu/about/lecturers/stephen-duneier|website=Technology Management Program, UCSB|publisher=University of California|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cold Spring Yarnbomb Installation by Stephen Duneier.JPG|thumb|40 ft tall eucalyptus tree 2.6 miles up the Cold Spring Trail wrapped with yarn.]]\n\n==Career as an Artist==\nDuneier is an [[installation artist]], part of the fiber-art movement known as [[Yarnbombing]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rogan|first1=Jack|title=The Yarnbomber|url=https://rootsrated.com/stories/yarnbomber|accessdate=December 9, 2015|publisher=Roots Rated|date=April 9, 2014}}</ref> His installations exist for just 9 days typically in [[Los Padres National Forest]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About Yarnbomber|url=http://www.yarnbomber.com/about.html|website=Yarnbomber.com|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs part of his 2012 resolution to learn 12 new skills, Duneier learned how to knit. His first project was the covering of a 40-foot tall eucalyptus tree, 2.6 miles up the Cold Spring Trail in [[Santa Barbara, California]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hemmons|first1=Jessie|title=Interview with Yarnbomber Stephen Duneier|url=http://www.ishknits.com/interview-with-yarnbomber-stephen-duneier/|website=IshKnits.com|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> It required 450 square feet of knitted material. The installation remained for just 9 days and all material used was donated to Warm Up America, a charity in [[North Carolina]].\n\nThe following year he wrapped a massive boulder atop the Saddlerock hiking trail above [[Montecito, California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hiking Saddlerock|url=http://www.santabarbaracompany.com/blogs/blog/11914285-hiking-saddlerock|website=The Santa Barbara Company|publisher=The Santa Barbara Company|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> [[File:Saddlerock Yarnbomb by Stephen Duneier.jpg|thumb|Photo of the 2013 yarnbomb installation by Stephen Duneier atop Saddlerock in the mountains above Montecito California.]]\n\nHis third installation was a large spiderweb made out of yarn which covered Sasquatch Cave in The Playgrounds at Lizard's Mouth. [[File:Spiderweb Yarnbomb Installation by Stephen Duneier.JPG|thumb|Sasquatch Cave at Lizards Mouth in Santa Barbara California]]\n\nFor his fourth installation, Duneier created a giant starfish made with reflective yarn from Red Heart Yarns and hung it 40 feet above the Seven Falls Trail. [[File:Starfish Yarnbomb Installation by Stephen Duneier.jpg|thumb|Seven Falls Trail in the mountains of Santa Barbara California]]\n\nHis fifth installation occurred at [[Santa Barbara City College]] where he laid out nearly 2,500 square feet of knitted and crocheted pieces on their lawn. [[File:SBCC Yarnbomb by Stephen Duneier.PNG|thumb|2,500 square feet of knitted and crocheted material laid out at SBCC in Santa Barbara.]]\n\n[[File:Lizards Mouth Yarnbomb by Stephen Duneier.jpg|thumb|18 massive boulders wrapped with yarn at Lizard's Mouth in Los Padres National Forest above Santa Barbara, CA.]]\n\nFor his sixth installation, he invited fiber artists from around the world to collaborate with him by sending crocheted and knitted pieces of any size, shape, color and style to participate. He received contributions from 388 artists in 36 countries and all 50 US States. Combined with his own work, he wrapped 18 giant boulders at Lizards Mouth<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lehr|first1=Tracy|title=Knitter Creates Unusual Art|url=http://www.keyt.com/news/knitter-creates-unusual-art/26378886|accessdate=December 9, 2015|publisher=KEYT KCOY|date=June 6, 2014}}</ref> in the [[Los Padres National Forest]] above [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]] in California.\n[[File:Alien Campsite yarnbomb installation by Stephen Duneier.jpg|thumb|10 aliens and 24 tents covered with yarn line the canyon at Davey Brown Trailhead above Santa Ynez in California.]]\nHis most recent project was called the Alien Campsite<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stewart|first1=Ethan|title=The Santa Barbara YarnBomber Strikes Again, But Gets Foiled by Mother Nature|url=https://rootsrated.com/stories/the-santa-barbara-yarnbomber-strikes-gets-foiled-mother-nature|website=Roots Rated|publisher=Roots Rated|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> where he incorporated additional materials including [[fiberglass]], wood, and metal in addition to [[yarn]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Alien Campsite|url=http://blog.redheart.com/alien-campsite/|website=Heart Strings|publisher=Red Heart Yarns|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> He created 10 aliens and 24 tents for the installation which lasted just 36 hours before being ripped apart by high winds in the canyon. The installation was permitted by the [[US Forest Service]] for the area just below the Davey Brown Trailhead. It incorporated Duneier's own work plus contributions from 656 fiber artists from 41 countries and all 50 states.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cooper|first1=Arnie|title=The Guerrilla Art of the Yarn Bomb Goes Natural|url=http://www.newsweek.com/guerilla-art-yarn-bomb-goes-natural-312069|accessdate=December 9, 2015|publisher=Newsweek Magazine|date=March 8, 2015}}</ref> \nDuneier's work is represented by the Sullivan Goss Gallery.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stewart|first1=Ethan|title=Knitting Psychedelic Daydreams|url=http://www.independent.com/news/2014/sep/11/knitting-psychedelic-day-dreams/|accessdate=December 9, 2015|publisher=The Santa Barbara Independent|date=September 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs part of his stated mission to build a global community kind and creative people,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Jordana|title=Ultimate Yarn Bomber: Steve Duneier|url=http://textileartscenter.com/blog/ultimate-yarn-bomber-steve-duneier/|website=Textile Arts Center|publisher=Textile Arts Center|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> Duneier hosts the Yarnbomber podcast in which he features interviews with famous yarnbombers from around the world including Carol Hummel, London Kaye and Jessie Hemmons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yarnbomber Podcast|url=https://itunes.apple.com/tc/podcast/yarnbomber-podcast/id1016663275|website=iTunes|publisher=Apple|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cognitive bias]]\n*[[Land art]]\n*[[Site-Specific Art]]\n*[[Environmental art]]\n*[[Decision Analysis]]\n*[[B\u012bja|Bija]]\n*[[Yarnbombing]]\n*[[Fiber art]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://BijaAdvisorsLLC.com Official Website of Bija Advisors LLC]\n* [http://yarnbomber.com Official Website of Yarnbomber Stephen Duneier]\n* [http://12for2012.com 2012 New Year's Resolution Blog]\n* [http://TheLPE.com Official Website of The League of Professional Educators]\n* [http://www.tmp.ucsb.edu/about/lecturers/stephen-duneier University of California Santa Barbara TMP Website]\n\n{{Instecon}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duneier, Stephen}}\n