{"title_page": "Susan Hunter", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand swimmer}}\n{{for|the American academic|Susan J. Hunter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{use New Zealand English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Susan Hunter\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nationality    = \n| strokes        = \n| club           = \n| collegeteam    = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1955|10|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n\n'''Susan Hunter''' (born 5 October 1955) is a New Zealand [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]]. She competed at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1976 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/hu/susan-hunter-1.html |title=Susan Hunter Olympic Results |accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1970 New Zealand British Commonwealth Games team}}\n{{1972 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{1974 New Zealand British Commonwealth Games team}}\n{{1976 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Susan}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1974 British Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Swimmers from Christchurch]]\n{{NewZealand-swimming-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|New Zealand swimmer}}\n{{for|the American academic|Susan J. Hunter}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{use New Zealand English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Susan Hunter\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nationality    = \n| strokes        = \n| club           = \n| collegeteam    = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1955|10|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n\n'''Susan Hunter''' (born 5 October 1955) is a New Zealand [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]]. She competed at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1976 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/hu/susan-hunter-1.html |title=Susan Hunter Olympic Results |accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1970 New Zealand British Commonwealth Games team}}\n{{1972 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{1974 New Zealand British Commonwealth Games team}}\n{{1976 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Susan}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1974 British Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Swimmers from Christchurch]]\n{{NewZealand-swimming-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Susan_Hunter"}
{"title_page": "The Earl of Essex (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1922 film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Earl of Essex \n| image          = The Earl of Essex (film).jpg\n| caption        = Eugen Kl\u00f6pfer as Essex\n| director       = [[Peter Paul Felner]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Peter Paul Felner]]|[[Louis Rokos]]}}\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Eugen Kl\u00f6pfer]]|[[Fritz Kortner]]|[[Werner Krauss]]|[[Eva May]]}}\n| music          = \n| editing        = \n| cinematography = {{ubl|[[Karl Hasselmann]]|[[Fritz Stein]]|[[Fritz Arno Wagner]]}}\n| studio         = [[National Film]]\n| distributor    = \n| released       = 14 September 1922 \n| runtime        = \n| country        = Germany\n| language       = {{ubl|[[Silent film|Silent]]|[[German language|German]] intertitles}}\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n'''''The Earl of Essex''''' ({{lang-de|'''Der Graf von Essex'''}}) is a 1922 [[Cinema of Germany|German]] [[silent film|silent]] [[historical film]] directed by [[Peter Paul Felner]] and starring [[Eugen Kl\u00f6pfer]], [[Fritz Kortner]] and [[Werner Krauss]]. It was loosely based on the 1761 play ''[[Der Graf von Essex (play)|Der Graf von Essex]]'' by [[Peter von St\u00fcven]] set in [[Elizabethan era|Elizabethan England]] and based in turn on the 1678 work ''[[Le Comte d'Essex]]'' by [[Thomas Corneille]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Eugen Kl\u00f6pfer]] - [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex|Graf Essex]]\n* [[Fritz Kortner]] - [[Charles Howard, 1st Earl of Nottingham|Lord Nottingham]]\n* [[Werner Krauss]]\n* [[Friedrich K\u00fchne]] - [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Cecil]]\n* [[Eva May]] - Lady Rutland\n* [[Erna Morena]] - [[Catherine Carey, Countess of Nottingham|Lady Nottingham]]\n* [[Charles Puffy]] - Cuff\n* [[Magnus Stifter]] - [[Henry Wriothesley, 3rd Earl of Southampton|Lord Southampton]]\n* [[Agnes Straub]]  - [[Queen Elisabeth I]]\n* [[Rosa Valetti]]\n* [[Ferdinand von Alten]] - [[Walter Raleigh|Raleigh]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Bergfelder, Tim & Bock, Hans-Michael. ''The Concise Cinegraph: Encyclopedia of German. Berghahn Books, 2009.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0013199}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Earl of Essex}}\n[[Category:1922 films]]\n[[Category:1920s historical films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:Films of the Weimar Republic]]\n[[Category:German historical films]]\n[[Category:German silent feature films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Paul Felner]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:German films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 16th century]]\n[[Category:National Film films]]\n[[Category:German black-and-white films]]\n{{1920s-Germany-film-stub}}\n{{historic-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1922 film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Earl of Essex \n| image          = The Earl of Essex (film).jpg\n| caption        = Eugen Kl\u00f6pfer as Essex\n| director       = [[Peter Paul Felner]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Peter Paul Felner]]|[[Louis Rokos]]}}\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Eugen Kl\u00f6pfer]]|[[Fritz Kortner]]|[[Werner Krauss]]|[[Eva May]]}}\n| music          = \n| editing        = \n| cinematography = {{ubl|[[Karl Hasselmann]]|[[Fritz Stein]]|[[Fritz Arno Wagner]]}}\n| studio         = [[National Film]]\n| distributor    = \n| released       = 14 September 1922 \n| runtime        = \n| country        = Germany\n| language       = {{ubl|[[Silent film|Silent]]|[[German language|German]] intertitles}}\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n'''''The Earl of Essex''''' ({{lang-de|'''Der Graf von Essex'''}}) is a 1922 [[Cinema of Germany|German]] [[silent film|silent]] [[historical film]] directed by [[Peter Paul Felner]] and starring [[Eugen Kl\u00f6pfer]], [[Fritz Kortner]] and [[Werner Krauss]]. It was loosely based on the 1761 play ''[[Der Graf von Essex (play)|Der Graf von Essex]]'' by [[Peter von St\u00fcven]] set in [[Elizabethan era|Elizabethan England]] and based in turn on the 1678 work ''[[Le Comte d'Essex]]'' by [[Thomas Corneille]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Eugen Kl\u00f6pfer]] - Graf Essex\n* [[Fritz Kortner]] - Lord Nottingham\n* [[Werner Krauss]]\n* [[Friedrich K\u00fchne]] - [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Cecil]]\n* [[Eva May]] - Lady Rutland\n* [[Erna Morena]] - Lady Nottingham\n* [[Charles Puffy]] - Cuff\n* [[Magnus Stifter]] - Lord Southampton\n* [[Agnes Straub]]  - [[Queen Elisabeth I]]\n* [[Rosa Valetti]]\n* [[Ferdinand von Alten]] - [[Walter Raleigh|Raleigh]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Bergfelder, Tim & Bock, Hans-Michael. ''The Concise Cinegraph: Encyclopedia of German. Berghahn Books, 2009.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0013199}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Earl of Essex}}\n[[Category:1922 films]]\n[[Category:1920s historical films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:Films of the Weimar Republic]]\n[[Category:German historical films]]\n[[Category:German silent feature films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Paul Felner]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:German films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 16th century]]\n[[Category:National Film films]]\n[[Category:German black-and-white films]]\n{{1920s-Germany-film-stub}}\n{{historic-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast:add links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Earl_of_Essex_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Economic Freedom Fighters", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use South African English|date=December 2015}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Economic Freedom Fighters\n| logo = Logo of the EFF.png\n| colorcode = {{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}\n| abbreviation = EFF\n| president = [[Julius Malema]]\n| chairperson = [[Veronica Mente]]\n| secretary_general = [[Marshall Dlamini]]\n| spokesperson = [[Vuyani Pambo]]\n| leader1_title = Deputy President\n| leader1_name = [[Floyd Shivambu]]\n| leader2_title = Deputy Secretary-General\n| leader2_name = Poppy Mailola\n| leader3_title = Treasurer-General\n| leader3_name = [[Omphile Maotwe]]\n| founder = Julius Malema\n| founded = {{Start date|df=yes|2013|07|26}}\n| dissolved = <!--{{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| split = [[African National Congress]]\n| headquarters = 82 De Korte Street,<br>[[Johannesburg]]\n| newspaper =\n| student_wing = [[EFF Students Command]] (EFFSC)\n| youth_wing =\n| ideology = {{Nowrap|[[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/economicfreedomstruggle|title=EFF|accessdate=24 February 2016|via=Facebook|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105041413/https://www.facebook.com/economicfreedomstruggle|archivedate=5 January 2018}}</ref><ref>https://www.effonline.org/constitution</ref><br>[[Left-wing populism]]<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Times of India]]|title=ANC holds onto power in South Africa as other parties increase vote share|date=11 May 2018|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/rest-of-world/anc-holds-onto-power-in-south-africa-as-other-parties-increase-vote-share/articleshow/69278436.cms}}</ref><br>[[Pan-Africanism]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kwinika |first1=Savious |title=South Africa: Pan-African EFF Makes Most of Rival Parties' Squabbles |url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201903180741.html |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=allAfrica |date=18 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><br>[[Anti-capitalism]]<ref name=\"aji\">{{cite web|url=http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201310142026-0023110|title=Economic Freedom Fighters Party reignites debate (in English)|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=14 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102192705/http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201310142026-0023110|archivedate=2 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"n24i\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Hundreds-gather-for-EFF-launch-20131013|title=Hundreds gather for EFF launch (in English)|publisher=[[News24]]|date=13 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104124450/http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Hundreds-gather-for-EFF-launch-20131013|archivedate=4 November 2013}}</ref><br>[[Anti-imperialism]]<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://effonline.org/about-us/ |publisher=Economic Freedom Fighters |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref><br>[[Racism in South Africa#Racism against white people|Anti-white sentiment]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Campbell|first=John|year=2016|title=Morning in South Africa|publisher=Indiana University Press|page=187|quotation=Often explicitly '''antiwhite''' in its rhetoric, it [the EFF] would expropriate without compensation white-owned property...}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Megan|year=2016|title=Performing Whitely in the Postcolony: Afrikaners in South African Theatrical and Public Life|publisher=University of Iowa Press|page=62|quotation=Several events added fuel to the fire: the increasing popularity of Julius Malema's '''antiwhite''' political party, the Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF) ...}}</ref>}}\n| position = {{nowrap|[[Far-left politics|Far-left]]<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-safrica-politics-malema/south-africas-malema-says-more-than-60-anc-mps-will-turn-on-zuma-idUSKBN1A61AP South Africa's Malema says more than 60 ANC MPs will turn on Zuma]. ''Reuters''. Authors - Ed Stoddard and Sisipho Skweyiya. Published 21 July 2017. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=eti_DgAAQBAJ&pg=PA66&dq=Far-left+Economic+Freedom+Fighters&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4ooLL96raAhWJalAKHTa0AMAQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Social Changes in a Global World'']. p.66. Author - Ulrike Schuerkens. Published by SAGE. Published in London in 2017. Accessed via Google Books.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9MZODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA535&lpg=PA535&dq=Far-left+Economic+Freedom+Fighters&source=bl&ots=HZyA_KTESl&sig=agvCpZ2_jS7zZKdYQolUvHnm0Xs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEl5ew96raAhVSPsAKHSM8C7A4PBDoAQhgMAk#v=onepage&q=Far-left%20Economic%20Freedom%20Fighters&f=false ''The World Since 1945: An International History'']. p.535. 2nd edition. Authors - P. M. H. Bell and Mark Gilbert. Published by Bloomsbury in London. First published in 2001, 2nd edition in 2017.</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/chaos-in-parliament-as-party-gets-ejected-for-grilling-zuma-over-corruption-in-south-africa-10043286.html Chaos in parliament as party gets ejected for grilling Zuma over corruption in South Africa]. ''Independent''. Author - Lamiat Sabin. Published 13 February 2015. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref>}}\n| international =\n| colours = [[Red]]<ref name=\"aji\"/><ref name=\"n24i\"/><ref name=\"dmi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-10-14-red-tide-from-economic-freedom-to-white-genocide-extremism-grabs-the-spotlight/#.UnQCyhb1DoF|title=Red Tide: From 'economic freedom' to 'white genocide', extremism grabs the spotlight (in English)|publisher=[[Daily Maverick]]|date=14 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017020415/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-10-14-red-tide-from-economic-freedom-to-white-genocide-extremism-grabs-the-spotlight/#.UnQCyhb1DoF|archivedate=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n| slogan = \"Our land and jobs, now!\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Daniel |first1=Luke |title=EFF manifesto launch 2019: Five main talking points |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/eff-manifesto-launch-2019-talking-points/ |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The South African |date=2 February 2019}}</ref>\n| seats1_title = [[National Assembly of South Africa|National Assembly]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|44|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[National Council of Provinces]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|11|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = {{nowrap|[[Pan-African Parliament]]}}\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|1|5|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}<small>(South African seats)</small>\n| seats4_title = [[Provincial legislature (South Africa)|Provincial Legislatures]]\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|50|430|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[City of Johannesburg Metropolitan Municipality]] (council)\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|30|270|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| seats6_title = [[Nelson Mandela Bay Metropolitan Municipality]] (council)\n| seats6 = {{Composition bar|6|120|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| seats7_title = [[City of Cape Town]] (council)\n| seats7 = {{Composition bar|7|231|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| flag =\n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| country = South Africa\n}}\n\nThe '''Economic Freedom Fighters''' ('''EFF''') is a [[South Africa]]n [[Far-left politics|far-left]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/southAfricaNews/idAFL5N1V80N0|title=South Africa's opposition EFF introduces bill to nationalise...|date=17 August 2018|work=Reuters|access-date=23 March 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref>[http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201408222154-0024098 South African lawmakers disrupt parliament and demand Zuma #PayBackTheMoney]. ''AlJazeera''. Published 22 August 2014. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.radionz.co.nz/news/world/266026/south-african-parliament-descends-into-chaos South African parliament descends into chaos]. ''Radio New Zealand''. Published 13 February 2015. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref> [[Pan-Africanism|Pan-Africanist]] [[political party]]. It was founded by expelled former [[African National Congress Youth League]] (ANCYL) President [[Julius Malema]], and his allies, in 2013.<ref name=\"Dispatch\">{{cite news|title=Malema launches his Economic Freedom Fighters|author=Meggan Saville|url=http://www.dispatch.co.za/malema-launches-his-economic-freedom-fighters/|newspaper=Dispatch Online|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725200305/http://www.dispatch.co.za/malema-launches-his-economic-freedom-fighters/|archivedate=25 July 2013}}</ref> Malema is President of the EFF, heading the Central Command Team which serves as the central structure of the party.<ref name=\"BD\">{{cite news|title=Malema takes command of Economic Freedom Fighters|author=Setumo Stone|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/11/malema-takes-command-of-economic-freedom-fighters|newspaper=[[Business Day (South Africa)|Business Day]]|date=11 July 2013|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130714113641/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/11/malema-takes-command-of-economic-freedom-fighters|archivedate=14 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt is currently the third-largest party in both houses of the [[Parliament of South Africa|South African Parliament]].\n\n==History==\nAt a 26 July 2013 press briefing in [[Soweto]], Malema announced that the new party had over 1000 members, double the 500 required for registration with the [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|Independent Electoral Commission]] (IEC).<ref name=\"EFF 1000\">{{cite news|title=EFF readies for election registration as over 1 000 members recruited|author=SAPA|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2013/07/28/eff-readies-for-election-registration-as-over-1-000-members-recruited|newspaper=[[The Times (South Africa)|The Times]]|date=28 July 2013|accessdate=28 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730092849/http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2013/07/28/eff-readies-for-election-registration-as-over-1-000-members-recruited|archivedate=30 July 2013}}</ref> The EFF is now registered with the IEC, after an objection to its registration by the [[Freedom Front Plus]] (FF+) was dismissed in September 2013.<ref name=\"It'sOfficial\">{{cite news|title=It's official: Malema's EFF is a political party|author=Verashni Pillay|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-09-05-malemas-eff-to-contest-2014-elections|newspaper=[[Mail & Guardian]]|date=5 September 2013|accessdate=5 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130907063401/http://mg.co.za/article/2013-09-05-malemas-eff-to-contest-2014-elections|archivedate=7 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Splinters and infighting==\nIn 2015, the EFF suspended [[Member of parliament|MP]] Lucky Twala and expelled three MPs, Mpho Ramakatsa, Andile Mngxitama and [[Khanyisile Litchfield-Tshabalala]].<ref name=m.news24.com>{{cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Litchfield-Tshabalala-UDMs-new-national-organiser-20150605|title=Litchfield-Tshabalala UDM's new national organiser|author=Genevieve Quintal|date=5 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930022925/http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Litchfield-Tshabalala-UDMs-new-national-organiser-20150605|archivedate=30 September 2015}}</ref> Mngxitama formed his own party, named [[Black First Land First]] (BLF), while Litchfield-Tshabalala joined the [[United Democratic Movement]].{{CN|date=March 2019}}\nMalema has been chiefly accused by former members of purging his critics to consolidate his power, thus ruling the party with an iron fist. Malema acknowledged this criticism in a press conference and further went on to say, the party should have expelled more ill disciplined members.\n\n==Policies==\n[[File:EFF land march on Mandela Day 2014.JPG|thumb|A small march by the EFF on Mandela Day (18 July) 2014 near the parliament building in [[Cape Town]] protesting in support of [[land reform in South Africa]].]]\nThe EFF \"draws inspiration from the broad [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist\u2013Leninist]] tradition and [[Frantz Fanon|Fanonian]] schools of thought in their analyses of the state, imperialism, culture and class contradictions in every society\", according to one of its declarations.<ref name=\"ml\">{{cite web|url=https://www.effonline.org/declaration|title=Declaration|work=effonline.org}}</ref>\n\nIt criticises the [[African National Congress]] and their primary opposition, the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]], for their allegedly pro-business stances, which it claims have sold out the black people of South Africa to capitalism as cheap labour. It promises to tackle corruption, provide quality social housing, and provide free primary healthcare and education for all, as well as proposing to [[expropriation|expropriate]] stolen land, nationalise the mining and banking sectors, double welfare grants and the minimum wage, and end the proposed toll system for highways.<ref name=\"irishtimes\"/>\n\nThe EFF takes significant inspiration from [[Thomas Sankara]] in terms of both style and ideology.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|last=Duval Smith|first=Alex|date=30 April 2014|title='Africa's Che Guevara': Thomas Sankara's legacy|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-27219307|newspaper=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|location=[[London]]|accessdate=5 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101053949/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-27219307|archivedate=1 November 2014}}</ref> In a May 2014 column, the prominent EFF member Jackie Shandu declared his party a \"proudly [[Sankarism|Sankarist]] formation\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Shandu|first=Jackie|date=22 May 2014|title=The Sankarist makings of the EFF|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2014-05-22-the-sankarist-makings-of-eff/#.VFqe0d186rX|newspaper=[[Daily Maverick]]|location=[[Johannesburg]]|accessdate=5 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106000454/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2014-05-22-the-sankarist-makings-of-eff/#.VFqe0d186rX|archivedate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF has been vocal in its criticism of black business owners and black owners of mining companies in South Africa. In an address at the [[Oxford Union]] in November 2015, Malema spoke out against billionaire mining company owner Patrice Motsepe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2015/11/26/effs-malema-takes-aim-at-sellout-black-billionaires-in-oxford-address|title=Business Day|website=www.bdlive.co.za|access-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229135821/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2015/11/26/effs-malema-takes-aim-at-sellout-black-billionaires-in-oxford-address|archivedate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2016/05/01/Patrice-Motsepe-has-no-power%E2%80%9A-says-Malema|title=Patrice Motsepe has no power\u201a says Malema|last=Jordaan|first=Buchule Raba And Nomahlubi|website=Times LIVE|access-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127215142/http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2016/05/01/Patrice-Motsepe-has-no-power%E2%80%9A-says-Malema|archivedate=27 November 2016}}</ref> Further protests in 2015, the EFF delivered demands that included the socialization of the mining sector and called for more explicit targets for the 26% BEE ownership required by law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2015-11-01-yes-and-no-to-effs-list-of-demands|title=Yes and no to EFF\u2019s list of demands|last=John|first=Victoria|newspaper=The M&G Online|access-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128050240/http://mg.co.za/article/2015-11-01-yes-and-no-to-effs-list-of-demands|archivedate=28 November 2016}}</ref>  The EFF is a vocal proponent of expanding the role of [[State-owned enterprises of South Africa|South African state owned enterprises]] in the country's economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techfinancials.co.za/2019/02/03/eff-wants-state-to-create-ai-robotics-and-biotechnology-firms/|title=EFF Wants State To Create AI, Robotics And BioTechnology Firms|last=Lourie|first=Gugu|date=3 February 2019|website=TechFinancials|language=en-ZA|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/the-effs-2019-election-manifesto-iv|title=The EFF`s 2019 election manifesto (IV) - DOCUMENTS {{!}} Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nMalema addressed a crowd in Marikana, Rustenburg in the platinum mining area, blaming mining companies and calling out platinum mining company Lonmin in particular, for poverty in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/bdd0ce804d689dfe9d42df4b5facb1b5/Malema-blames-mining-companies-for-high-levels-of-poverty-20160707|title=SABC News - Malema blames mining companies for high levels of poverty:Thursday 7 July 2016|last=Tatai|first=Sello|website=www.sabc.co.za|access-date=27 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127232029/http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/bdd0ce804d689dfe9d42df4b5facb1b5/Malema-blames-mining-companies-for-high-levels-of-poverty-20160707|archivedate=27 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe party supports the re-introduction of the [[Capital punishment in South Africa|death penalty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.iafrica.com/sa/883240.html|title=iafrica.com Juju wants death penalty|website=News.iafrica.com|accessdate=19 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901181605/http://news.iafrica.com/sa/883240.html|archivedate=1 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economicfreedomfighters.org/malema-wants-death-penalty-efflaunch/|title=Malema wants death penalty #EFFlaunch &#124; Economic Freedom Fighters - EFF|publisher=Economic Freedom Fighters|date=13 October 2013|accessdate=19 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126014743/http://www.economicfreedomfighters.org/malema-wants-death-penalty-efflaunch/|archivedate=26 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, after [[2016 South African municipal elections|local elections]] in South Africa, the EFF has suggested that they will back the Democratic Alliance in hung-metro areas, but would not be entering into a coalition with any political party in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2016-08-17-malema-says-the-eff-wont-form-coalitions-but-will-support-da-in-hung-metros|title=Malema says the EFF won't form coalitions, but will support DA in hung metros|last=Feltham|first=Luke|newspaper=The M&G Online|access-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128050103/http://mg.co.za/article/2016-08-17-malema-says-the-eff-wont-form-coalitions-but-will-support-da-in-hung-metros|archivedate=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was the only parliamentary party that opposed the 2018 political party funding bill.<ref name=\"citizenFundingRejectionReasons\">https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1871025/reasons-why-the-eff-rejects-the-political-party-funding-bill/</ref>\n\n==High-profile members==\nHigh-profile members of the Central Command Team include [[Floyd Shivambu]], [[Fana Mokoena]] and [[Mbuyiseni Ndlozi]] (National Spokesperson).<ref name=\"EFF Central Command\">{{cite web|author=Economic Freedom Fighters|title=Central Command Team|url=http://www.effonline.org/structure|publisher=effonline.org|accessdate=21 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812200344/http://effighters.org.za/structure/officials/|archivedate=12 August 2013}}</ref> Controversial businessman [[Kenny Kunene]] joined the Central Command Team in July 2013 before resigning from the Central Command Team on 20 August 2013 and from the organisation on 26 August 2013.<ref name=\"Sushi\">{{cite news|title='Sushi King' quits EFF leadership|author=Poloko Tau|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/sushi-king-quits-eff-leadership-1.1565564#.UhhxMWthiSM|newspaper=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Independent Online]]|date=21 August 2013|accessdate=24 August 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824143456/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/sushi-king-quits-eff-leadership-1.1565564#.UhhxMWthiSM|archivedate=24 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ExitKunene\">{{cite news|title=Kunene quits EFF|author=[[South African Press Association|SAPA]]|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Kunene-quits-EFF-20130826|newspaper=[[News24]]|date=26 August 2013|accessdate=5 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829084845/http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Kunene-quits-EFF-20130826|archivedate=29 August 2013}}</ref> On 4 November 2013, it was announced that [[Dali Mpofu]] had left the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) after 33 years of membership and joined the EFF.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/dali-mpofu-joins-eff-1.1601553#.UoctTNKmimg|title=Dali Mpofu joins EFF - Cape Times|publisher=IOL.co.za|date=4 November 2013|accessdate=23 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202233822/http://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/dali-mpofu-joins-eff-1.1601553#.UoctTNKmimg|archivedate=2 December 2013}}</ref> Musician and actress [[Ntando Duma]] also publicly pledged allegiance to EFF in February 2019.\n\n==Support base==\nAccording to a November 2013 [[Ipsos]] survey, the party's supporters are younger than average, with 49% being younger than 24, overwhelmingly black (99%) and mostly male, with women representing only 33% of the support base. A disproportionate number of supporters live in Malema's home province of [[Limpopo]] (28%), while only 1% live in [[KwaZulu-Natal]], a more populous province.<ref name=ipsos>{{cite web|title=The supporter profiles of SA`s three largest parties|url=http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politicsweb/view/politicsweb/en/page72308?oid=534039&sn=Marketingweb+detail&pid=90389|publisher=Politicsweb|accessdate=6 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222022154/http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politicsweb/view/politicsweb/en/page72308?oid=534039&sn=Marketingweb+detail&pid=90389|archivedate=22 February 2014}}</ref> A 2018 survey conducted by social research company Citizen Surveys found that around 70% of EFF supporters were between the ages of 18 to 34, overwhelmingly black (97%), mostly based in major metropolitan cities (48%), predominantly male (62%) with 43% of their support base located in [[Gauteng|Gauteng Province]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizensurveys.net/citizen-surveys-how-many-white-eff-supporters-exist-and-11-other-stats/|title=Citizen Surveys: How many white EFF supporters exist, and 11 other stats|last=|first=|date=1 November 2018|website=Citizen Surveys|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe party was expected to make an impact in the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general election]], taking between 4 per cent and 8 per cent of the national vote. This was potentially enough for the party to hold [[Balance of power (parliament)|the balance of power]] in provinces where the governing African National Congress was in danger of losing its absolute majority.<ref name=\"irishtimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/africa/economic-freedom-fighters-on-rise-in-south-africa-1.1779028|title=Economic Freedom Fighters on rise in South Africa|date=1 May 2014|accessdate=6 May 2014|newspaper=The Irish Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506162746/http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/africa/economic-freedom-fighters-on-rise-in-south-africa-1.1779028|archivedate=6 May 2014}}</ref> The ANC retained is absolute majority whilst the EFF got 6.35% of the vote in the 2014 election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/Elections/News/ANC-wins-249-seats-20140510|title=ANC wins 249 seats|last=|first=|date=12 May 2014|website=News24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512215131/http://www.news24.com/Elections/News/ANC-wins-249-seats-20140510|archive-date=12 May 2014|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n===National elections===\n====National Assembly====\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Total votes\n!Share of vote\n!Seats \n!+/\u2013\n!Government\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]<ref name=\"IEC 2014 election results\">{{Cite web|title=2014 National and Provincial Elections Results - 2014 National and Provincial Election Results|url=http://www.elections.org.za/resultsNPE2014/|publisher=IEC|accessdate=11 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140510231542/http://www.elections.org.za/resultsNPE2014/|archivedate=10 May 2014}}</ref>\n|1,169,259\n|6.35%\n|{{Composition bar|25|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 25\n|{{no2|in opposition}}\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|1,881,521\n|10.79%\n|{{Composition bar|44|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 19\n|{{no2|in opposition}}\n|}\n\n====National Council of Provinces====\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Total # of<br/>seats won\n!+/\u2013\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]\n|{{Composition bar|7|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 7\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|{{Composition bar|11|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 4\n|}\n\n===Municipal elections===\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n![[2016 South African municipal elections|2016]]<ref name=\"iec_summary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.org.za/content/LGEPublicReports/402/Detailed%20Results/National.pdf|title=Results Summary - All Ballots|publisher=elections.org.za|accessdate=11 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808191111/http://www.elections.org.za/content/LGEPublicReports/402/Detailed%20Results/National.pdf|archivedate=8 August 2016}}</ref>\n|3,202,679\n|8.31%\n|-\n|}\n\n===Provincial elections===\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n!rowspan=2|Election<br><ref name=\"IEC 2014 election results\"/><ref name=\"dash\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elections.org.za/NPEDashboard/app/dashboard.html|title=Results Dashboard|website=www.elections.org.za|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n!colspan=2|[[Eastern Cape]]\n!colspan=2|[[Free State (province)|Free State]]\n!colspan=2|[[Gauteng]]\n!colspan=2|[[KwaZulu-Natal|Kwazulu-Natal]]\n!colspan=2|[[Limpopo]]\n!colspan=2|[[Mpumalanga]]\n!colspan=2|[[North West (South African province)|North-West]]\n!colspan=2|[[Northern Cape]]\n!colspan=2|[[Western Cape]]\n|- \n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]\n|3.48%||2/63\n|8.15%||2/30\n|10.30%||8/73\n|1.85%||2/80\n|10.74%||6/49\n|6.26%||2/30\n|13.21%||5/33\n|4.96%||2/30\n|2.11%||1/42\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|7.84%||5/63\n|12.58%||4/30\n|14.69%||11/73\n|9.71%||8/80\n|14.43%||7/49\n|12.79%||4/30\n|18.36%||6/33\n|9.71%||3/30\n|4.04%||2/42\n|}\n\n==Achievements==\nOn 6 August 2015 the EFF announced that it has secured a Constitutional court case for its [[Jacob Zuma]] campaign of \"#PayBackTheMoney\". The case was heard on 9 February 2016. The Judgement was released by Chief Justice Mogoeng Mogoeng. The judgement stated that The President has violated the Constitution of South Africa, along with the [[Speaker of the National Assembly of South Africa|Speaker of the National Assembly]] [[Baleka Mbete]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} The President was given 60 days to fulfill the requirements of the Public Protector [[Thuli Madonsela]].<ref name=\"ZumaConCourt\">{{cite news|title=Lets meet in court, Malema tells Zuma|author=Emsie Ferreira|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/lets-meet-in-court-malema-tells-zuma-1896636|date=6 August 2015|accessdate=26 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201155340/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/lets-meet-in-court-malema-tells-zuma-1896636|archivedate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February 2018 the EFF tabled a motion in The National Assembly to amend the Constitution so as to allow for the expropriation of land without compensation. The motion, brought by the EFF leader [[Julius Malema]], was adopted with a vote of 241 in support, and 83 against. The only parties who did not support the motion were the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]], [[Freedom Front Plus]], [[Cope]] and the [[African Christian Democratic Party|ACDP]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} Land Expropriation is one of the EFF's Seven cardinal pillars.<ref name=\"LandExpropriation\">{{cite news|title=National Assembly adopts motion on land expropriation without compensation|author=Jan Gerber|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-national-assembly-adopts-motion-on-land-expropriation-without-compensation-20180227|date=27 February 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920012156/https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-national-assembly-adopts-motion-on-land-expropriation-without-compensation-20180227|archivedate=20 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the student wing of the EFF, the EFF Student Command won many universities across the country. The red berets defeated the ANC-aligned [[South African Students Congress]] (Sasco) at the [[Durban University of Technology]], the [[University of Zululand]] and [[Mangosuthu University of Technology]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} They also won in Cape Town, the District Six, Mowbray and Bellville [[Cape Peninsula University of Technology]] (CPUT) campuses with landslide victories, meaning they now are in charge of the institution's SRC. They also won the [[University of Cape Town]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} Peter Keetse, president of the EFFSC, said the win was a warning shot for what was going to happen in 2019 national general elections. He said the youth were the influencers of the future, \u201ctherefore, this is an indication of what is to follow\u201d.<ref name=\"EFFStudentCommand\">{{cite news|title=Comrades see red as students back EFF on campus|author=Kwandokuhle Njoli|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sunday-tribune/news/comrades-see-red-as-students-back-eff-on-campus-17275465|date=30 September 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms and controversies==\nThe ANC has accused the Zimbabwean ruling party, the [[ZANU\u2013PF|Zimbabwe African National Union \u2013 Patriotic Front]] (ZANU\u2013PF), of supporting the EFF in order to destabilise the ANC.<ref name=\"bdliveMantashe\">{{cite news|title=Mantashe hits out at EFF for 'distorting the Freedom Charter'|author=Natasha Marrian|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/29/mantashe-hits-out-at-eff-for-distorting-the-freedom-charter|newspaper=Business Day|date=29 July 2013|accessdate=30 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801072713/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/29/mantashe-hits-out-at-eff-for-distorting-the-freedom-charter|archivedate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, a group of 17 former EFF members and councillors in the [[Northern Cape]] accused the party's senior leadership of corruption and sexual exploitation of more junior female party members.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2019199/expelled-eff-members-accuse-malema-shivambu-of-corruption-want-to-work-with-hawks/|title=Expelled EFF members accuse Malema, Shivambu of corruption, want to work with Hawks|last=reporter|first=Citizen|date=7 October 2018|work=The Citizen|access-date=13 October 2018|language=en}}</ref>  Four months later two former female employees of the EFF claimed that party leadership intimidated and engaged in acts of bullying behaviour towards them and other party staff members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://city-press.news24.com/News/more-women-make-claims-of-eff-bullying-and-abuse-20190216|title=More women make claims of EFF bullying and abuse|last=Peter|first=Zamayirha|date=16 February 2019|website=CityPress|language=en|access-date=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 a former member of the EFF's central command, Thembinkosi Rawula, accused senior party leaders of dictatorial leadership practices and of using party finances for personal benefit.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/disgruntled-eff-member-slams-malema-shivambu-for-taking-vbs-donation-party-denies-claims-20190405|title=Former EFF leader accuses Malema, Shivambu of taking VBS donation, party denies claims|last=Lizeka Tandwa and Tshidi Madia|date=5 April 2019|website=News24|language=en|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref> The EFF denied Rawula's accusation and stated that they would sue him for defamation as well as make the party's financials public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/malema-to-sue-rawula-offers-journalists-access-to-effs-financial-records-20190410|title=Malema to sue Rawula, offers journalists access to EFF's financial records|last=Tandwa|first=Lizeka|date=10 April 2019|website=News24|language=en|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was found guilty of [[Defamation|defamation of character]] in May 2019 by the South Gauteng High Court and ordered to pay R500,000 in damages to former Finance Minister [[Trevor Manuel]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-05-30-court-finds-effs-comments-about-trevor-manuel-defamatory-and-false/|title=Court vindicates Trevor Manuel in defamation battle with EFF|last=Quintal|first=Genevieve|date=30 May 2019|website=BusinessLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref> Manuel brought the EFF and its leader, Julius Malema, to court after they alleged that the appointment of Edward Kieswetter as commissioner of SARS by Manuel was the result of nepotism.<ref name=\":4\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/14/challenge-me-don-t-defame-manuel-to-eff-in-kieswetter-matter|title=Challenge me, don't defame - Manuel to EFF in Kieswetter nepotism matter|last=Modise|first=Kgomotso|website=ewn.co.za|language=en|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref>  Following the judgement Manuel stated that he would be donating the R500,000 in damages to victims of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters#VBS Mutual Bank|VBS Mutual Bank scandal]] which the EFF is alleged to have participated in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fin24.com/Economy/trevor-manuel-i-dont-need-a-cent-of-eff-money-20190531-2|title=Trevor Manuel: I don't need a cent of EFF money|last=Khumalo|first=Sibongile|date=31 May 2019|website=Fin24|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref>  \n\nFollowing a string of court case losses for inciting supporters to commit acts of either intimidation (against Karima Brown), land invasion ([[AfriForum]]) or of defamation of character (against Trevor Manuel) the party was left with combined court costs amounting to almost R1 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/courts/2144536/eff-wallows-in-legal-debt-of-almost-r1m/|title=EFF wallows in legal debt of almost R1m|last=Watson|first=Amanda|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref>  \n\n===Alleged Corruption===\n\n==== Tenders ====\nA number of articles published by investigative journalists have accused the party of using their influence to earn improper payments from government suppliers in cities where the EFF has significant representative power.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2185034/malema-and-eff-get-r15m-in-kickbacks-in-tshwane-fuel-scandal-report/|title=Malema and EFF get R15m in \u2018kickbacks\u2019 in Tshwane fuel scandal \u2013 report|last=|first=|date=|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>  An investigation by the [[amaBhungane]] centre for investigative journalism stated that the EFF received R500,000 in kickbacks from a company in return for a R1.26 billion contract to manage a fleet of vehicles used by the [[City of Johannesburg Metropolitan Municipality|City of Johannesburg]] with tacit acquiescence of the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amabhungane.org/stories/firm-that-won-r1bn-joburg-fleet-contract-paid-malema-eff-slush-fund/|title=Firm that won R1bn Jo'burg fleet contract paid Malema-EFF 'slush-fund' - amaBhungane|last=Micah Reddy and Stefaans Br\u00fcmmer|date=29 November 2018|website=amabhungane.org|language=en-ZA|access-date=29 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amabhungane.org/stories/tender-comrades-part-1-trailing-the-juju-tractor/|title=Tender comrades part 1: Trailing the Juju tractor|website=amaBhungane|language=en-US|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref> Another investigation alleges that the party improperly benefited from the awarding of a fuel supply contract for the [[City of Tshwane Metropolitan Municipality|City of Tshwane]] netting the party R15 million from successful contractors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-29-tender-comrades-part-two-tshwane-tenderpreneurs-r15m-eff-tithe/|title=AMABHUNGANE: Tender Comrades Part Two: Tshwane tenderpreneur\u2019s R15m \u2018EFF tithe\u2019|last=amaBhungane|first=Stefaans Brummer & Micah Reddy for|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n====VBS Mutual Bank====\n{{See also|VBS Mutual Bank}}\nFollowing the publication of a [[South African Reserve Bank]] report<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.resbank.co.za/Lists/News%20and%20Publications/Attachments/8830/VBS%20Mutual%20Bank%20-%20The%20Great%20Bank%20Heist.pdf|title=The Great Bank Heist: Investigator's Report to the Prudential Authority|last=Motau|first=Terry|date=10 October 2018|website=South African Reserve Bank|page=135|access-date=11 October 2018}}</ref> into the collapse of [[VBS Mutual Bank]] implicating EFF deputy president Floyd Shivambu's brother media reports came out alleging that Shivambu received R10 million in illicit payments from VBS prior to it being placed under [[Receivership|curatorship]] in March 2018.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-10-11-the-shivambu-brothers-and-the-great-vbs-heist/|title=The Shivambu Brothers and the Great VBS Heist|last=Van Wyk|first=Pauli|date=11 October 2018|work=[[Daily Maverick]]|access-date=11 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-10-12-00-pic-vbs-floyd-and-his-baby-brother|title=PIC, VBS, Floyd and his baby brother|last=Jika|first=Sabelo Skiti, Thanduxolo|date=12 October 2018|work=The M&G Online|access-date=13 October 2018}}</ref> Prior to the publication of the Reserve Bank's report the EFF criticised the Reserve Bank for placing VBS under curatorship and accused it of victimising VBS on racial grounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.effonline.org/single-post/2018/03/11/EFF-STATEMENT-ON-VBS-CURATORSHIP|title=EFF STATEMENT ON VBS CURATORSHIP {{!}} EFF: Economic Freedom Fighters|last=Ndlozi|first=Mbuyiseni Quintin|date=11 March 2018|website=Economic Freedom Fighters|access-date=13 October 2018}}</ref> The EFF stated that it had seen no evidence that Shivambu received the R10 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-10-16-there-are-exchanges-of-money-between-floyd-and-brian-shivambu-but-floyd-did-not-get-money-from-vbs-says-eff/|title=Money was exchanged - but Floyd did not get any from VBS bank, says Malema|access-date=16 October 2018}}</ref> and called for government to recapitalise VBS Mutual Bank<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-calls-for-vbs-to-be-recapitalised-17501083|title=EFF calls for VBS to be recapitalised {{!}} IOL News|last=Zintle|first=Mahlati|date=16 October 2018|work=IOL|access-date=16 October 2018}}</ref> whilst also taking legal action against those mentioned in the Reserve Bank report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dispatchlive.co.za/politics/2018-10-16-malema-vbs-allegations-meant-to-discredit-the-eff/|title=Malema: VBS allegations meant to 'discredit the EFF'|last=Mvumvu|first=Zingisa|date=16 October 2018|work=Dispatch Live|access-date=16 October 2018}}</ref> A follow up investigation by the ''[[Daily Maverick]]'' alleged that the EFF illicitly received R1.8 million of VBS money through a network of proxy companies with the party's leadership (notably Shivambu and Malema) also illicitly receiving money though this network.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-11-21-vbs-bank-heist-effs-family-ties-and-moneyed-connections/|title=VBS bank heist: EFF's family ties and moneyed connections|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|date=21 November 2018|work=Daily Maverick|access-date=21 November 2018}}</ref> After being approached by the ''[[Mail & Guardian]]'' for comment on his personal financial expenses Floyd Shivambu admitted that money from VBS, channeled through his brother, was used to buy his [[Range Rover Sport]] valued at R680,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-09-26-vbss-r680k-paid-for-floyds-wheels/|title=VBS\u2019s R680k paid for Floyd\u2019s wheels|last=Skiti|first=Thanduxolo Jika, Sabelo|website=The M&G Online|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nA follow up investigation by the ''Daily Maverick'' found that R454,000 of VBS money was used to pay for the 2017 EFF birthday celebration.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-05-27-cruising-nicely-on-vbs-effs-parties-lies-and-looted-money/|title=SCORPIO: 'Cruising nicely' on VBS: EFF's Parties, Lies and Looted Money|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref> It also found that a total of R16.1 million was channeled through a Shivambu associated company largely for the benefit of the EFF.<ref name=\":5\" /> An additional investigation traced financial statements from an account that received VBS funds and allegedly controlled by Julius Malema; leading the author of the investigation to estimate that Malema received and directly benefited from R5.3-million illegally taken from VBS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-08-vbs-theft-money-laundering-lifes-little-luxuries-julius-malemas-time-of-spending-dangerously/|title=SCORPIO: VBS Theft, Money Laundering & Life's Little Luxuries: Julius Malema's time of spending dangerously|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|date=8 September 2019|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> Additional media reports in October 2019 alleged that the party received R4 million of VBS funds into a slush fund that was channeled to Malema via a company named Santaclara Trading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2190574/over-r4m-in-concerning-payments-made-into-malema-slush-fund-report/|title=Over R4m in 'concerning' payments made into Malema slush fund \u2013 report|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2019-10-13-julius-malemas-slush-fund-exposed/|title=Julius Malema's 'slush fund' exposed|website=TimesLIVE|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/malema-linked-to-another-company-that-had-a-vbs-loan-report-20191013|title=Malema linked to another company that had a VBS loan - report|date=13 October 2019|website=News24|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nA former member of the EFF's leadership accused the party leadership of accepting donations from VBS Mutual Bank prior to its collapse.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMalema later forwarded a [[conspiracy theory]] that the VBS collapse was part of a plot intended to damage the EFF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/watch-vbs-was-meant-to-collapse-and-finish-eff-malema-20190503|title=WATCH: 'VBS was meant to collapse and finish EFF' \u2013 Malema|date=3 May 2019|website=News24|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ideology===\nFeminists and the [[National Union of Metalworkers of South Africa]] have criticised the party's militarism and \"military command structure\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/numsa-wary-of-capitalist-malema-1.1627179#.Usa_NvQW3Y5|title=Numsa wary of \u2018capitalist\u2019 Malema|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103182553/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/numsa-wary-of-capitalist-malema-1.1627179|archive-date=3 January 2014|author=Shanti Aboobaker|work=Sunday Independent|date=29 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thoughtleader.co.za/siphokazimagadla/2013/11/06/eff-and-the-return-of-the-warrior-citizen/|title=EFF & the Return of the Warrior Citizen|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410024005/http://www.thoughtleader.co.za/siphokazimagadla/2013/11/06/eff-and-the-return-of-the-warrior-citizen|archive-date=10 April 2014|author=Siphokazi Magadla|work=Thought Leader|date=2013}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-June 2016 a group calling themselves \"Anonymous Africa\", claiming to be associated with the [[Hacktivism|hacktivist]] group [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]], perpetrated a [[Denial-of-service attack|DDoS attack]] on the EFF's website stating the reason for the attack was the party's \"nationalist socialist rhetoric\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fin24.com/Tech/Companies/exclusive-why-anonymous-hacked-the-sabc-guptas-20160617|title=EXCLUSIVE: Why Anonymous 'hacked' the SABC, Gupta websites|website=Fin24|access-date=19 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617140057/http://www.fin24.com/Tech/Companies/exclusive-why-anonymous-hacked-the-sabc-guptas-20160617|archivedate=17 June 2016}}</ref> The [[South African Communist Party]] also condemns this party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sacp.org.za/main.php?ID=5299|title=SACP supports ANC, condemns Julius Malema`s propagation of war in the strongest possible terms, calls on the police ?to act swiftly in terms of the rule of law|website=www.sacp.org.za|access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Violence and bigotry===\nVusi Khoza, the party's candidate for [[Premier of KwaZulu-Natal]], has a criminal conviction for his involvement in what was believed to be a [[Xenophobia in South Africa|xenophobic attack]] on foreigners at Albert Park, [[Durban]] in December 2009.<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-s-kzn-man-has-criminal-past-1.1663164#.Uy0Y3vmSzY4 EFF\u2019s KZN man has criminal past] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322091149/http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-s-kzn-man-has-criminal-past-1.1663164 |date=22 March 2014 }}, BHEKI MBANJWA, ''The Daily News'', 2014</ref>\n\nFeminists have characterised leading members of the party as [[Misogyny|misogynist]].<ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-04-25-floyd-shivambu-despicable-me/ Floyd Shivambu: Despicable Me] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224084746/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-04-25-floyd-shivambu-despicable-me |date=24 December 2013 }}, Sipho Hlongwane, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-05-remembering-thomas-sankara-the-effs-muse/ Remembering Thomas Sankara, the EFF\u2019s muse] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224094726/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-05-remembering-thomas-sankara-the-effs-muse/ |date=24 December 2013 }}, Rebecca Davis, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2013</ref><ref>[http://feministssa.com/2013/11/28/elections-analysis-the-economic-freedom-fighters-2/ Elections Analysis: The Economic Freedom Fighters] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322090232/http://feministssa.com/2013/11/28/elections-analysis-the-economic-freedom-fighters-2/|date=22 March 2014}}, Sonja Bornman, ''Feminist SA'', 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-25-eff-two-senior-party-officials-accused-of-involvement-in-2008-gang-rape EFF: Two senior party officials accused of involvement in 2008 gang rape] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322091542/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-25-eff-two-senior-party-officials-accused-of-involvement-in-2008-gang-rape |date=22 March 2014 }}, Rebecca Davis, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2013</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2014, eight members of the EFF were forcibly removed from the legislature after their attire of red overalls carrying the slogan \"asijiki\" (meaning \"we are not turning back\") was found to be inappropriate by presiding officer, Ntombi Mekgwe.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.enca.com/eff-kicked-out-gauteng-legislature |title=EFF kicked out of Gauteng Legislature |publisher=enca.co.za |date=1 July 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> Hundreds of EFF members protested against the ruling on 22 July near the legislature building.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://ewn.co.za/2014/07/22/EFF-storm-Gauteng-Provincial-Legislature |title=EFF storm Gauteng Provincial Legislature |publisher=ewn.co.za |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, during [[FeesMustFall|violent university protests]] characterised by arson and vandalism, EFF Youth leader Omphile Seleke posted instructions for making petrol bombs on social media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://citizen.co.za/news/news-national/1013882/effs-petrol-bomb-recipe-fuels-tuks-fears/|title=EFF\u2019s \u2018petrol bomb recipe\u2019 fuels Tuks fears|last=de Lange|first=Ilse|date=29 February 2016|work=The Citizen|access-date=14 April 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414081535/http://citizen.co.za/news/news-national/1013882/effs-petrol-bomb-recipe-fuels-tuks-fears/|archivedate=14 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, EFF Deputy President [[Floyd Shivambu]] congratulated the party supporters for causing damage to various [[H&M]] stores<ref>{{cite tweet|number=952114009448304640|user=FloydShivambu|title=That @hm nonsense of a clothing store is now facing consequences for its racism.|date=13 January 2018}}</ref> across South Africa due to a picture of a young black child wearing a green hoodie reading, \"Coolest Monkey in the Jungle\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/h-m-the-weeknd-coolest-monkey-in-the-jungle-racist-hoodie/|title=H&M monkey hoodie sparks outrage for \"racist\" image - CBS News|date=8 January 2018|work=[[CBS News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108222136/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/h-m-the-weeknd-coolest-monkey-in-the-jungle-racist-hoodie/|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/01/08/news/companies/hm-apologizes-monkey-hoodie/index.html|title=H&M apologizes for using black child to sell 'coolest monkey' top|date=8 January 2018|work=[[CNN]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108143043/http://money.cnn.com/2018/01/08/news/companies/hm-apologizes-monkey-hoodie/index.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/08/hm-slammed-for-racist-monkey-in-the-jungle-hoodie.html|title=H&M slammed as racist for 'monkey in the jungle' hoodie|date=8 January 2018|work=[[CNBC]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108165628/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/08/hm-slammed-for-racist-monkey-in-the-jungle-hoodie.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1174479/hm-is-apologizing-for-a-product-image-called-out-as-racist/|title=H&M is apologizing for a product image called out as racist - Quartz|date=8 January 2018|work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108235715/https://qz.com/1174479/hm-is-apologizing-for-a-product-image-called-out-as-racist/|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hm-apology-racist-image-website-child-model-backlash-twitter-monkey-jumper-black-a8147641.html|title=H&M apologises following backlash over 'racist' image of child model on website - The Independent|date=8 January 2018|work=[[The Independent]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108173805/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hm-apology-racist-image-website-child-model-backlash-twitter-monkey-jumper-black-a8147641.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/h-m-faces-twitter-backlash-racist-hoodie-1072791|title=H&M Faces Twitter Backlash for \"Racist\" Hoodie - Pret-a-Reporter|date=8 January 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108095220/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/h-m-faces-twitter-backlash-racist-hoodie-1072791|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> A [[Vodacom]] store in [[Polokwane]] was damaged and looted by EFF members following a presentation by [[Corruption Watch (South Africa)|Corruption Watch]] at the 2018 Vodacom Awards which included an image depicting EFF leaders Malema and Shivambu as \"abusers of Democracy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/matter-now-closed-eff-vodacom-issue-joint-statement-following-unrest-20181204|title='Matter now closed' - EFF, Vodacom issue joint statement following unrest|last=Seleka|first=Ntwaagae|date=4 December 2018|website=News24|language=en-ZA|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mybroadband.co.za/news/business-telecoms/288272-why-vodacom-met-with-the-eff.html|title=Why Vodacom met with the EFF|last=Staff Writer|date=4 December 2018|website=mybroadband.co.za|language=en-ZA|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, after the SONA address in parliament by the SA President, EFF MP [[Marshall Dlamini]] physically assaulted a member of the presidential security team after a disagreement between EFF MPs and the security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/watch-eff-mp-slaps-man-after-sona-20190208|title=EFF MP slaps man after SONA|last=Gerber|first=Jan|date=8 February 2019|website=www.news24.com|language=en-ZA|access-date=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Actions against journalists and the media====\nJournalist Ranjeni Munusamy lodged an affidavit in December 2018 detailing threatening remarks, intimidation, harassment and personal attacks made by party members, including Malema, towards her and other journalists<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sanef.org.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Part-2.pdf|title=Supporting Affidavit: Navaranjeni Munusamy|last=Munusamy|first=Ranjeni|date=19 December 2018|website=South African National Editors Forum|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref> targeted by the party. The affidavit was supported by the South African National Editors Forum and other notable South African journalists such as [[Max du Preez]], Pauli VanWyk, Adriaan Jurgens Basson, and Barry Bateman.<ref name=\":1\" /> The EFF denied any involvement in attacks on Munusamy and other journalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-12-19-eff-denies-involvement-in-attacks-on-journalists/|title=EFF denies involvement in attacks on journalists|last=Shange|first=Naledi|date=19 December 2018|website=www.timeslive.co.za|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref>{{quote box|quote=''\"We need to ask the [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|IEC]] how such a party can be on the ballot box. It threatens journalists. It encourages its supporters to make rape threats and sexual assault threats. It wants to dictate what I can do as a journalist.\"''<br/>\u2014Karima Brown<ref name=\"KB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|title=Karima Brown vows to lay further complaints as EFF supporters continue to attack|publisher=African News Agency|date=20 March 2016|accessdate=6 March 2019|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306215040/https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|archivedate=6 March 2019}}</ref>|width=25%|align=right}}\nSouth African political journalist Karima Brown was the target of verbal abuse and threats of violence by EFF supporters following the EFF's publication of her personal contact details. This led charges with the police and Equity Court being laid against the party amidst speculation that this instance might be in breach of South Africa's Electoral Code of Conduct. Parties in breach of the code risk having their registration to run in elections being revoked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|title=Karima Brown vows to lay further complaints as EFF supporters continue to attack {{!}} IOL News|website=www.iol.co.za|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> Malema stated on the incident that journalists have no privileges whilst accusing Brown of being a state agent and denied that EFF supporters were making threatening remarks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/how-do-you-hold-an-underground-editor-accountable-malema-on-karima-brown-matter-20190306|title='How do you hold an underground editor accountable ' \u2013 Malema on Karima Brown matter|date=6 March 2019|website=News24|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> The court found in favour of Brown and ruled that the EFF had contravened the South African electoral code by inciting its supports to harass Brown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-06-06-eff-court-losses-mount-as-karima-brown-wins-battle-but-faces-criticism-of-her-own/|title=REPORT: EFF court losses mount as Karima Brown wins battle, but faces criticism of her own|last=Davis|first=Rebecca|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the publication of an article by the amaBhungane Centre for investigative journalism looking into allegations of corruption by the EFF the party controversially announced that it would be banning both amaBhungane and the ''Daily Maverick'' from its public events<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2185034/malema-and-eff-get-r15m-in-kickbacks-in-tshwane-fuel-scandal-report/|title=Malema and EFF get R15m in 'kickbacks' in Tshwane fuel scandal \u2013 report|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-13-this-is-what-panic-looks-like/|title=Editorial: This is What Panic Looks Like|last=Maverick|first=Daily|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sanef-appalled-by-malemas-call-to-ban-amabhungane-daily-mavericks-scorpio-from-eff-events-20190913|title=Sanef 'appalled' by Malema's call to ban amaBhungane, Daily Maverick's Scorpio from EFF events|date=13 September 2019|website=News24|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref> and announced that they would be treated an enemies of the party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/we-shall-treat-them-as-enemies-malema-bans-amabhungane-and-daily-mavericks-scorpio-from-eff-events-20190912|title=Malema bans amaBhungane and Daily Maverick's Scorpio from EFF events: 'We shall treat them as enemies'|date=12 September 2019|website=News24|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 the EFF was forced to publicly apologies and pay damages following a Gauteng High Court judgment that the party had made and spread false allegations that two journalists, Thandeka Gqubule and Anton Harber, were apartheid era 'StratCom' agents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/eff-retracts-stratcom-agent-allegations-against-gqubule-and-harber-apologises-after-court-order-20200125|title=EFF retracts 'Stratcom agent' allegations against Gqubule and Harber, apologises after court order|date=25 January 2020|website=News24|language=en|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-01-24-eff-ndlozi-have-twenty-four-hours-to-pay-damages-to-journalists/|title=NEWSFLASH: EFF, Ndlozi have twenty-four hours to pay damages to journalists|last=Snijman|first=Lia|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Racial and ethnic prejudice===\nSince its establishment the EFF has made a number of controversial racially or ethnically based statements about a number of South African minority groups. The EFF is widely criticised for inciting and perpetuating racism.<ref>[http://sacsis.org.za/site/article/1899 The EFF and the Question of National Unity] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413154904/http://sacsis.org.za/site/article/1899|date=13 April 2014}}, Duncan, Jane, ''SACSIS WEBSITE'', 29 Jan 2014</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-must-paybackthemoney-for-damage-to-varsities-1995188|title=\u2018EFF must #PayBackTheMoney for damage to varsities\u2019|last=Sain|first=Raahil|date=8 March 2016|access-date=14 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414162203/http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-must-paybackthemoney-for-damage-to-varsities-1995188|archivedate=14 April 2017}}</ref>  \n\n====Anti-Indian prejudice====\nThe South African Minority Rights Equality Movement initiated a court case against Malema for inciting racial sentiment by stating that a \"majority of [[Indian South Africans|Indians]] are racist\" at an EFF Youth Day rally in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/group-to-take-juliusmalema-to-court-for-racist-rant-15526571|title=Group to take #JuliusMalema to court for racist rant {{!}} IOL News|last=Mngoma|first=Nosipho|date=18 June 2018|website=www.iol.co.za|publisher=The Mercury|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was criticised by the [[South African Council of Churches]], the [[Ahmed Kathrada Foundation]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/no-one-is-going-to-intimidate-us-eff-hits-back-at-clergy-and-ahmed-kathrada-foundation-20181122|title='No one is going to intimidate us' - EFF hits back at clergy and Ahmed Kathrada Foundation|work=News24|access-date=23 November 2018|language=en}}</ref> and the ANC<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/eff-bullies-trying-to-hide-their-own-shenanigans-anc-chief-whip-mthembu-20181123|title='EFF bullies' trying to 'hide their own shenanigans' - ANC chief whip Mthembu|work=News24|access-date=23 November 2018|language=en}}</ref> for comparing Public Enterprises Minister [[Pravin Gordhan]] to a \"dog\" whilst protesting the [[The Judicial Commission of Inquiry into Allegations of State Capture|Zondo Commission]] inquiry into government corruption. The EFF also accused the anti-corruption investigators of being members of an \"[[Indian South Africans|Indian]] [[cabal]]\" commenting on the presence of Indian South African's making up the investigative team.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://city-press.news24.com/Voices/indian-cabal-narrative-is-to-protect-the-looting-project-20181119|title=\u2018Indian cabal\u2019 narrative is to protect the looting project|work=CityPress|access-date=23 November 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-to-gordhan-i-am-not-scared-of-the-indian-cabal|title=Malema to Gordhan: I am not scared of the Indian cabal|website=eNCA|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref> The EFF also accused Gordhan and his daughter of corruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-11-23-00-gordhan-decries-eff-attack-on-daughter/|title=Gordhan decries EFF attack on daughter|last=Smit|first=Sarah|website=The M&G Online|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref> The EFF accusations were proven false<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/Analysis/fact-checked-julius-malemas-charges-against-pravin-gordhan-20181128|title=FACT CHECKED: EFF's charges against Pravin Gordhan|last=Jean le Roux, Kyle Cowan, Pieter du Toit and Adriaan Basson|date=28 November 2018|website=News24|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-11-29-snowbank-bleff-pravin-gordhan-and-the-imaginary-r675m-canadian-account/|title=SnowBank \u2013 BLEFF, Pravin Gordhan and the imaginary R6...|last=Poplak|first=Richard|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref> and Gordhan laid charge of defamation against Malema stating that the EFF's \"determined defence of corruption and the corrupt, using personal attacks, racism and alleged hate speech is not acceptable and must be challenged.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/pravin-gordhan-lays-defamation-charges-against-malema-18267798|title=Pravin Gordhan lays defamation charges against Malema {{!}} IOL News|last=Ndaba|first=Baldwin|date=26 November 2018|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref>  The Equality Court found that the EFF was not guilty of hate speech in its statements relating to Gordhan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/pravin-gordhan-vs-julius-malema-the-high-court-jud|title=Pravin Gordhan vs Julius Malema|last=Sutherland|first=Roland|date=31 October 2019|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-10-31-judge-slates-malemas-juvenile-rant-as-eff-leader-wins-case-against-gordhan/|title=Judge slates Malema's 'juvenile' rant as EFF leader wins case against Gordhan|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref> EFF leadership and its supporters have been criticised for using Gordhan's second name, Jamnadas, as a racial [[Dog-whistle politics|dog whistle]] to highlight to his Indian ethnicity in a [[pejorative]] way and question his status as a South African on social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-01-23-pravin-jamnadas-gordhan-a-case-study-when-your-name-is-weaponised-by-haters-on-twitter/|title=POPULIST DOG WHISTLES: Pravin Jamnadas Gordhan, a case study: When your name is weaponised on Twitter|last=Snijman|first=Lia|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nANC member and government minister [[Jackson Mthembu]] accused the EFF of being racist and having a \"deep-seated hatred\" for Indian South Africans whilst criticizing the party's pursuit of Gordhan whilst participating in a parliamentary debate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-07-17-of-course-you-are-racist-you-are-jackson-mthembu-tells-eff-mps/|title='Of course, you are racist. You are,' Jackson Mthembu tells EFF MPs|last=Makinana|first=Andisiwe|date=17 July 2019|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/cigarettes-corruption-and-racism-why-the-eff-hates-gordhan-according-to-jackson-mthembu-20190718|title=Cigarettes, corruption and racism: Why the EFF hates Gordhan, according to Jackson Mthembu|last=van Diemen|first=Ethan|date=18 July 2019|website=News24|language=en|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Anti-white prejudice====\nMalema stated at a political rally in 2016 that \u201cWe are not calling for the slaughter of [[White South Africans|white people]]\u201a at least for now\". When asked for comment by a news agency, the ANC spokesperson, Zizi Kodwa stated that there will be no comment from the ANC, as \"[h]e [Malema] was addressing his own party supporters.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Malema slammed for comments on whites|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-%E2%80%98slaughter-statement%E2%80%99-rocks-sa|accessdate=30 May 2017|publisher=ENCA|date=8 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417053045/http://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-%E2%80%98slaughter-statement%E2%80%99-rocks-sa|archivedate=17 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While still the ANCYL leader, Malema was taken to the [[Promotion of Equality and Prevention of Unfair Discrimination Act, 2000|Equality Court]] by [[AfriForum]] for repeatedly singing \u201c[[Dubul' ibhunu|dubul\u2019 ibhunu]]\u201d, which translate as \u201cshoot the [[boer]] [white farmer]\u201d. The ANC supported Malema, though AfriForum and the ANC reached a settlement before the appeal case was due to be argued in the [[Supreme Court of Appeal of South Africa|Supreme Court of Appeal]].{{CN|date=March 2019}}\n\nSouth Africa's [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|Independent Electoral Commission]] disqualified EFF councillor Thabo Mabotja in the 2016 local elections due a [[Twitter|tweet]] made by Mabotja calling for violence against white South Africans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa/iec-disqualifies-eff-councillor-for-racist-tweet|title=IEC disqualifies EFF councillor for racist tweet|date=29 August 2016|work=eNCA|access-date=14 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414082702/http://www.enca.com/south-africa/iec-disqualifies-eff-councillor-for-racist-tweet|archivedate=14 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/elections/news/eff-councillor-candidate-disqualified-after-calling-for-whites-to-be-hacked-and-killed-reports-20160729|title=EFF councillor candidate disqualified after calling for whites to be 'hacked and killed' reports|date=29 July 2016|website=News24|language=en|access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref> The EFF welcomed the commission's decision and renounced Mabotja.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/hes-on-his-own-juju-says-of-mabotja|title='He's on his own' Juju says of Mabotja|website=eNCA|language=en|access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/electoral-court-right-to-give-thabo-mabotja-the-ch|title=Electoral Court right to give Thabo Mabotja the chop|last=|first=|date=|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nJulius Malema, leader of the Economic Freedom Fighters, stated at a political rally in 2018 that \"''Go After A White Man... We Are Cutting The Throat Of Whiteness\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/we-are-cutting-the-throat-of-whiteness-malema-on-plans-to-remove-trollip-20180304|title='We are cutting the throat of whiteness' \u2013 Malema on plans to remove Trollip|work=News24|access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref>'' This led to the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] accusing the EFF's leader, Malema, of [[racism]] and not sharing the more tolerant views of South Africans broadly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/south-africans-dont-share-malemas-racist-views-maimane-13714966|title=South Africans don't share Malema's racist views - Maimane {{!}} IOL News|access-date=11 March 2018}}</ref> The EFF later stated that the reference to the \"throat of whiteness\" was a metaphorical reference to destroying [[white privilege]] and was not referring or advocating harm to white people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2019-03-28-empty-analysis-will-not-deter-the-eff-from-its-core-task-reaching-out-to-the-electorate/|title=OPINIONISTA: Empty analysis will not deter the EFF from its core task \u2014 reaching out to the electorate|last=Thambo|first=Sinawo|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the death of former Zimbabwean President [[Robert Mugabe]] EFF leader Julius Malema tweeted a number of controversial quotes from the late Mugabe that were interpreted as racially prejudiced towards white people.  Most notable was the quote that \"''The only white man you can trust is a dead white man''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-09-17-yep-its-hate-speech-says-sahrc-on-julius-malemas-dead-white-man-tweet/|title=Yep, it's hate speech, says SAHRC on Julius Malema's 'dead white man' tweet|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-15-malemas-mugabe-closing-gambit/|title=ANALYSIS: Malema\u2019s Mugabe closing gambit|last=Grootes|first=Stephen|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>  The [[South African Human Rights Commission]] (SAHRC) condemned the quote and stated that they would be taking Malema to court for allegedly spreading [[hate speech]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sahrc.org.za/index.php/sahrc-media/news-2/item/2137-sahrc-to-take-malema-to-court-for-hate-speech|title=SAHRC to take Malema to court for hate speech|last=|first=|date=19 September 2019|website=South African Human Rights Commission|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Namibian Economic Freedom Fighters]]\n*[[Socialist Party of Azania]]\n*[[Workers and Socialist Party]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news|last1=Van Onselen|first1=Gareth|title=Malema steals young communists' thunder|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/opinion/columnists/2013/07/29/malema-steals-young-communists-thunder|accessdate=6 June 2014|work=Business Day|date=29 July 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Q7p7lAID?url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/opinion/columnists/2013/07/29/malema-steals-young-communists-thunder|archivedate=6 June 2014|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite news|last1=Pillay|first1=Verashni|title=EFF: You want land, a loan? You got it|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2014-02-20-eff-you-want-land-a-loan-you-got-it|accessdate=6 June 2014|work=Mail & Guardian|date=21 February 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328111438/http://mg.co.za/article/2014-02-20-eff-you-want-land-a-loan-you-got-it|archivedate=28 March 2014|url-status=live}}\n*Julius Malema (preface), [https://archive.org/details/EconomicFreedomFighters2014ElectionsManifesto ''EFF 2014 Elections Manifesto,''] Economic Freedom Fighters.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.effonline.org Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140918100051/http://effighters.org.za/ Old official website]\n*[http://economicfreedomfighters.org/ Supporter website]\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n{{South Africa political parties}}\n[[Category:Economic Freedom Fighters| ]]\n[[Category:African and Black nationalist organizations in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-capitalist political parties]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics]]\n[[Category:Political parties in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2013]]\n[[Category:National liberation movements in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-white racism in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-Indian sentiment in Africa]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Left-wing populist parties]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use South African English|date=December 2015}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Economic Freedom Fighters\n| logo = Logo of the EFF.png\n| colorcode = {{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}\n| abbreviation = EFF\n| president = [[Julius Malema]]\n| chairperson = [[Veronica Mente]]\n| secretary_general = [[Marshall Dlamini]]\n| spokesperson = [[Vuyani Pambo]]\n| leader1_title = Deputy President\n| leader1_name = [[Floyd Shivambu]]\n| leader2_title = Deputy Secretary-General\n| leader2_name = Poppy Mailola\n| leader3_title = Treasurer-General\n| leader3_name = [[Omphile Maotwe]]\n| founder = Julius Malema\n| founded = {{Start date|df=yes|2013|07|26}}\n| dissolved = <!--{{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| split = [[African National Congress]]\n| headquarters = 82 De Korte Street,<br>[[Johannesburg]]\n| newspaper =\n| student_wing = [[EFF Students Command]] (EFFSC)\n| youth_wing =\n| ideology = {{Nowrap|[[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/economicfreedomstruggle|title=EFF|accessdate=24 February 2016|via=Facebook|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105041413/https://www.facebook.com/economicfreedomstruggle|archivedate=5 January 2018}}</ref><ref>https://www.effonline.org/constitution</ref><br>[[Left-wing populism]]<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Times of India]]|title=ANC holds onto power in South Africa as other parties increase vote share|date=11 May 2018|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/rest-of-world/anc-holds-onto-power-in-south-africa-as-other-parties-increase-vote-share/articleshow/69278436.cms}}</ref><br>[[Pan-Africanism]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kwinika |first1=Savious |title=South Africa: Pan-African EFF Makes Most of Rival Parties' Squabbles |url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201903180741.html |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=allAfrica |date=18 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><br>[[Anti-capitalism]]<ref name=\"aji\">{{cite web|url=http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201310142026-0023110|title=Economic Freedom Fighters Party reignites debate (in English)|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=14 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102192705/http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201310142026-0023110|archivedate=2 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"n24i\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Hundreds-gather-for-EFF-launch-20131013|title=Hundreds gather for EFF launch (in English)|publisher=[[News24]]|date=13 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104124450/http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Hundreds-gather-for-EFF-launch-20131013|archivedate=4 November 2013}}</ref><br>[[Anti-imperialism]]<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://effonline.org/about-us/ |publisher=Economic Freedom Fighters |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref><br>[[Racism in South Africa#Racism against white people|Anti-white sentiment]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Campbell|first=John|year=2016|title=Morning in South Africa|publisher=Indiana University Press|page=187|quotation=Often explicitly '''antiwhite''' in its rhetoric, it [the EFF] would expropriate without compensation white-owned property...}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Megan|year=2016|title=Performing Whitely in the Postcolony: Afrikaners in South African Theatrical and Public Life|publisher=University of Iowa Press|page=62|quotation=Several events added fuel to the fire: the increasing popularity of Julius Malema's '''antiwhite''' political party, the Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF) ...}}</ref>}}\n| position = {{nowrap|[[Far-left politics|Far-left]]<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-safrica-politics-malema/south-africas-malema-says-more-than-60-anc-mps-will-turn-on-zuma-idUSKBN1A61AP South Africa's Malema says more than 60 ANC MPs will turn on Zuma]. ''Reuters''. Authors - Ed Stoddard and Sisipho Skweyiya. Published 21 July 2017. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=eti_DgAAQBAJ&pg=PA66&dq=Far-left+Economic+Freedom+Fighters&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4ooLL96raAhWJalAKHTa0AMAQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Social Changes in a Global World'']. p.66. Author - Ulrike Schuerkens. Published by SAGE. Published in London in 2017. Accessed via Google Books.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9MZODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA535&lpg=PA535&dq=Far-left+Economic+Freedom+Fighters&source=bl&ots=HZyA_KTESl&sig=agvCpZ2_jS7zZKdYQolUvHnm0Xs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEl5ew96raAhVSPsAKHSM8C7A4PBDoAQhgMAk#v=onepage&q=Far-left%20Economic%20Freedom%20Fighters&f=false ''The World Since 1945: An International History'']. p.535. 2nd edition. Authors - P. M. H. Bell and Mark Gilbert. Published by Bloomsbury in London. First published in 2001, 2nd edition in 2017.</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/chaos-in-parliament-as-party-gets-ejected-for-grilling-zuma-over-corruption-in-south-africa-10043286.html Chaos in parliament as party gets ejected for grilling Zuma over corruption in South Africa]. ''Independent''. Author - Lamiat Sabin. Published 13 February 2015. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref>}}\n| international =\n| colours = [[Red]]<ref name=\"aji\"/><ref name=\"n24i\"/><ref name=\"dmi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-10-14-red-tide-from-economic-freedom-to-white-genocide-extremism-grabs-the-spotlight/#.UnQCyhb1DoF|title=Red Tide: From 'economic freedom' to 'white genocide', extremism grabs the spotlight (in English)|publisher=[[Daily Maverick]]|date=14 October 2013|accessdate=1 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017020415/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-10-14-red-tide-from-economic-freedom-to-white-genocide-extremism-grabs-the-spotlight/#.UnQCyhb1DoF|archivedate=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n| slogan = \"Our land and jobs, now!\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Daniel |first1=Luke |title=EFF manifesto launch 2019: Five main talking points |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/eff-manifesto-launch-2019-talking-points/ |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The South African |date=2 February 2019}}</ref>\n| seats1_title = [[National Assembly of South Africa|National Assembly]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|44|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[National Council of Provinces]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|11|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = {{nowrap|[[Pan-African Parliament]]}}\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|1|5|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}<small>(South African seats)</small>\n| seats4_title = [[Provincial legislature (South Africa)|Provincial Legislatures]]\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|50|430|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[City of Johannesburg Metropolitan Municipality]] (council)\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|30|270|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| seats6_title = [[Nelson Mandela Bay Metropolitan Municipality]] (council)\n| seats6 = {{Composition bar|6|120|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| seats7_title = [[City of Cape Town]] (council)\n| seats7 = {{Composition bar|7|231|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n| flag =\n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| country = South Africa\n}}\n\nThe '''Economic Freedom Fighters''' ('''EFF''') is a [[South Africa]]n [[Far-left politics|far-left]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/southAfricaNews/idAFL5N1V80N0|title=South Africa's opposition EFF introduces bill to nationalise...|date=17 August 2018|work=Reuters|access-date=23 March 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref>[http://stream.aljazeera.com/story/201408222154-0024098 South African lawmakers disrupt parliament and demand Zuma #PayBackTheMoney]. ''AlJazeera''. Published 22 August 2014. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.radionz.co.nz/news/world/266026/south-african-parliament-descends-into-chaos South African parliament descends into chaos]. ''Radio New Zealand''. Published 13 February 2015. Retrieved 8 April 2018.</ref> [[Pan-Africanism|Pan-Africanist]] [[political party]]. It was founded by expelled former [[African National Congress Youth League]] (ANCYL) President [[Julius Malema]], and his allies, in 2013.<ref name=\"Dispatch\">{{cite news|title=Malema launches his Economic Freedom Fighters|author=Meggan Saville|url=http://www.dispatch.co.za/malema-launches-his-economic-freedom-fighters/|newspaper=Dispatch Online|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725200305/http://www.dispatch.co.za/malema-launches-his-economic-freedom-fighters/|archivedate=25 July 2013}}</ref> Malema is President of the EFF, heading the Central Command Team which serves as the central structure of the party.<ref name=\"BD\">{{cite news|title=Malema takes command of Economic Freedom Fighters|author=Setumo Stone|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/11/malema-takes-command-of-economic-freedom-fighters|newspaper=[[Business Day (South Africa)|Business Day]]|date=11 July 2013|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130714113641/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/11/malema-takes-command-of-economic-freedom-fighters|archivedate=14 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt is currently the third-largest party in both houses of the [[Parliament of South Africa|South African Parliament]].\n\n==History==\nAt a 26 July 2013 press briefing in [[Soweto]], Malema announced that the new party had over 1000 members, double the 500 required for registration with the [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|Independent Electoral Commission]] (IEC).<ref name=\"EFF 1000\">{{cite news|title=EFF readies for election registration as over 1 000 members recruited|author=SAPA|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2013/07/28/eff-readies-for-election-registration-as-over-1-000-members-recruited|newspaper=[[The Times (South Africa)|The Times]]|date=28 July 2013|accessdate=28 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730092849/http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2013/07/28/eff-readies-for-election-registration-as-over-1-000-members-recruited|archivedate=30 July 2013}}</ref> The EFF is now registered with the IEC, after an objection to its registration by the [[Freedom Front Plus]] (FF+) was dismissed in September 2013.<ref name=\"It'sOfficial\">{{cite news|title=It's official: Malema's EFF is a political party|author=Verashni Pillay|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-09-05-malemas-eff-to-contest-2014-elections|newspaper=[[Mail & Guardian]]|date=5 September 2013|accessdate=5 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130907063401/http://mg.co.za/article/2013-09-05-malemas-eff-to-contest-2014-elections|archivedate=7 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Splinters and infighting==\nIn 2015, the EFF suspended [[Member of parliament|MP]] Lucky Twala and expelled three MPs, Mpho Ramakatsa, Andile Mngxitama and [[Khanyisile Litchfield-Tshabalala]].<ref name=m.news24.com>{{cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Litchfield-Tshabalala-UDMs-new-national-organiser-20150605|title=Litchfield-Tshabalala UDM's new national organiser|author=Genevieve Quintal|date=5 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930022925/http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Litchfield-Tshabalala-UDMs-new-national-organiser-20150605|archivedate=30 September 2015}}</ref> Mngxitama formed his own party, named [[Black First Land First]] (BLF), while Litchfield-Tshabalala joined the [[United Democratic Movement]].{{CN|date=March 2019}}\nMalema has been chiefly accused by former members of purging his critics to consolidate his power, thus ruling the party with an iron fist. Malema acknowledged this criticism in a press conference and further went on to say, the party should have expelled more ill disciplined members.\n\n==Policies==\n[[File:EFF land march on Mandela Day 2014.JPG|thumb|A small march by the EFF on Mandela Day (18 July) 2014 near the parliament building in [[Cape Town]] protesting in support of [[land reform in South Africa]].]]\nThe EFF \"draws inspiration from the broad [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist\u2013Leninist]] tradition and [[Frantz Fanon|Fanonian]] schools of thought in their analyses of the state, imperialism, culture and class contradictions in every society\", according to one of its declarations.<ref name=\"ml\">{{cite web|url=https://www.effonline.org/declaration|title=Declaration|work=effonline.org}}</ref>\n\nIt criticises the [[African National Congress]] and their primary opposition, the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]], for their allegedly pro-business stances, which it claims have sold out the black people of South Africa to capitalism as cheap labour. It promises to tackle corruption, provide quality social housing, and provide free primary healthcare and education for all, as well as proposing to [[expropriation|expropriate]] stolen land, nationalise the mining and banking sectors, double welfare grants and the minimum wage, and end the proposed toll system for highways.<ref name=\"irishtimes\"/>\n\nThe EFF takes significant inspiration from [[Thomas Sankara]] in terms of both style and ideology.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|last=Duval Smith|first=Alex|date=30 April 2014|title='Africa's Che Guevara': Thomas Sankara's legacy|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-27219307|newspaper=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|location=[[London]]|accessdate=5 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101053949/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-27219307|archivedate=1 November 2014}}</ref> In a May 2014 column, the prominent EFF member Jackie Shandu declared his party a \"proudly [[Sankarism|Sankarist]] formation\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Shandu|first=Jackie|date=22 May 2014|title=The Sankarist makings of the EFF|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2014-05-22-the-sankarist-makings-of-eff/#.VFqe0d186rX|newspaper=[[Daily Maverick]]|location=[[Johannesburg]]|accessdate=5 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106000454/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2014-05-22-the-sankarist-makings-of-eff/#.VFqe0d186rX|archivedate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF has been vocal in its criticism of black business owners and black owners of mining companies in South Africa. In an address at the [[Oxford Union]] in November 2015, Malema spoke out against billionaire mining company owner Patrice Motsepe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2015/11/26/effs-malema-takes-aim-at-sellout-black-billionaires-in-oxford-address|title=Business Day|website=www.bdlive.co.za|access-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229135821/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2015/11/26/effs-malema-takes-aim-at-sellout-black-billionaires-in-oxford-address|archivedate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2016/05/01/Patrice-Motsepe-has-no-power%E2%80%9A-says-Malema|title=Patrice Motsepe has no power\u201a says Malema|last=Jordaan|first=Buchule Raba And Nomahlubi|website=Times LIVE|access-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127215142/http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2016/05/01/Patrice-Motsepe-has-no-power%E2%80%9A-says-Malema|archivedate=27 November 2016}}</ref> Further protests in 2015, the EFF delivered demands that included the socialization of the mining sector and called for more explicit targets for the 26% BEE ownership required by law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2015-11-01-yes-and-no-to-effs-list-of-demands|title=Yes and no to EFF\u2019s list of demands|last=John|first=Victoria|newspaper=The M&G Online|access-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128050240/http://mg.co.za/article/2015-11-01-yes-and-no-to-effs-list-of-demands|archivedate=28 November 2016}}</ref>  The EFF is a vocal proponent of expanding the role of [[State-owned enterprises of South Africa|South African state owned enterprises]] in the country's economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techfinancials.co.za/2019/02/03/eff-wants-state-to-create-ai-robotics-and-biotechnology-firms/|title=EFF Wants State To Create AI, Robotics And BioTechnology Firms|last=Lourie|first=Gugu|date=3 February 2019|website=TechFinancials|language=en-ZA|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/the-effs-2019-election-manifesto-iv|title=The EFF`s 2019 election manifesto (IV) - DOCUMENTS {{!}} Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nMalema addressed a crowd in Marikana, Rustenburg in the platinum mining area, blaming mining companies and calling out platinum mining company Lonmin in particular, for poverty in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/bdd0ce804d689dfe9d42df4b5facb1b5/Malema-blames-mining-companies-for-high-levels-of-poverty-20160707|title=SABC News - Malema blames mining companies for high levels of poverty:Thursday 7 July 2016|last=Tatai|first=Sello|website=www.sabc.co.za|access-date=27 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127232029/http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/bdd0ce804d689dfe9d42df4b5facb1b5/Malema-blames-mining-companies-for-high-levels-of-poverty-20160707|archivedate=27 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe party supports the re-introduction of the [[Capital punishment in South Africa|death penalty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.iafrica.com/sa/883240.html|title=iafrica.com Juju wants death penalty|website=News.iafrica.com|accessdate=19 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901181605/http://news.iafrica.com/sa/883240.html|archivedate=1 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economicfreedomfighters.org/malema-wants-death-penalty-efflaunch/|title=Malema wants death penalty #EFFlaunch &#124; Economic Freedom Fighters - EFF|publisher=Economic Freedom Fighters|date=13 October 2013|accessdate=19 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126014743/http://www.economicfreedomfighters.org/malema-wants-death-penalty-efflaunch/|archivedate=26 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, after [[2016 South African municipal elections|local elections]] in South Africa, the EFF has suggested that they will back the Democratic Alliance in hung-metro areas, but would not be entering into a coalition with any political party in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2016-08-17-malema-says-the-eff-wont-form-coalitions-but-will-support-da-in-hung-metros|title=Malema says the EFF won't form coalitions, but will support DA in hung metros|last=Feltham|first=Luke|newspaper=The M&G Online|access-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128050103/http://mg.co.za/article/2016-08-17-malema-says-the-eff-wont-form-coalitions-but-will-support-da-in-hung-metros|archivedate=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was the only parliamentary party that opposed the 2018 political party funding bill.<ref name=\"citizenFundingRejectionReasons\">https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1871025/reasons-why-the-eff-rejects-the-political-party-funding-bill/</ref>\n\n==High-profile members==\nHigh-profile members of the Central Command Team include [[Floyd Shivambu]], [[Fana Mokoena]] and [[Mbuyiseni Ndlozi]] (National Spokesperson).<ref name=\"EFF Central Command\">{{cite web|author=Economic Freedom Fighters|title=Central Command Team|url=http://www.effonline.org/structure|publisher=effonline.org|accessdate=21 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812200344/http://effighters.org.za/structure/officials/|archivedate=12 August 2013}}</ref> Controversial businessman [[Kenny Kunene]] joined the Central Command Team in July 2013 before resigning from the Central Command Team on 20 August 2013 and from the organisation on 26 August 2013.<ref name=\"Sushi\">{{cite news|title='Sushi King' quits EFF leadership|author=Poloko Tau|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/sushi-king-quits-eff-leadership-1.1565564#.UhhxMWthiSM|newspaper=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Independent Online]]|date=21 August 2013|accessdate=24 August 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824143456/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/sushi-king-quits-eff-leadership-1.1565564#.UhhxMWthiSM|archivedate=24 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ExitKunene\">{{cite news|title=Kunene quits EFF|author=[[South African Press Association|SAPA]]|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Kunene-quits-EFF-20130826|newspaper=[[News24]]|date=26 August 2013|accessdate=5 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829084845/http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Kunene-quits-EFF-20130826|archivedate=29 August 2013}}</ref> On 4 November 2013, it was announced that [[Dali Mpofu]] had left the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) after 33 years of membership and joined the EFF.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/dali-mpofu-joins-eff-1.1601553#.UoctTNKmimg|title=Dali Mpofu joins EFF - Cape Times|publisher=IOL.co.za|date=4 November 2013|accessdate=23 November 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202233822/http://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/dali-mpofu-joins-eff-1.1601553#.UoctTNKmimg|archivedate=2 December 2013}}</ref> Musician and actress [[Ntando Duma]] also publicly pledged allegiance to EFF in February 2019.\n\n==Support base==\nAccording to a November 2013 [[Ipsos]] survey, the party's supporters are younger than average, with 49% being younger than 24, overwhelmingly black (99%) and mostly male, with women representing only 33% of the support base. A disproportionate number of supporters live in Malema's home province of [[Limpopo]] (28%), while only 1% live in [[KwaZulu-Natal]], a more populous province.<ref name=ipsos>{{cite web|title=The supporter profiles of SA`s three largest parties|url=http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politicsweb/view/politicsweb/en/page72308?oid=534039&sn=Marketingweb+detail&pid=90389|publisher=Politicsweb|accessdate=6 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222022154/http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politicsweb/view/politicsweb/en/page72308?oid=534039&sn=Marketingweb+detail&pid=90389|archivedate=22 February 2014}}</ref> A 2018 survey conducted by social research company Citizen Surveys found that around 70% of EFF supporters were between the ages of 18 - 34, overwhelmingly black (97%), mostly based in major metropolitan cities (48%), predominantly male (62%) with 43% of their support base located in [[Gauteng|Gauteng Province]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizensurveys.net/citizen-surveys-how-many-white-eff-supporters-exist-and-11-other-stats/|title=Citizen Surveys: How many white EFF supporters exist, and 11 other stats|last=|first=|date=1 November 2018|website=Citizen Surveys|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe party was expected to make an impact in the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general election]], taking between 4 per cent and 8 per cent of the national vote. This was potentially enough for the party to hold [[Balance of power (parliament)|the balance of power]] in provinces where the governing African National Congress was in danger of losing its absolute majority.<ref name=\"irishtimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/africa/economic-freedom-fighters-on-rise-in-south-africa-1.1779028|title=Economic Freedom Fighters on rise in South Africa|date=1 May 2014|accessdate=6 May 2014|newspaper=The Irish Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506162746/http://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/africa/economic-freedom-fighters-on-rise-in-south-africa-1.1779028|archivedate=6 May 2014}}</ref> The ANC retained is absolute majority whilst the EFF got 6.35% of the vote in the 2014 election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/Elections/News/ANC-wins-249-seats-20140510|title=ANC wins 249 seats|last=|first=|date=12 May 2014|website=News24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512215131/http://www.news24.com/Elections/News/ANC-wins-249-seats-20140510|archive-date=12 May 2014|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n===National elections===\n====National Assembly====\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Total votes\n!Share of vote\n!Seats \n!+/\u2013\n!Government\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]<ref name=\"IEC 2014 election results\">{{Cite web|title=2014 National and Provincial Elections Results - 2014 National and Provincial Election Results|url=http://www.elections.org.za/resultsNPE2014/|publisher=IEC|accessdate=11 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140510231542/http://www.elections.org.za/resultsNPE2014/|archivedate=10 May 2014}}</ref>\n|1,169,259\n|6.35%\n|{{Composition bar|25|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 25\n|{{no2|in opposition}}\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|1,881,521\n|10.79%\n|{{Composition bar|44|400|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 19\n|{{no2|in opposition}}\n|}\n\n====National Council of Provinces====\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Total # of<br/>seats won\n!+/\u2013\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]\n|{{Composition bar|7|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 7\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|{{Composition bar|11|90|hex={{Economic Freedom Fighters/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 4\n|}\n\n===Municipal elections===\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n|-\n!Election\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n![[2016 South African municipal elections|2016]]<ref name=\"iec_summary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.org.za/content/LGEPublicReports/402/Detailed%20Results/National.pdf|title=Results Summary - All Ballots|publisher=elections.org.za|accessdate=11 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808191111/http://www.elections.org.za/content/LGEPublicReports/402/Detailed%20Results/National.pdf|archivedate=8 August 2016}}</ref>\n|3,202,679\n|8.31%\n|-\n|}\n\n===Provincial elections===\n{{election table|editlink=no}}\n!rowspan=2|Election<br><ref name=\"IEC 2014 election results\"/><ref name=\"dash\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elections.org.za/NPEDashboard/app/dashboard.html|title=Results Dashboard|website=www.elections.org.za|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n!colspan=2|[[Eastern Cape]]\n!colspan=2|[[Free State (province)|Free State]]\n!colspan=2|[[Gauteng]]\n!colspan=2|[[KwaZulu-Natal|Kwazulu-Natal]]\n!colspan=2|[[Limpopo]]\n!colspan=2|[[Mpumalanga]]\n!colspan=2|[[North West (South African province)|North-West]]\n!colspan=2|[[Northern Cape]]\n!colspan=2|[[Western Cape]]\n|- \n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n!%!!Seats\n|-\n![[2014 South African general election|2014]]\n|3.48%||2/63\n|8.15%||2/30\n|10.30%||8/73\n|1.85%||2/80\n|10.74%||6/49\n|6.26%||2/30\n|13.21%||5/33\n|4.96%||2/30\n|2.11%||1/42\n|-\n![[2019 South African general election|2019]]\n|7.84%||5/63\n|12.58%||4/30\n|14.69%||11/73\n|9.71%||8/80\n|14.43%||7/49\n|12.79%||4/30\n|18.36%||6/33\n|9.71%||3/30\n|4.04%||2/42\n|}\n\n==Achievements==\nOn 6 August 2015 the EFF announced that it has secured a Constitutional court case for its [[Jacob Zuma]] campaign of \"#PayBackTheMoney\". The case was heard on 9 February 2016. The Judgement was released by Chief Justice Mogoeng Mogoeng. The judgement stated that The President has violated the Constitution of South Africa, along with the [[Speaker of the National Assembly of South Africa|Speaker of the National Assembly]] [[Baleka Mbete]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} The President was given 60 days to fulfill the requirements of the Public Protector [[Thuli Madonsela]].<ref name=\"ZumaConCourt\">{{cite news|title=Lets meet in court, Malema tells Zuma|author=Emsie Ferreira|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/lets-meet-in-court-malema-tells-zuma-1896636|date=6 August 2015|accessdate=26 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201155340/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/lets-meet-in-court-malema-tells-zuma-1896636|archivedate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February 2018 the EFF tabled a motion in The National Assembly to amend the Constitution so as to allow for the expropriation of land without compensation. The motion, brought by the EFF leader [[Julius Malema]], was adopted with a vote of 241 in support, and 83 against. The only parties who did not support the motion were the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]], [[Freedom Front Plus]], [[Cope]] and the [[African Christian Democratic Party|ACDP]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} Land Expropriation is one of the EFF's Seven cardinal pillars.<ref name=\"LandExpropriation\">{{cite news|title=National Assembly adopts motion on land expropriation without compensation|author=Jan Gerber|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-national-assembly-adopts-motion-on-land-expropriation-without-compensation-20180227|date=27 February 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920012156/https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/breaking-national-assembly-adopts-motion-on-land-expropriation-without-compensation-20180227|archivedate=20 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the student wing of the EFF, the EFF Student Command won many universities across the country. The red berets defeated the ANC-aligned [[South African Students Congress]] (Sasco) at the [[Durban University of Technology]], the [[University of Zululand]] and [[Mangosuthu University of Technology]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} They also won in Cape Town, the District Six, Mowbray and Bellville [[Cape Peninsula University of Technology]] (CPUT) campuses with landslide victories, meaning they now are in charge of the institution's SRC. They also won the [[University of Cape Town]].{{CN|date=March 2019}} Peter Keetse, president of the EFFSC, said the win was a warning shot for what was going to happen in 2019 national general elections. He said the youth were the influencers of the future, \u201ctherefore, this is an indication of what is to follow\u201d.<ref name=\"EFFStudentCommand\">{{cite news|title=Comrades see red as students back EFF on campus|author=Kwandokuhle Njoli|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sunday-tribune/news/comrades-see-red-as-students-back-eff-on-campus-17275465|date=30 September 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms and controversies==\nThe ANC has accused the Zimbabwean ruling party, the [[ZANU\u2013PF|Zimbabwe African National Union \u2013 Patriotic Front]] (ZANU\u2013PF), of supporting the EFF in order to destabilise the ANC.<ref name=\"bdliveMantashe\">{{cite news|title=Mantashe hits out at EFF for 'distorting the Freedom Charter'|author=Natasha Marrian|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/29/mantashe-hits-out-at-eff-for-distorting-the-freedom-charter|newspaper=Business Day|date=29 July 2013|accessdate=30 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801072713/http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2013/07/29/mantashe-hits-out-at-eff-for-distorting-the-freedom-charter|archivedate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, a group of 17 former EFF members and councillors in the [[Northern Cape]] accused the party's senior leadership of corruption and sexual exploitation of more junior female party members.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2019199/expelled-eff-members-accuse-malema-shivambu-of-corruption-want-to-work-with-hawks/|title=Expelled EFF members accuse Malema, Shivambu of corruption, want to work with Hawks|last=reporter|first=Citizen|date=7 October 2018|work=The Citizen|access-date=13 October 2018|language=en}}</ref>  Four months later two former female employees of the EFF claimed that party leadership intimidated and engaged in acts of bullying behaviour towards them and other party staff members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://city-press.news24.com/News/more-women-make-claims-of-eff-bullying-and-abuse-20190216|title=More women make claims of EFF bullying and abuse|last=Peter|first=Zamayirha|date=16 February 2019|website=CityPress|language=en|access-date=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 a former member of the EFF's central command, Thembinkosi Rawula, accused senior party leaders of dictatorial leadership practices and of using party finances for personal benefit.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/disgruntled-eff-member-slams-malema-shivambu-for-taking-vbs-donation-party-denies-claims-20190405|title=Former EFF leader accuses Malema, Shivambu of taking VBS donation, party denies claims|last=Lizeka Tandwa and Tshidi Madia|date=5 April 2019|website=News24|language=en|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref> The EFF denied Rawula's accusation and stated that they would sue him for defamation as well as make the party's financials public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/malema-to-sue-rawula-offers-journalists-access-to-effs-financial-records-20190410|title=Malema to sue Rawula, offers journalists access to EFF's financial records|last=Tandwa|first=Lizeka|date=10 April 2019|website=News24|language=en|access-date=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was found guilty of [[Defamation|defamation of character]] in May 2019 by the South Gauteng High Court and ordered to pay R500,000 in damages to former Finance Minister [[Trevor Manuel]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-05-30-court-finds-effs-comments-about-trevor-manuel-defamatory-and-false/|title=Court vindicates Trevor Manuel in defamation battle with EFF|last=Quintal|first=Genevieve|date=30 May 2019|website=BusinessLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref> Manuel brought the EFF and its leader, Julius Malema, to court after they alleged that the appointment of Edward Kieswetter as commissioner of SARS by Manuel was the result of nepotism.<ref name=\":4\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/14/challenge-me-don-t-defame-manuel-to-eff-in-kieswetter-matter|title=Challenge me, don't defame - Manuel to EFF in Kieswetter nepotism matter|last=Modise|first=Kgomotso|website=ewn.co.za|language=en|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref>  Following the judgement Manuel stated that he would be donating the R500,000 in damages to victims of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters#VBS Mutual Bank|VBS Mutual Bank scandal]] which the EFF is alleged to have participated in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fin24.com/Economy/trevor-manuel-i-dont-need-a-cent-of-eff-money-20190531-2|title=Trevor Manuel: I don't need a cent of EFF money|last=Khumalo|first=Sibongile|date=31 May 2019|website=Fin24|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref>  \n\nFollowing a string of court case losses for inciting supporters to commit acts of either intimidation (against Karima Brown), land invasion ([[AfriForum]]) or of defamation of character (against Trevor Manuel) the party was left with combined court costs amounting to almost R1 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/courts/2144536/eff-wallows-in-legal-debt-of-almost-r1m/|title=EFF wallows in legal debt of almost R1m|last=Watson|first=Amanda|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref>  \n\n===Alleged Corruption===\n\n==== Tenders ====\nA number of articles published by investigative journalists have accused the party of using their influence to earn improper payments from government suppliers in cities where the EFF has significant representative power.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2185034/malema-and-eff-get-r15m-in-kickbacks-in-tshwane-fuel-scandal-report/|title=Malema and EFF get R15m in \u2018kickbacks\u2019 in Tshwane fuel scandal \u2013 report|last=|first=|date=|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>  An investigation by the [[amaBhungane]] centre for investigative journalism stated that the EFF received R500,000 in kickbacks from a company in return for a R1.26 billion contract to manage a fleet of vehicles used by the [[City of Johannesburg Metropolitan Municipality|City of Johannesburg]] with tacit acquiescence of the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amabhungane.org/stories/firm-that-won-r1bn-joburg-fleet-contract-paid-malema-eff-slush-fund/|title=Firm that won R1bn Jo'burg fleet contract paid Malema-EFF 'slush-fund' - amaBhungane|last=Micah Reddy and Stefaans Br\u00fcmmer|date=29 November 2018|website=amabhungane.org|language=en-ZA|access-date=29 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amabhungane.org/stories/tender-comrades-part-1-trailing-the-juju-tractor/|title=Tender comrades part 1: Trailing the Juju tractor|website=amaBhungane|language=en-US|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref> Another investigation alleges that the party improperly benefited from the awarding of a fuel supply contract for the [[City of Tshwane Metropolitan Municipality|City of Tshwane]] netting the party R15 million from successful contractors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-29-tender-comrades-part-two-tshwane-tenderpreneurs-r15m-eff-tithe/|title=AMABHUNGANE: Tender Comrades Part Two: Tshwane tenderpreneur\u2019s R15m \u2018EFF tithe\u2019|last=amaBhungane|first=Stefaans Brummer & Micah Reddy for|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n====VBS Mutual Bank====\n{{See also|VBS Mutual Bank}}\nFollowing the publication of a [[South African Reserve Bank]] report<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.resbank.co.za/Lists/News%20and%20Publications/Attachments/8830/VBS%20Mutual%20Bank%20-%20The%20Great%20Bank%20Heist.pdf|title=The Great Bank Heist: Investigator's Report to the Prudential Authority|last=Motau|first=Terry|date=10 October 2018|website=South African Reserve Bank|page=135|access-date=11 October 2018}}</ref> into the collapse of [[VBS Mutual Bank]] implicating EFF deputy president Floyd Shivambu's brother media reports came out alleging that Shivambu received R10 million in illicit payments from VBS prior to it being placed under [[Receivership|curatorship]] in March 2018.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-10-11-the-shivambu-brothers-and-the-great-vbs-heist/|title=The Shivambu Brothers and the Great VBS Heist|last=Van Wyk|first=Pauli|date=11 October 2018|work=[[Daily Maverick]]|access-date=11 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-10-12-00-pic-vbs-floyd-and-his-baby-brother|title=PIC, VBS, Floyd and his baby brother|last=Jika|first=Sabelo Skiti, Thanduxolo|date=12 October 2018|work=The M&G Online|access-date=13 October 2018}}</ref> Prior to the publication of the Reserve Bank's report the EFF criticised the Reserve Bank for placing VBS under curatorship and accused it of victimising VBS on racial grounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.effonline.org/single-post/2018/03/11/EFF-STATEMENT-ON-VBS-CURATORSHIP|title=EFF STATEMENT ON VBS CURATORSHIP {{!}} EFF: Economic Freedom Fighters|last=Ndlozi|first=Mbuyiseni Quintin|date=11 March 2018|website=Economic Freedom Fighters|access-date=13 October 2018}}</ref> The EFF stated that it had seen no evidence that Shivambu received the R10 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-10-16-there-are-exchanges-of-money-between-floyd-and-brian-shivambu-but-floyd-did-not-get-money-from-vbs-says-eff/|title=Money was exchanged - but Floyd did not get any from VBS bank, says Malema|access-date=16 October 2018}}</ref> and called for government to recapitalise VBS Mutual Bank<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-calls-for-vbs-to-be-recapitalised-17501083|title=EFF calls for VBS to be recapitalised {{!}} IOL News|last=Zintle|first=Mahlati|date=16 October 2018|work=IOL|access-date=16 October 2018}}</ref> whilst also taking legal action against those mentioned in the Reserve Bank report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dispatchlive.co.za/politics/2018-10-16-malema-vbs-allegations-meant-to-discredit-the-eff/|title=Malema: VBS allegations meant to 'discredit the EFF'|last=Mvumvu|first=Zingisa|date=16 October 2018|work=Dispatch Live|access-date=16 October 2018}}</ref> A follow up investigation by the ''[[Daily Maverick]]'' alleged that the EFF illicitly received R1.8 million of VBS money through a network of proxy companies with the party's leadership (notably Shivambu and Malema) also illicitly receiving money though this network.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-11-21-vbs-bank-heist-effs-family-ties-and-moneyed-connections/|title=VBS bank heist: EFF's family ties and moneyed connections|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|date=21 November 2018|work=Daily Maverick|access-date=21 November 2018}}</ref> After being approached by the ''[[Mail & Guardian]]'' for comment on his personal financial expenses Floyd Shivambu admitted that money from VBS, channeled through his brother, was used to buy his [[Range Rover Sport]] valued at R680,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-09-26-vbss-r680k-paid-for-floyds-wheels/|title=VBS\u2019s R680k paid for Floyd\u2019s wheels|last=Skiti|first=Thanduxolo Jika, Sabelo|website=The M&G Online|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nA follow up investigation by the ''Daily Maverick'' found that R454,000 of VBS money was used to pay for the 2017 EFF birthday celebration.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-05-27-cruising-nicely-on-vbs-effs-parties-lies-and-looted-money/|title=SCORPIO: 'Cruising nicely' on VBS: EFF's Parties, Lies and Looted Money|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref> It also found that a total of R16.1 million was channeled through a Shivambu associated company largely for the benefit of the EFF.<ref name=\":5\" /> An additional investigation traced financial statements from an account that received VBS funds and allegedly controlled by Julius Malema; leading the author of the investigation to estimate that Malema received and directly benefited from R5.3-million illegally taken from VBS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-08-vbs-theft-money-laundering-lifes-little-luxuries-julius-malemas-time-of-spending-dangerously/|title=SCORPIO: VBS Theft, Money Laundering & Life's Little Luxuries: Julius Malema's time of spending dangerously|last=Wyk|first=Pauli Van|date=8 September 2019|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> Additional media reports in October 2019 alleged that the party received R4 million of VBS funds into a slush fund that was channeled to Malema via a company named Santaclara Trading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2190574/over-r4m-in-concerning-payments-made-into-malema-slush-fund-report/|title=Over R4m in 'concerning' payments made into Malema slush fund \u2013 report|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2019-10-13-julius-malemas-slush-fund-exposed/|title=Julius Malema's 'slush fund' exposed|website=TimesLIVE|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/malema-linked-to-another-company-that-had-a-vbs-loan-report-20191013|title=Malema linked to another company that had a VBS loan - report|date=13 October 2019|website=News24|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nA former member of the EFF's leadership accused the party leadership of accepting donations from VBS Mutual Bank prior to its collapse.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMalema later forwarded a [[conspiracy theory]] that the VBS collapse was part of a plot intended to damage the EFF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/watch-vbs-was-meant-to-collapse-and-finish-eff-malema-20190503|title=WATCH: 'VBS was meant to collapse and finish EFF' \u2013 Malema|date=3 May 2019|website=News24|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ideology===\nFeminists and the [[National Union of Metalworkers of South Africa]] have criticised the party's militarism and \"military command structure\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/numsa-wary-of-capitalist-malema-1.1627179#.Usa_NvQW3Y5|title=Numsa wary of \u2018capitalist\u2019 Malema|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103182553/http://www.iol.co.za/news/special-features/numsa-wary-of-capitalist-malema-1.1627179|archive-date=3 January 2014|author=Shanti Aboobaker|work=Sunday Independent|date=29 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thoughtleader.co.za/siphokazimagadla/2013/11/06/eff-and-the-return-of-the-warrior-citizen/|title=EFF & the Return of the Warrior Citizen|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410024005/http://www.thoughtleader.co.za/siphokazimagadla/2013/11/06/eff-and-the-return-of-the-warrior-citizen|archive-date=10 April 2014|author=Siphokazi Magadla|work=Thought Leader|date=2013}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-June 2016 a group calling themselves \"Anonymous Africa\", claiming to be associated with the [[Hacktivism|hacktivist]] group [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]], perpetrated a [[Denial-of-service attack|DDoS attack]] on the EFF's website stating the reason for the attack was the party's \"nationalist socialist rhetoric\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fin24.com/Tech/Companies/exclusive-why-anonymous-hacked-the-sabc-guptas-20160617|title=EXCLUSIVE: Why Anonymous 'hacked' the SABC, Gupta websites|website=Fin24|access-date=19 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617140057/http://www.fin24.com/Tech/Companies/exclusive-why-anonymous-hacked-the-sabc-guptas-20160617|archivedate=17 June 2016}}</ref> The [[South African Communist Party]] also condemns this party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sacp.org.za/main.php?ID=5299|title=SACP supports ANC, condemns Julius Malema`s propagation of war in the strongest possible terms, calls on the police ?to act swiftly in terms of the rule of law|website=www.sacp.org.za|access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Violence and bigotry===\nVusi Khoza, the party's candidate for [[Premier of KwaZulu-Natal]], has a criminal conviction for his involvement in what was believed to be a [[Xenophobia in South Africa|xenophobic attack]] on foreigners at Albert Park, [[Durban]] in December 2009.<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-s-kzn-man-has-criminal-past-1.1663164#.Uy0Y3vmSzY4 EFF\u2019s KZN man has criminal past] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322091149/http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-s-kzn-man-has-criminal-past-1.1663164 |date=22 March 2014 }}, BHEKI MBANJWA, ''The Daily News'', 2014</ref>\n\nFeminists have characterised leading members of the party as [[Misogyny|misogynist]].<ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-04-25-floyd-shivambu-despicable-me/ Floyd Shivambu: Despicable Me] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224084746/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-04-25-floyd-shivambu-despicable-me |date=24 December 2013 }}, Sipho Hlongwane, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-05-remembering-thomas-sankara-the-effs-muse/ Remembering Thomas Sankara, the EFF\u2019s muse] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224094726/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-05-remembering-thomas-sankara-the-effs-muse/ |date=24 December 2013 }}, Rebecca Davis, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2013</ref><ref>[http://feministssa.com/2013/11/28/elections-analysis-the-economic-freedom-fighters-2/ Elections Analysis: The Economic Freedom Fighters] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322090232/http://feministssa.com/2013/11/28/elections-analysis-the-economic-freedom-fighters-2/|date=22 March 2014}}, Sonja Bornman, ''Feminist SA'', 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-25-eff-two-senior-party-officials-accused-of-involvement-in-2008-gang-rape EFF: Two senior party officials accused of involvement in 2008 gang rape] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322091542/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2013-11-25-eff-two-senior-party-officials-accused-of-involvement-in-2008-gang-rape |date=22 March 2014 }}, Rebecca Davis, ''The Daily Maverick'', 2013</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2014, eight members of the EFF were forcibly removed from the legislature after their attire of red overalls carrying the slogan \"asijiki\" (meaning \"we are not turning back\") was found to be inappropriate by presiding officer, Ntombi Mekgwe.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.enca.com/eff-kicked-out-gauteng-legislature |title=EFF kicked out of Gauteng Legislature |publisher=enca.co.za |date=1 July 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> Hundreds of EFF members protested against the ruling on 22 July near the legislature building.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://ewn.co.za/2014/07/22/EFF-storm-Gauteng-Provincial-Legislature |title=EFF storm Gauteng Provincial Legislature |publisher=ewn.co.za |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, during [[FeesMustFall|violent university protests]] characterised by arson and vandalism, EFF Youth leader Omphile Seleke posted instructions for making petrol bombs on social media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://citizen.co.za/news/news-national/1013882/effs-petrol-bomb-recipe-fuels-tuks-fears/|title=EFF\u2019s \u2018petrol bomb recipe\u2019 fuels Tuks fears|last=de Lange|first=Ilse|date=29 February 2016|work=The Citizen|access-date=14 April 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414081535/http://citizen.co.za/news/news-national/1013882/effs-petrol-bomb-recipe-fuels-tuks-fears/|archivedate=14 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, EFF Deputy President [[Floyd Shivambu]] congratulated the party supporters for causing damage to various [[H&M]] stores<ref>{{cite tweet|number=952114009448304640|user=FloydShivambu|title=That @hm nonsense of a clothing store is now facing consequences for its racism.|date=13 January 2018}}</ref> across South Africa due to a picture of a young black child wearing a green hoodie reading, \"Coolest Monkey in the Jungle\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/h-m-the-weeknd-coolest-monkey-in-the-jungle-racist-hoodie/|title=H&M monkey hoodie sparks outrage for \"racist\" image - CBS News|date=8 January 2018|work=[[CBS News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108222136/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/h-m-the-weeknd-coolest-monkey-in-the-jungle-racist-hoodie/|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/01/08/news/companies/hm-apologizes-monkey-hoodie/index.html|title=H&M apologizes for using black child to sell 'coolest monkey' top|date=8 January 2018|work=[[CNN]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108143043/http://money.cnn.com/2018/01/08/news/companies/hm-apologizes-monkey-hoodie/index.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/08/hm-slammed-for-racist-monkey-in-the-jungle-hoodie.html|title=H&M slammed as racist for 'monkey in the jungle' hoodie|date=8 January 2018|work=[[CNBC]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108165628/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/08/hm-slammed-for-racist-monkey-in-the-jungle-hoodie.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1174479/hm-is-apologizing-for-a-product-image-called-out-as-racist/|title=H&M is apologizing for a product image called out as racist - Quartz|date=8 January 2018|work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108235715/https://qz.com/1174479/hm-is-apologizing-for-a-product-image-called-out-as-racist/|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hm-apology-racist-image-website-child-model-backlash-twitter-monkey-jumper-black-a8147641.html|title=H&M apologises following backlash over 'racist' image of child model on website - The Independent|date=8 January 2018|work=[[The Independent]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108173805/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hm-apology-racist-image-website-child-model-backlash-twitter-monkey-jumper-black-a8147641.html|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/h-m-faces-twitter-backlash-racist-hoodie-1072791|title=H&M Faces Twitter Backlash for \"Racist\" Hoodie - Pret-a-Reporter|date=8 January 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108095220/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/h-m-faces-twitter-backlash-racist-hoodie-1072791|archivedate=8 January 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> A [[Vodacom]] store in [[Polokwane]] was damaged and looted by EFF members following a presentation by [[Corruption Watch (South Africa)|Corruption Watch]] at the 2018 Vodacom Awards which included an image depicting EFF leaders Malema and Shivambu as \"abusers of Democracy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/matter-now-closed-eff-vodacom-issue-joint-statement-following-unrest-20181204|title='Matter now closed' - EFF, Vodacom issue joint statement following unrest|last=Seleka|first=Ntwaagae|date=4 December 2018|website=News24|language=en-ZA|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mybroadband.co.za/news/business-telecoms/288272-why-vodacom-met-with-the-eff.html|title=Why Vodacom met with the EFF|last=Staff Writer|date=4 December 2018|website=mybroadband.co.za|language=en-ZA|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, after the SONA address in parliament by the SA President, EFF MP [[Marshall Dlamini]] physically assaulted a member of the presidential security team after a disagreement between EFF MPs and the security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/watch-eff-mp-slaps-man-after-sona-20190208|title=EFF MP slaps man after SONA|last=Gerber|first=Jan|date=8 February 2019|website=www.news24.com|language=en-ZA|access-date=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Actions against journalists and the media====\nJournalist Ranjeni Munusamy lodged an affidavit in December 2018 detailing threatening remarks, intimidation, harassment and personal attacks made by party members, including Malema, towards her and other journalists<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sanef.org.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Part-2.pdf|title=Supporting Affidavit: Navaranjeni Munusamy|last=Munusamy|first=Ranjeni|date=19 December 2018|website=South African National Editors Forum|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref> targeted by the party. The affidavit was supported by the South African National Editors Forum and other notable South African journalists such as [[Max du Preez]], Pauli VanWyk, Adriaan Jurgens Basson, and Barry Bateman.<ref name=\":1\" /> The EFF denied any involvement in attacks on Munusamy and other journalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-12-19-eff-denies-involvement-in-attacks-on-journalists/|title=EFF denies involvement in attacks on journalists|last=Shange|first=Naledi|date=19 December 2018|website=www.timeslive.co.za|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref>{{quote box|quote=''\"We need to ask the [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|IEC]] how such a party can be on the ballot box. It threatens journalists. It encourages its supporters to make rape threats and sexual assault threats. It wants to dictate what I can do as a journalist.\"''<br/>\u2014Karima Brown<ref name=\"KB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|title=Karima Brown vows to lay further complaints as EFF supporters continue to attack|publisher=African News Agency|date=20 March 2016|accessdate=6 March 2019|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306215040/https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|archivedate=6 March 2019}}</ref>|width=25%|align=right}}\nSouth African political journalist Karima Brown was the target of verbal abuse and threats of violence by EFF supporters following the EFF's publication of her personal contact details. This led charges with the police and Equity Court being laid against the party amidst speculation that this instance might be in breach of South Africa's Electoral Code of Conduct. Parties in breach of the code risk having their registration to run in elections being revoked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/karima-brown-vows-to-lay-further-complaints-as-eff-supporters-continue-to-attack-19679315|title=Karima Brown vows to lay further complaints as EFF supporters continue to attack {{!}} IOL News|website=www.iol.co.za|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> Malema stated on the incident that journalists have no privileges whilst accusing Brown of being a state agent and denied that EFF supporters were making threatening remarks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/how-do-you-hold-an-underground-editor-accountable-malema-on-karima-brown-matter-20190306|title='How do you hold an underground editor accountable ' \u2013 Malema on Karima Brown matter|date=6 March 2019|website=News24|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref> The court found in favour of Brown and ruled that the EFF had contravened the South African electoral code by inciting its supports to harass Brown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-06-06-eff-court-losses-mount-as-karima-brown-wins-battle-but-faces-criticism-of-her-own/|title=REPORT: EFF court losses mount as Karima Brown wins battle, but faces criticism of her own|last=Davis|first=Rebecca|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the publication of an article by the amaBhungane Centre for investigative journalism looking into allegations of corruption by the EFF the party controversially announced that it would be banning both amaBhungane and the ''Daily Maverick'' from its public events<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2185034/malema-and-eff-get-r15m-in-kickbacks-in-tshwane-fuel-scandal-report/|title=Malema and EFF get R15m in 'kickbacks' in Tshwane fuel scandal \u2013 report|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-13-this-is-what-panic-looks-like/|title=Editorial: This is What Panic Looks Like|last=Maverick|first=Daily|website=Daily Maverick|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sanef-appalled-by-malemas-call-to-ban-amabhungane-daily-mavericks-scorpio-from-eff-events-20190913|title=Sanef 'appalled' by Malema's call to ban amaBhungane, Daily Maverick's Scorpio from EFF events|date=13 September 2019|website=News24|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref> and announced that they would be treated an enemies of the party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/we-shall-treat-them-as-enemies-malema-bans-amabhungane-and-daily-mavericks-scorpio-from-eff-events-20190912|title=Malema bans amaBhungane and Daily Maverick's Scorpio from EFF events: 'We shall treat them as enemies'|date=12 September 2019|website=News24|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 the EFF was forced to publicly apologies and pay damages following a Gauteng High Court judgment that the party had made and spread false allegations that two journalists, Thandeka Gqubule and Anton Harber, were apartheid era 'StratCom' agents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/eff-retracts-stratcom-agent-allegations-against-gqubule-and-harber-apologises-after-court-order-20200125|title=EFF retracts 'Stratcom agent' allegations against Gqubule and Harber, apologises after court order|date=25 January 2020|website=News24|language=en|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-01-24-eff-ndlozi-have-twenty-four-hours-to-pay-damages-to-journalists/|title=NEWSFLASH: EFF, Ndlozi have twenty-four hours to pay damages to journalists|last=Snijman|first=Lia|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Racial and ethnic prejudice===\nSince its establishment the EFF has made a number of controversial racially or ethnically based statements about a number of South African minority groups. The EFF is widely criticised for inciting and perpetuating racism.<ref>[http://sacsis.org.za/site/article/1899 The EFF and the Question of National Unity] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413154904/http://sacsis.org.za/site/article/1899|date=13 April 2014}}, Duncan, Jane, ''SACSIS WEBSITE'', 29 Jan 2014</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-must-paybackthemoney-for-damage-to-varsities-1995188|title=\u2018EFF must #PayBackTheMoney for damage to varsities\u2019|last=Sain|first=Raahil|date=8 March 2016|access-date=14 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414162203/http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-must-paybackthemoney-for-damage-to-varsities-1995188|archivedate=14 April 2017}}</ref>  \n\n====Anti-Indian prejudice====\nThe South African Minority Rights Equality Movement initiated a court case against Malema for inciting racial sentiment by stating that a \"majority of [[Indian South Africans|Indians]] are racist\" at an EFF Youth Day rally in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/group-to-take-juliusmalema-to-court-for-racist-rant-15526571|title=Group to take #JuliusMalema to court for racist rant {{!}} IOL News|last=Mngoma|first=Nosipho|date=18 June 2018|website=www.iol.co.za|publisher=The Mercury|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe EFF was criticised by the [[South African Council of Churches]], the [[Ahmed Kathrada Foundation]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/no-one-is-going-to-intimidate-us-eff-hits-back-at-clergy-and-ahmed-kathrada-foundation-20181122|title='No one is going to intimidate us' - EFF hits back at clergy and Ahmed Kathrada Foundation|work=News24|access-date=23 November 2018|language=en}}</ref> and the ANC<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/eff-bullies-trying-to-hide-their-own-shenanigans-anc-chief-whip-mthembu-20181123|title='EFF bullies' trying to 'hide their own shenanigans' - ANC chief whip Mthembu|work=News24|access-date=23 November 2018|language=en}}</ref> for comparing Public Enterprises Minister [[Pravin Gordhan]] to a \"dog\" whilst protesting the [[The Judicial Commission of Inquiry into Allegations of State Capture|Zondo Commission]] inquiry into government corruption. The EFF also accused the anti-corruption investigators of being members of an \"[[Indian South Africans|Indian]] [[cabal]]\" commenting on the presence of Indian South African's making up the investigative team.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://city-press.news24.com/Voices/indian-cabal-narrative-is-to-protect-the-looting-project-20181119|title=\u2018Indian cabal\u2019 narrative is to protect the looting project|work=CityPress|access-date=23 November 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-to-gordhan-i-am-not-scared-of-the-indian-cabal|title=Malema to Gordhan: I am not scared of the Indian cabal|website=eNCA|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref> The EFF also accused Gordhan and his daughter of corruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-11-23-00-gordhan-decries-eff-attack-on-daughter/|title=Gordhan decries EFF attack on daughter|last=Smit|first=Sarah|website=The M&G Online|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref> The EFF accusations were proven false<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/Analysis/fact-checked-julius-malemas-charges-against-pravin-gordhan-20181128|title=FACT CHECKED: EFF's charges against Pravin Gordhan|last=Jean le Roux, Kyle Cowan, Pieter du Toit and Adriaan Basson|date=28 November 2018|website=News24|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-11-29-snowbank-bleff-pravin-gordhan-and-the-imaginary-r675m-canadian-account/|title=SnowBank \u2013 BLEFF, Pravin Gordhan and the imaginary R6...|last=Poplak|first=Richard|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref> and Gordhan laid charge of defamation against Malema stating that the EFF's \"determined defence of corruption and the corrupt, using personal attacks, racism and alleged hate speech is not acceptable and must be challenged.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/pravin-gordhan-lays-defamation-charges-against-malema-18267798|title=Pravin Gordhan lays defamation charges against Malema {{!}} IOL News|last=Ndaba|first=Baldwin|date=26 November 2018|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref>  The Equality Court found that the EFF was not guilty of hate speech in its statements relating to Gordhan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/pravin-gordhan-vs-julius-malema-the-high-court-jud|title=Pravin Gordhan vs Julius Malema|last=Sutherland|first=Roland|date=31 October 2019|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-10-31-judge-slates-malemas-juvenile-rant-as-eff-leader-wins-case-against-gordhan/|title=Judge slates Malema's 'juvenile' rant as EFF leader wins case against Gordhan|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref> EFF leadership and its supporters have been criticised for using Gordhan's second name, Jamnadas, as a racial [[Dog-whistle politics|dog whistle]] to highlight to his Indian ethnicity in a [[pejorative]] way and question his status as a South African on social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-01-23-pravin-jamnadas-gordhan-a-case-study-when-your-name-is-weaponised-by-haters-on-twitter/|title=POPULIST DOG WHISTLES: Pravin Jamnadas Gordhan, a case study: When your name is weaponised on Twitter|last=Snijman|first=Lia|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nANC member and government minister [[Jackson Mthembu]] accused the EFF of being racist and having a \"deep-seated hatred\" for Indian South Africans whilst criticizing the party's pursuit of Gordhan whilst participating in a parliamentary debate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-07-17-of-course-you-are-racist-you-are-jackson-mthembu-tells-eff-mps/|title='Of course, you are racist. You are,' Jackson Mthembu tells EFF MPs|last=Makinana|first=Andisiwe|date=17 July 2019|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/cigarettes-corruption-and-racism-why-the-eff-hates-gordhan-according-to-jackson-mthembu-20190718|title=Cigarettes, corruption and racism: Why the EFF hates Gordhan, according to Jackson Mthembu|last=van Diemen|first=Ethan|date=18 July 2019|website=News24|language=en|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Anti-white prejudice====\nMalema stated at a political rally in 2016 that \u201cWe are not calling for the slaughter of [[White South Africans|white people]]\u201a at least for now\". When asked for comment by a news agency, the ANC spokesperson, Zizi Kodwa stated that there will be no comment from the ANC, as \"[h]e [Malema] was addressing his own party supporters.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Malema slammed for comments on whites|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-%E2%80%98slaughter-statement%E2%80%99-rocks-sa|accessdate=30 May 2017|publisher=ENCA|date=8 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417053045/http://www.enca.com/south-africa/malema-%E2%80%98slaughter-statement%E2%80%99-rocks-sa|archivedate=17 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While still the ANCYL leader, Malema was taken to the [[Promotion of Equality and Prevention of Unfair Discrimination Act, 2000|Equality Court]] by [[AfriForum]] for repeatedly singing \u201c[[Dubul' ibhunu|dubul\u2019 ibhunu]]\u201d, which translate as \u201cshoot the [[boer]] [white farmer]\u201d. The ANC supported Malema, though AfriForum and the ANC reached a settlement before the appeal case was due to be argued in the [[Supreme Court of Appeal of South Africa|Supreme Court of Appeal]].{{CN|date=March 2019}}\n\nSouth Africa's [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|Independent Electoral Commission]] disqualified EFF councillor Thabo Mabotja in the 2016 local elections due a [[Twitter|tweet]] made by Mabotja calling for violence against white South Africans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa/iec-disqualifies-eff-councillor-for-racist-tweet|title=IEC disqualifies EFF councillor for racist tweet|date=29 August 2016|work=eNCA|access-date=14 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414082702/http://www.enca.com/south-africa/iec-disqualifies-eff-councillor-for-racist-tweet|archivedate=14 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/elections/news/eff-councillor-candidate-disqualified-after-calling-for-whites-to-be-hacked-and-killed-reports-20160729|title=EFF councillor candidate disqualified after calling for whites to be 'hacked and killed' reports|date=29 July 2016|website=News24|language=en|access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref> The EFF welcomed the commission's decision and renounced Mabotja.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/hes-on-his-own-juju-says-of-mabotja|title='He's on his own' Juju says of Mabotja|website=eNCA|language=en|access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/electoral-court-right-to-give-thabo-mabotja-the-ch|title=Electoral Court right to give Thabo Mabotja the chop|last=|first=|date=|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nJulius Malema, leader of the Economic Freedom Fighters, stated at a political rally in 2018 that \"''Go After A White Man... We Are Cutting The Throat Of Whiteness\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/we-are-cutting-the-throat-of-whiteness-malema-on-plans-to-remove-trollip-20180304|title='We are cutting the throat of whiteness' \u2013 Malema on plans to remove Trollip|work=News24|access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref>'' This led to the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] accusing the EFF's leader, Malema, of [[racism]] and not sharing the more tolerant views of South Africans broadly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/south-africans-dont-share-malemas-racist-views-maimane-13714966|title=South Africans don't share Malema's racist views - Maimane {{!}} IOL News|access-date=11 March 2018}}</ref> The EFF later stated that the reference to the \"throat of whiteness\" was a metaphorical reference to destroying [[white privilege]] and was not referring or advocating harm to white people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2019-03-28-empty-analysis-will-not-deter-the-eff-from-its-core-task-reaching-out-to-the-electorate/|title=OPINIONISTA: Empty analysis will not deter the EFF from its core task \u2014 reaching out to the electorate|last=Thambo|first=Sinawo|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the death of former Zimbabwean President [[Robert Mugabe]] EFF leader Julius Malema tweeted a number of controversial quotes from the late Mugabe that were interpreted as racially prejudiced towards white people.  Most notable was the quote that \"''The only white man you can trust is a dead white man''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-09-17-yep-its-hate-speech-says-sahrc-on-julius-malemas-dead-white-man-tweet/|title=Yep, it's hate speech, says SAHRC on Julius Malema's 'dead white man' tweet|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-09-15-malemas-mugabe-closing-gambit/|title=ANALYSIS: Malema\u2019s Mugabe closing gambit|last=Grootes|first=Stephen|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>  The [[South African Human Rights Commission]] (SAHRC) condemned the quote and stated that they would be taking Malema to court for allegedly spreading [[hate speech]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sahrc.org.za/index.php/sahrc-media/news-2/item/2137-sahrc-to-take-malema-to-court-for-hate-speech|title=SAHRC to take Malema to court for hate speech|last=|first=|date=19 September 2019|website=South African Human Rights Commission|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Namibian Economic Freedom Fighters]]\n*[[Socialist Party of Azania]]\n*[[Workers and Socialist Party]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news|last1=Van Onselen|first1=Gareth|title=Malema steals young communists' thunder|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/opinion/columnists/2013/07/29/malema-steals-young-communists-thunder|accessdate=6 June 2014|work=Business Day|date=29 July 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Q7p7lAID?url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/opinion/columnists/2013/07/29/malema-steals-young-communists-thunder|archivedate=6 June 2014|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite news|last1=Pillay|first1=Verashni|title=EFF: You want land, a loan? You got it|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2014-02-20-eff-you-want-land-a-loan-you-got-it|accessdate=6 June 2014|work=Mail & Guardian|date=21 February 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328111438/http://mg.co.za/article/2014-02-20-eff-you-want-land-a-loan-you-got-it|archivedate=28 March 2014|url-status=live}}\n*Julius Malema (preface), [https://archive.org/details/EconomicFreedomFighters2014ElectionsManifesto ''EFF 2014 Elections Manifesto,''] Economic Freedom Fighters.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.effonline.org Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140918100051/http://effighters.org.za/ Old official website]\n*[http://economicfreedomfighters.org/ Supporter website]\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n{{South Africa political parties}}\n[[Category:Economic Freedom Fighters| ]]\n[[Category:African and Black nationalist organizations in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-capitalist political parties]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics]]\n[[Category:Political parties in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2013]]\n[[Category:National liberation movements in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-white racism in Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-Indian sentiment in Africa]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Left-wing populist parties]]\n", "name_user": "CentreLeftRight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSupport base", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_Freedom_Fighters"}
{"title_page": "Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna", "text_new": "{{short description|2006 film directed by Karan Johar}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna\n| image          = KANK poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Karan Johar]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|    \n* Hiroo Yash Johar\n* Karan Johar\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* Karan Johar\n* [[Shibani Bathija]]\n* [[Niranjan Iyengar]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|       \n* [[Amitabh Bachchan]]\n* [[Shah Rukh Khan]]    \n* [[Abhishek Bachchan]]    \n* [[Rani Mukerji]]                              \n* [[Preity Zinta]]                \n* [[Kirron Kher]]                    \n}}\n| narrator       = Shah Rukh Khan\n| music          = [[Shankar-Ehsaan-Loy]]\n| cinematography = [[Anil Mehta]]\n| editing        = Sanjay Sankla\n| studio         = [[Dharma Productions]]\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|  \n* Dharma Productions         \n* [[Yash Raj Films]] \n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2006|08|11|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 192 minutes<ref>{{cite web|title=''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna'' (12A)|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/kabhi-alvida-naa-kehna-1970-1|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|accessdate=2 February 2013}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = {{ubl|Hindi|English}}\n| budget         = {{INR|50 [[crore]]}}<ref>{{cite web|title=A Rs 150 cr question|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/news/a-rs150cr-question/148355/0|publisher=Financial Express|accessdate=26 December 2010}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}226 crore<ref name=\"BOI gross\">https://www.boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=364</ref><ref name=\"Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna''''' ({{Translation|never say goodbye}}), also abbreviated as '''''KANK,''''' is a 2006 Indian [[Musical film|musical]] [[romantic drama film]], directed by [[Karan Johar]] and produced under the [[Dharma Productions]] banner. The film stars [[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Shah Rukh Khan]], [[Abhishek Bachchan]], [[Rani Mukerji]], [[Preity Zinta]] and [[Kirron Kher]] in prominent roles. Set and mostly taking place in [[New York City]], the film explores themes of adultery. The title was promoted with the tag-line \"''A Love.... That Broke All Relationships''\".  \n\nThe film released worldwide on 11 August 2006. It was a success internationally, especially in the [[United States]]. It became the highest grossing Indian film of all time overseas at the time of its release. The film was screened in over 1,200 cinemas worldwide,<ref name=\"sify.com\">{{cite web|url=http://sify.com/movies/bollywood/fullstory.php?id=14257901|title=sify.com|last=|first=|date=|work=KANK opens in 1,200 screens|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 August 2007}}</ref> grossing a worldwide total of {{INR|2.26 billion}} ({{US$|{{#expr:1200/32.307 round 0}} million|long=no}}).<ref name=\"Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna\">{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/story/20061030-bollywood-hits-overseas-box-office-in-2006-784334-2006-10-30|title=Bollywood hits overseas box office in 2006|last1=Bamzai|first1=Kaveree|date=30 October 2006|work=[[India Today]]|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"currency\"/> It was screened at the [[Tokyo International Film Festival]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}\n\n==Plot==\n{{Plot|section|date=May 2016}}\nMaya ([[Rani Mukerji]]) is an orphan who is to marry her closest childhood friend Rishi Talwar ([[Abhishek Bachchan]]). The two have been raised by Rishi's fun-loving and millionaire father Samarjit a.k.a. Sam ([[Amitabh Bachchan]]). Dev Saran ([[Shah Rukh Khan]]) is a successful soccer player in the United States who after winning one of his biggest games signs a $5 million contract. He lives in [[New York City]] with his wife Rhea ([[Preity Zinta]]), his son Arjun ([[Ahsaas Channa]]) and his mother Kamaljit a.k.a. Kamal ([[Kirron Kher]]). Maya encounters Dev moments before she is to marry Rishi. Although Dev and Maya are strangers, they connect instantly and moments after they part, Dev is hit by a car and permanently injures his leg, as a result, he loses his contract and can no longer play soccer ever again.\n\nFour years later, Dev is now extremely short tempered and bitter because of his inability to play soccer and Rhea's successful career makes him feel inferior to her. Maya too is in a similar situation. She has found that she is [[infertile]] and does not feel any love for Rishi because she believes he is childish. Dev and Maya meet each other and as a result of misunderstanding end up in the hospital. Rhea and Rishi are introduced and they strike a professional relationship. Dev and Maya witness them together and become jealous. They attend Sam's party together and during that the cracks in their respective marriages become visible to each other. Few days later, Dev and Maya witness Sam and Kamal embracing at a flower shop. Sam and Kamal explain that both, having lost their spouses, have decided to help one another through their loneliness by means of friendship. Dev and Maya decide to take a break from the stress of their respective relationships by becoming friends and support each other. In doing so, they find themselves drawn to one another.\n\nDev and Maya arrange a dinner for their respective spouses on the occasion of their wedding anniversaries so as to salvage their respective marriages. During the anniversary, both Dev and Maya have realised they have feelings for one another and not towards their respective partners. After returning home from the dinner, Rhea mentions that she received a promotion to which Dev tells her she is trying to show off to him knowing of his insecurity. Rhea then accuses Dev of being jealous of her professional success and also makes Dev realize his failure in his own life and of being a good husband and a good father to their son. Simultaneously, Rishi expresses his frustration at the lack of affection that Maya has shown towards him and in a burst of anger, finally opens up to his resentment towards Maya's inability to have children. Feeling worthless, Maya arrives at the train station and finds a disheartened Dev standing there before her. After confronting Dev, he finally confesses that he has fallen in love with Maya, and so has she.\n\nSensing the tension in their children's marriages, Sam and Kamal try to talk Rhea and Rishi into trying to reach out to their spouses and when they do, Dev and Maya start feeling guilty because they are happier with each other than with their respective spouses. The two couples attend a ballet, where Dev and Maya try making each other jealous by showing affection to their partners. The next day, they realize that they have been playing with their spouses' feelings and feel guilty but nevertheless give in and make love. \n\nThe next day, Sam invites the Sarans for a dinner party on the occasion of Kamal's birthday. At the party, after a conversation on love, marriage, and fidelity, Dev 'jokingly' confesses that he loves Maya. Sam senses that there was more to Dev's remark than light banter. The next day, Dev and Maya are caught in an embrace outside the train station by Sam and Kamal. Both Sam and Kamal are shocked and upset at the fact that Dev and Maya cheated on their spouses, despite both Rhea and Rishi's attempts to salvage their respective marriages. That night, Sam has a heart attack. On his deathbed, he advises Maya to leave Rishi as she was depriving Rishi and herself of true love and happiness in life. After Sam's death, Dev and Maya decide they must end their relationship and go back to their respective spouses, but first, they must tell them the truth about their extramarital affair, because neither of them would be able to move on with their spouses in the shadow of dishonesty. Shocked and heartbroken, Rhea and Rishi divorce their spouses. Dev and Maya lie to each other and say that they have managed to sort things out with their spouses, believing they'll never meet again. \n\nThree years have passed since their last encounter with each other. Dev and Maya have been living alone and miserably. Rishi visits Maya and says that he has fallen in love again and is remarrying. Rhea, having also been invited, arrives at Rishi's wedding with her boss Jay ([[Arjun Rampal]]), whom she is now dating. Rhea learns that Rishi and Maya are divorced \u2013 Rishi learns the same about Dev and Rhea. Rhea, after confronting Maya tells her that she had left Dev as soon as she came to know of his affair with her. Maya is encouraged by Rishi and Rhea to stop Dev, who is leaving for [[Toronto]] by train. At the train station, Dev sees Maya but tries to avoid her, believing she is still with Rishi. Maya sees him just as the train leaves. Dev, having seen Maya's teary eyes, pulls the emergency brake and arrives back at the station. He makes it back before Maya leaves the train station. They finally find happiness with their true love and decide to start a new life together. In the end, Dev mentions that true love should be the only foundation of a relationship. A flawed foundation would lead to the breakdown of the relationship, which in turn would lead to heartbreak.\n\n==Cast==\n===Main===\n*[[Amitabh Bachchan]] as Samarjit Talwar a.k.a. Sam, Rishi's father\n*[[Shah Rukh Khan]] as Dev Saran\n*[[Abhishek Bachchan]] as Rishi Talwar\n*[[Rani Mukerji]] as Maya Talwar\n*[[Preity Zinta]] as Rhea Saran\n*[[Kirron Kher]] as Kamaljit Saran a.k.a. Kamal, Dev's mother\n\n===Recurring===\n\n*[[Arjun Rampal]] as Jai, Rhea's boss\n*[[Ahsaas Channa]] as Arjun Saran, Dev and Rhea's son \n*Kavi Chopra as a young soccer player\n*[[Kajol]] in a [[item number|special appearance]] in the song Rock 'N' Roll Soniye \n*[[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]] in a [[cameo appearance|special appearance]] as DJ in the song Where's The Party Tonight? \n*[[Riteish Deshmukh]] as Mr. Narang, Maya's boss (Deleted Scene)\n*[[Karan Johar]] as a train passenger in a [[cameo appearance]]\n*[[Ayan Mukerji]] in a [[cameo appearance]] in the song Tumhi Dekho Naa\n\n==Production==\n''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna'' was directed and written by [[Karan Johar]] who collaborated with [[Shibani Bathija]] to write the screenplay, and [[Niranjan Iyengar]] produced the dialogue. Produced by [[Dharma Productions]], the soundtrack was performed by the musical trio, [[Shankar-Ehsaan-Loy]] with lyrics written by [[Javed Akhtar]]. [[Farah Khan]] was brought in to organize the choreographical aspects of the film, with costume designer [[Manish Malhotra]], production designer [[Sharmishta Roy]] and [[MAC (cosmetics)|MAC]] cosmetics all playing a major role in production.\n\n[[Kajol]] was initially offered the role of Maya Talwar. When she refused, due to her prior commitments with [[Yash Raj Films]]'s ''[[Fanaa (film)|Fanaa]]'', the role was passed on to her cousin [[Rani Mukerji]], who was supposed to play [[Preity Zinta]]'s part. However, Kajol made a guest appearance in the song \"''Rock 'N' Roll Soniye''\".\n\n[[Riteish Deshmukh]] also had a guest appearance, but his scene was cut during the editing process.\n\n''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna'' is set in [[New York City]], while many of the scenes were filmed in [[East Hartford]] and [[New Haven]] in [[Connecticut]]. The soccer game scene was filmed at [[Rentschler Field (stadium)|Rentschler Field]], the home of the [[UConn Huskies football team]]. In several scenes, a light '''UConn''<nowiki/>' can be seen on the field. The majority of the [[Grand Central Terminal|Grand Central Station]] scenes were filmed at New Haven's [[Union Station (New Haven)|Union Station]] and [[Philadelphia]]'s [[30th Street Station]].\n\nIn an interview, Karan Johar stated that the filming for the song \"Tumhi Dekho Naa\" was done at multiple locations and ended up being extremely time-consuming. The \"blue section\" of the song was shot at [[Columbia University]] in [[Upper West Side]], the \"yellow section\" was shot at [[Wall Street]] in [[Lower Manhattan]], the \"orange section\" at [[Bear Mountain State Park|Bear Mountain]], the \"red section\" at the [[Landmarks of Hoboken, New Jersey#Pier A|Pier A Park]] in [[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken]], and the \"green section\" at the Union Station in New Haven. The red section was initially designed to take place in the rain. However, due to the low temperatures, the raindrops produced by the rain machines started freezing in mid-air. This posed a risk of physical harm to the actors. Consequently, the filmmakers decided to do away with the rain. However, they still wanted to make use of the 200 red umbrellas they had purchased. Eventually, they decided to shoot the red section on a sunny day where the actors used the umbrellas to block out the sun. The shooting for the green section also ran into problems. Two hundred extras were hired for the section but only fifteen showed up. Consequently, crew members present on the set wore the green costumes to take their place. [[Ayan Mukerji]] who was an Assistant Director of the film can be seen in a green sweater carrying a box in one of the frames.\n\nThe movie was filmed over a 90-day shooting period in the USA but a few scenes were shot on four large sets in [[Mumbai]] studios.<ref>[http://www3.dharma-production.com/KANK/launch.html Official website of Dharma Productions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071126060438/http://www3.dharma-production.com/KANK/launch.html |date=26 November 2007 }}, Retrieved 31 January 2008</ref>\n\nMukerji suffered from a severe skin allergy during the filming in the US. \n\nLike previous [[Karan Johar]] movies (''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'', ''[[Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...]]'' and ''[[Kal Ho Naa Ho]])'', ''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna'' has a four-word title that starts with a \"''K''\".\n\n==Music==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna\n| type         = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist       = [[Shankar-Ehsaan-Loy]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 12 June 2006 {{small|([[United Kingdom|UK]])}}<br/>16 June 2006 {{small|([[India]])}}\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = 42:07\n| label        = [[Sony BMG]]\n| producer     = [[Shankar-Ehsaan-Loy]]\n| prev_title   = [[Dil Jo Bhi Kahey...]]\n| prev_year    = 2005\n| next_title   = [[Don - The Chase Begins Again]]\n| next_year    = 2006\n}}\n\nThe music and background score of ''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna'' was composed by [[Shankar-Ehsaan-Loy]], while the lyrics were penned by [[Javed Akhtar]]. This is the second time that lyricist Javed Akhtar and the composers Shankar-Ehsaan-Loy have teamed up for a Dharma production. The trio also replaces Johar's usual collaborators [[Jatin\u2013Lalit]], who had composed for his previous films. The audio rights were acquired by [[Sony Music India]], under [[Sony BMG]], teaming up with [[Karan Johar]], for the third time after ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'' (1998) and ''[[Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...|Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...]]'' (2001).\n\nThe title song \"Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna\" rendered by [[Sonu Nigam]] and [[Alka Yagnik]] is a [[tear jerker|tearjerker]]. \"[[Mitwa]]\", an evocative [[sufi rock]] ballad, marked the introduction of Pakistani singer [[Shafqat Amanat Ali]] into the [[Bollywood]] scene. \"Where's The Party Tonight?\" by Shaan, [[Vasundhara Das]], [[Loy Mendonsa|Loy]] and Shankar Mahadevan is the [[Club music|club song]] picturized on Abhishek and Preity. Then follows \"Tumhi Dekho Naa\", a soft and romantic ballad, which again is sung by the Sonu Nigam - Alka Yagnik duo is picturized on Shah Rukh and Rani. \"Rock 'N' Roll Soniye\", picturized on Amitabh, Abhishek and Preity is a [[Rock 'N' Roll|60's Rock 'N' Roll]] track, sung by [[Shankar Mahadevan]], [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] and [[Mahalakshmi Iyer]]. \"Farewell Trance\" is the [[Trance music|trance]] version of the title track, which is a rarity in Bollywood. The album also has a remix - \"Mitwa - Revisted\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/karan-johar-on-kank-s-music-news-bollywood-kkfvjMicbgc.html |title=Karan Johar on KANK's Music |publisher=Sify.com |date=2006-06-14 |accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref> The soundtrack ends with a sad version of the title track, \"Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna - Sad Version\" which speaks of destiny, meeting again in life and never saying goodbye. The trio took care to not make the album sound repetitive, especially since the overall genre of the soundtrack is similar to that of their previous chartbuster ''[[Kal Ho Naa Ho]]'' (2003).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/aug/10sel.htm|title='Karan Johar likes his English hooks'|date=|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref>\n\nThe music of ''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna'' was launched in the [[United Kingdom]] on 12 June 2006 and was officially released in [[India]] on 16 June 2006 along with a grand music launch at the [[IIFA Awards]] function in [[Dubai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2006/06/09/7255/index.html |title='Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna' music launch at I.I.F.A |publisher=Bollywoodhungama.com |date=2006-06-09 |accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Track listing ===\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| title1 = Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna\n| extra1 = [[Sonu Nigam]], [[Alka Yagnik]]\n| length1 = 08:07\n| title2 = [[Mitwa]]\n| extra2 = [[Shafqat Amanat Ali]], [[Shankar Mahadevan]], [[Caralisa Monteiro]]\n| length2 = 06:24\n| title6 = Rock 'N' Roll Soniye\n| extra6 = [[Mahalakshmi Iyer]], Shankar Mahadevan, [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]]\n| length6 = 05:44\n| title5 = Tumhi Dekho Naa\n| extra5 = Sonu Nigam, [[Alka Yagnik]]\n| length5 = 05:50\n| title3 = Where's The Party Tonight?\n| extra3 = [[Vasundhara Das]], Shaan, [[Joi Barua]]\n| length3 = 06:21\n| title4 = Mitwa\n| note4 = Revisited\n| extra4 = Shafqat Amanat Ali, Shankar Mahadevan, Caralisa Monteiro\n| length4 = 05:35\n| title7 = Farewell Trance\n| extra7 = Caralisa Monteiro, [[Shweta Pandit]]\n| length7 = 05:47\n| title8 = Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna\n| note8 = Sad Version\n| extra8 = Sonu Nigam, Alka Yagnik\n| length8 = 02:06\n| total_length = 42:07\n| all_writing = \n| all_lyrics = [[Javed Akhtar]]\n}}\n\n=== Critical reception ===\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=bh>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/features/2006/06/13/1289/index.html |title=\"We were quite disheartened on Sunday when some websites in London said that ''KANK'' is the worst album they have ever heard. And they wrote this without even listening to the album\" \u2013 Ehsaan Noorani |publisher=Bollywoodhungama.com |date=2006-06-15 |accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[Rediff.com]]\n| rev2Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=rediff>{{cite web|url=http://in.rediff.com/movies/2006/jun/16kank.htm |title=Great tunes from KANK - Rediff.com movies |publisher=In.rediff.com |date=2006-06-16 |accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''Planet Bollywood''\n| rev3Score = {{rating|9.5|10}}\n| rev4 = ''Bollyvista''\n| rev4Score = {{rating|9.5|10}}\n| rev1score = \n}}Joginder Tuteja of ''[[Bollywood Hungama]]'' dismissed those initial negative reaction, saying \"Much before the official release of the music album of ''KANK'', rumour brigade has been having a field day in pulling down the album. Well, that's not something new as with every biggie comes its share of detractors. But on hearing the songs for yourself, you realize that is it NOTHING, but a rumour! The album is yet another fine product from the team that delivers the kind of path-breaking music expected from it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/musicreview/12514/index.html|title=Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna : Music Review by Joginder Tuteja|date=|publisher=Bollywoodhungama.com|accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref> Sukanya Verma of [[Rediff]] called the album \"a treat for the melody-starved.\"<ref name=\"rediff22\">{{cite web|url=http://in.rediff.com/movies/2006/jun/16kank.htm|title=Great tunes from KANK - Rediff.com movies|last=|first=|date=2006-06-21|website=|publisher=In.rediff.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref>\n\nThe album opened at #1 and retained the top position in the music charts for ten straight weeks, despite facing tough competition from musical hits like ''[[Fanaa (film)|Fanaa]]'', ''[[Krrish]]'' and ''[[Gangster (2006 film)|Gangster]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/features/2006/09/01/1504/index.html|title=Top Ten albums of the week|date=2006-09-01|publisher=Bollywoodhungama.com|accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref> According to the figures from ''BoxOffice India'', the album sold over 1,900,000 copies in India<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=286&catName=MjAwMC0yMDA5|title=Internet Archive Wayback Machine|date=2009-01-22|publisher=Web.archive.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122120910/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=286&catName=MjAwMC0yMDA5|archivedate=22 January 2009|accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref> making it the second best selling album of the year, marginally behind ''[[Dhoom 2]]''.\n\n==Release==\n''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna'', with a multi-star cast, premiered on 11 August 2006 and was screened in over 1,200 cinemas worldwide.<ref name=\"sify.com\"/>\n\nAccording to the [[Internet Movie Database]] (IMDb), the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] (MPAA) originally gave the film an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|R]] rating because of language and some sexual content. It was re-rated [[PG-13]] on appeal.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna'' was one of India's possible nominations for the [[79th Academy Awards|2007]] [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Film]], with films such as ''[[Rang De Basanti]]'', ''[[Krrish]]'', ''[[Omkara (2006 film)|Omkara]]'' and ''[[Lage Raho Munna Bhai]]'' also in the running. However, the country ultimately chose ''Rang De Basanti'' as its pick.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\nCritic [[Taran Adarsh]] described the subject matter as a delicate one which could have easily been disastrous and praised the way in which director Karan Johar boldly constructed the film, citing it as his finest work to date.<ref name=\"Adarsh\">{{cite web|title=Indiafm.com| work=Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna, by Taran Arash|url=http://www.indiafm.com/movies/review/12514/index.html|accessdate=31 January 2008}}</ref> Adarsh approved in particular of the script and the devices the director incorporated to contrast emotions between scenes, remarking that, \"the screenplay balances the two extremes; light moments and dollops of emotions with amazing ease\".<ref name=Adarsh/> The individual cast performances were also praised by Adarsh, who commented on the effectiveness of the casting and the interaction of the actors.<ref name=\"Adarsh\"/>\n\n[[Rajeev Masand]] gave the film 4 out of 5 stars praising the screenplay and Johar's direction, saying \"Few writers have such solid control over their screenplay as Karan Johar does. Few understand the intricacies of narrative as well as he does. Johar goes from highs to lows, from plateaus to peaks with the ease of a pro. He knows exactly how to turn a seemingly ordinary scene into something special with just that one line of dialogue, or that hint of background music.\"<ref>http://ibnlive.in.com/news/masands-verdict--kabhi-alvida-naa-kehna/18315-8.html</ref>\n\nDerek Elley of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' also praised the diversity of emotions displayed by the cast, remarking that, \"Scripter Shibani Bathija never lets her characters inhabit a secure emotional place for very long, and impediments to happiness come from their own weaknesses rather than social constraints or plot-generated misunderstandings\".<ref name=\"Elley\">{{cite web|url=https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117931316.html?categoryid=31&cs=1|title=Variety|last=|first=|date=30 August 2006|work=Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna, by Derek Elley|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230002241/https://variety.com/review/VE1117931316.html?categoryid=31&cs=1|archivedate=30 December 2006|accessdate=31 January 2008}}</ref> Elley noted Amitabh Bachchan's performance as an ageing lothario and praised Preity Zinta as \"stepping far beyond her makeup\".<ref name=\"Elley\"/>\n\nRaja Sen of ''[[rediff.com]]'' was particularly critical of the film, also expressing dissatisfaction with its length. He remarked, \"I feel older. A showing of Karan Johar's mammoth 22-reel ''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna'' has left me unbelievably exhausted. I walked out of the hall feeling my cheeks for stubble, wondering if my clothes are suddenly dated and my hair's turned grey. I've lost a sizeable chunk of my life, and you will too\".<ref name=\"Sen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/aug/11kank.htm|title=Rediff.com|last=|first=|date=25 August 2006|work=KANK is an exhausting film by Raja Sen|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=30 January 2008}}</ref> Unlike other critics, he identified flaws in the script and criticized the strength of characters saying \"The characters are cardboard, the setting is glitzy, the songs are tiresome, and the story oscillates between high melodrama and slapstick hilarity, going nowhere. Rarely has a weak script relied so completely on pretty people with big names to carry every line through\".<ref name=\"Sen\"/>\n\nIn the United States, the film received a number of positive reviews.\n\nCritics such as [[Neil Genzlinger]] of the ''[[New York Times]]'' emphasized the larger-than-life nature of the film, remarking that, \"It is full of big Bollywood stars and out-sized everything: the rainstorms are a little rainier than real life; the wind machines are cranked up an extra notch; the close-ups get closer and linger longer than usual; the coincidences that drive the plot are a little more numerous and unlikely than normal screenwriting allows\".<ref name=\"Genzlinger\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/12/movies/12kabh.html?ex=1313035200&en=44270ed672924be2&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss|title=New York Times|last=Genzlinger|first=Neil|date=26 August 2006|work=Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna, a Bollywood Divorce Tale by Neil Genzlinger|accessdate=30 January 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> He praised the humor in the script and the director's comic timing in certain scenes such as the children's soccer match, the bed store, and at the ballet show.<ref name=\"Genzlinger\"/>\n\n===Box office===\n''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna'' saw a record opening at many cities in India and generated {{INR|600 million}} in the first week itself, although it is currently Johar's lowest-grossing film according to net collections, even if unadjusted for inflation. It emerged the highest grosser worldwide for an Indian film, surpassing ''[[Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham|Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...]]'''s five-year-old record.<ref name=\"sify.com\"/> With a total overseas gross of {{US$|10.77 million|long=no}}, the film was the third [[List of Bollywood highest-grossing films in overseas markets|highest overseas grosser]] as of 2013.<ref>{{cite web| title=boxofficeindia.com| work=KANK| url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=308&catName=TGlmZXRpbWU=| accessdate=10 August 2007| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006052405/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=308&catName=TGlmZXRpbWU%3D| archivedate=6 October 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIt opened strongly in the United States and the United Kingdom with first weekend grosses of $1.3 million in the U.S and $1.4 million (\u00a3750,000) in the UK<ref>{{cite web|title=boxofficeindia.com| work=KANK declared a hit in India| url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/2006.htm |accessdate=10 August 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070808100831/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/2006.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 8 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn total ''Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna'' collected US$3,275,444 in the United States<ref>{{cite web|title=boxofficemojo.com| work=Box office results in USA|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=kabhialvidanaakehna.htm|accessdate=10 August 2007}}</ref> while in UK it netted over \u00a35,079,688.00. In the US, one factor contributing to its success was the fact it debuted in 64 theatres, unusually high for a Bollywood film in cities with lower Indian populations such as [[Miami]], [[Tampa]], and [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] as well.{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}}\n\nThe film's total worldwide gross was between {{INR}}2.26 billion ({{US$|{{#expr:1200/32.307 round 0}} million|long=no}}).<ref name=\"BOI gross\" /><ref name=\"currency\">{{cite web |title=Official exchange rate (LCU per US$, period average) |url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/PA.NUS.FCRF?end=2007&locations=IN&start=2006 |website=[[World Bank]] |year=2006 |accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna\" />\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%;\" ;\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"|Annual Central European Bollywood Awards (India)\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align center;\"\n! style=\"width:30%;\"| Category\n! style=\"width:35%;\"| Recipients\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Results\n|- style=\"border-top:2px solid gray;\"\n|Best Actor\n|[[Shah Rukh Khan]]\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{won}}\n|-\n|Best Actress\n|[[Rani Mukerji]]\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%;\" ;\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"|Annual Indian Film Awards\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align center;\"\n! style=\"width:30%;\"| Category\n! style=\"width:35%;\"| Recipients\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Results\n|- style=\"border-top:2px solid gray;\"\n|Best Supporting Actress\n|[[Preity Zinta]]\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{won}}\n|-\n|Best Supporting Actor\n|[[Abhishek Bachchan]]\n|-\n|Best Lyricist\n|[[Javed Akhtar]] for \"[[Mitwa]]\"\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%;\" ;\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"12\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"|[[Filmfare Awards]]\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align center;\"\n! style=\"width:30%;\"| Category\n! style=\"width:35%;\"| Recipients\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Results\n|- style=\"border-top:2px solid gray;\"\n|[[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n|Abhishek Bachchan\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{won}}\n|-\n|[[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|[[Karan Johar]]\n|rowspan=\"11\" {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n|Karan Johar\n|-\n|[[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n|Shah Rukh Khan\n|-\n|[[Filmfare Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n|Rani Mukerji\n|-\n|[[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n|[[Amitabh Bachchan]]\n|-\n|[[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n|Preity Zinta\n|-\n|Best Supporting Actress\n|[[Kirron Kher]]\n|-\n|[[Filmfare Award for Best Music Director|Best Music Director]]\n|[[Shankar-Ehsaan-Loy]]\n|-\n|[[Filmfare Award for Best Lyrics|Best Lyrics]]\n|Javed Akhtar for \"Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna\"\n|-\n|[[Filmfare Award for Best Male Playback Singer|Best Male Playback Singer]]\n|[[Sonu Nigam]] for \"Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna\"\n|-\n|[[Filmfare Award for Best Female Playback Singer|Best Female Playback Singer]]\n|[[Alka Yagnik]] for \"Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna\"\n\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%;\" ;\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! 